aget, 1st Earl of Uxbridge (second creation)|earl of Uxbridge]] and partly by the family of Llysdulas; for a time both parties entrusted the management to Williams alone. He was closely associated with the Uxbridge family and helped several sons get elected to Parliament. In 1790, probably with help from the earl of Uxbridge, he was elected for [[Great Marlow (UK Parliament constituency)|Great Marlow]], and held the seat till his death on 30 November 1802. (The seat was won in 1820 by his grandson and retained until 1868).  Four generations from Thomas Williams of Llanidan to his great-grandson Lt-General Owen Lewis Cope Peers Williams (d. 1904) held the Great Marlow seat with intervals, from 1790 until 1885.\n\nHis son [[Owen Williams (MP)|Owen Williams]] (1764\u20131832), also MP for [[Great Marlow (UK Parliament constituency)|Great Marlow]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43195 |title=Parishes: Bisham |author=P.H. Ditchfield and William Page (eds) |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |year=1923 |work=A History of the County of Berkshire: Volume 3 |accessdate=24 February 2008}}.</ref> married [http://www.geneall.net/U/per_page.php?id=634980 Margaret Hughes], and had a son Thomas Peers Williams (the subject of this article).  Three of the younger Thomas's daughters were married to members of the House of Lords, two others to sons of lords.\n\nThe elder Thomas's descendants gradually released their hold on the copper industry; they are now remembered as owners of the Craig-y-don estate and the founders of banks. Several were Members of Parliament.\n\n==Marriage and children==\n[[File:Bronwen Peers-Williams and her sisters.JPG|thumb|250px|Madge, Nina and Blanche Peers-Williams]]\nPeers Williams married 27 August 1835 Emily Bacon (d. 24 November 1876), daughter of [[Anthony Bushby Bacon]] of [[Benham Park]] and later of [[Elcot Park Hotel|Elcot Park]], both in [[Berkshire]]<ref name=EET>{{cite book |last= [[Emma Elizabeth Thoyts|Thoyts]] |first= Emma Elizabeth |title= History of the Royal Berkshire Militia |publisher= J. Hawkes |year= 1897 |url=https://archive.org/details/historyroyalber00thoygoog}}</ref>\n\nLt Col Thomas Peers Williams had at least two sons and several daughters who married into the peerage.\n* Lieutenant General<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43195 |title=Parishes: Bisham |author=P.H. Ditchfield and William Page (eds) |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |year=1923 |work=A History of the County of Berkshire: Volume 3 |accessdate=26 August 2012}}</ref>'''[[Owen Lewis Cope Williams]]''' (12 July 1836 Berkeley Square, London - 2 October 1904 Temple House, Bisham) of Craig-y-Don, Llandegfan, Anglesey (which he sold 1884),<ref>[http://www.greatorme.org.uk/craigydon.html]</ref> and Temple House, Bisham, Berkshire, sometime MP for [[Great Marlow]] 1880-1885. He married 1stly 18 August 1862 Fanny Florence Caulfeild (1838 Florence, Italy - 28 July 1876 Berwick House, Stable Yard, St. James's, London), younger daughter of St.George Francis Caulfeild and yr sister of [[Henry Lowther, 3rd Earl of Lonsdale|Emily, Countess of Lonsdale]] by whom he had issue 1 son, Owen '''Gwynedd''' St. George Williams (1865-killed in 1903 Matabele War).  He married 2ndly 1882 Nina Mary Adelaide Sinclair, daughter of Sir John George Tollemache Sinclair, Bt.  Owen Williams had two sons who predeceased him, one of whom, Gwynedd, was killed in the Matabele War.<ref name=\"Montgomerie\">Montgomerie</ref><ref>[http://www.caulfeild.co.uk/ged/individual.php?pid=I0161&ged=Caulfeild.GED]</ref>\n* '''Hwfa Williams'''  ([[floruit|fl.]] 1914),<ref>[http://www.historygallery.com/prints/vanityfair/sandownpark/sandownpark.htm Hwfa Williams]</ref> who with his wife was prominent in the court of Edward VII. He was manager of the racing course Sandown Park, created about 120 years ago. His wife Florence Farquharson (affectionally remembered by [[Felix Yusupov]])<ref>Felix Yusupov. ''Lost Splendour'' [Chapter Fifteen]</ref> was a notable society hostess, and known as the best-dressed woman in England.  They were both still alive in 1913, having married in 1881.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9A04E1DF133BE633A25755C2A9679C946296D6CF Mrs Hwfa Williams's charity ball]</ref> In 1914, Williams was shot and badly wounded in the Pall Mall by an overworked telegraph clerk.<ref>See Barbara Tuchman, ''The Guns of August'', p. 167.</ref>  His wife later authored ''It Was Such Good Fun'', an account of Edwardian high society life.\n[[File:Herb Korybut.jpg|thumb|200px|Woroniecki coat of arms]]\n* '''Gwenfra Williams''' - she had a daughter Julie who became Princess Korybut-Woroniecki by her marriage to Prince Krzysztof Korybut-Woroniecki.<ref>Montgomerie, Page 75</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/01/07/100579204.pdf \"NEW LONDON HOME FOR MRS. AVA ASTOR; Fine Residence to be Ready for the Early Opening of the Social Season\"]. ''The New York Times'' 27 January 1912, Section: PARTS 111 AND 1V CABLE NEWS WIRELESS AND SPORTING SECTIONS, Page C2, 1363 words. According to the article, their house in [[Ovington Square]] narrowly escaped being burnt down by fire on Boxing Day, and Mr Williams was ill with influenza. The daughter is mentioned as in America with Mrs Bridget Guinness (nee Montgomerie), her cousin.</ref> They had two children. Jan Korybut-Woroniecki - a London restaurateur, and Marysia Korybut-Woroniecka - a Fashion Business executive based in New York.\n* '''Margaret''' Elizabeth Williams (24 November 1838 - 10 August 1909), married 12 August 1866 as his 2nd wife [[Williams-Bulkeley Baronets|Sir Richard Mostyn Lewis Williams-Bulkeley, 11th Baronet]] (20 May 1833 \u2013 28 January 1884) of [[Baron Hill, Anglesey]]; son of Sir Richard Williams-Bulkeley, 10th Baronet (1801\u20131875).  Sir Richard and Madge Williams-Bulkeley had one daughter, Bridget Henrietta Frances, who married Benjamin Seymour Guinness, of Anglesey; they were parents of [[Thomas \"Loel\" Guinness]].  \n* '''Emily Gwendoline Williams'''  (July 1839-9 November 1932), known as Gwen, wife since 1863 of the [[Earl Cowley|2nd Earl Cowley]]; she lived at Bodwen on the Isle of Wight overlooking Wotton Creek. She died at the age of 92 and had a daughter, Eva.\n[[File:Edith Peers Williams, later Countess of Aylesford.JPG|thumb|upright|Edith Peers-Williams, later Countess of Aylesford]]\n* '''Edith Peers-William''' (died 23 June 1897), who married 1871 [[Earl of Aylesford|Heneage Finch, 7th Earl of Aylesford]] (1849\u20131885), and had two daughters. The Earl and his wife separated in 1877, when she became involved with the married [[George Charles Spencer-Churchill, 8th Duke of Marlborough|Marquess of Blandford]], the future 8th Duke of Marlborough. In 1881, she bore a son, later known as Guy Bertrand (b. 4 November 1881 Paris, christened 1883). This son was baptized only in June 1883 St Mary-le-Strand, London as a son of the 7th Earl.  His claims to the peerage (made by his mother Edith) were  denied by the House of Lords in July 1885.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1885/07/03/103026617.pdf]</ref><ref>''\"[Aylesford's] paternity was however subsequently disallowed by the House of Lords: see 'The Complete Peerage', vol. 1 p.&nbsp;367 fn. a; in July 1885, in the case of the Earldom of Aylesford as against the legitimacy of a child b. 4 Nov 1881 in wedlock, of parties who were residing respectively in Chapel Place (Oxford Str.) and in Portugal Str. (South Audley Str.) Midx., in the months of Jan., Feb., Mar., and Apr. previous to the BIRTH: see 'The Complete Peerage', vol. 1 p.&nbsp;367 fn. b.\"''].</ref> Edith, Countess of Aylesford never married Lord Blandford who went on to marry an American heiress.<ref>[http://thehistorychicks.com/?page_id=1200 The Angry Prince, or, Why You Shouldn\u2019t Blackmail Your Future Sovereign]. Retrieved 27 November 2012.</ref>  The Earl of Aylesford attempted to divorce his wife, but was himself found guilty of adultery, and thus the decree nisi was cancelled.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3153963 \"Divorce In High Life\"] ''Northern Territory Times and Gazette'' (Darwin, NT, Australia : 1873 - 1927  Saturday 12 May 1883, p. 3</ref>\n* '''Blanche''' Mary Williams (1844-1 July 1914)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/Roxburghe1707.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-10-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120519050317/http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/Roxburghe1707.htm |archivedate=19 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> married 15 January 1866  Lt Col Lord Charles John Innes-Ker (b. 31 Dec 1842; d. 19 Nov 1919), 2nd son of the 6th Duke of Roxburghe, and had issue\n* Nina Janet '''Bronwen''' Williams (died 1939), known as Bronwen, married 1870 Hon [[Seton Montolieu Montgomerie]] (15 May 1846 \u2013 26 Nov 1883) a younger son of the [[Archibald Montgomerie, 13th Earl of Eglinton|13th Earl of Eglinton & Winton]], and had issue three daughters; Alswen, Viva and May.\n[[File:Evelyn Peers Williams, wife of the 3rd Duke of Wellington.JPG|thumb|Evelyn, Duchess of Wellington.]]\n* {{anchor|Evelyn}}<!-- [[Evelyn Katrine Gwenfra Williams]] and [[Evelyn, Duchess of Wellington]] redirect here-->'''Evelyn Katrine Gwenfra Williams''' (1855-11 March 1939 West Green House, Hartley Wintney, Hants), who married firstly 7 March 1882 the [[Henry Wellesley, 3rd Duke of Wellington|3rd Duke of Wellington]] (1846\u20131900) in 1882; they had no issue. She remarried in 1904 a Wellesley cousin Col. Hon. Frederick Arthur Wellesley (1844\u20131931), a son of the [[Earl Cowley|1st Earl Cowley]], as his third wife. Frederick Wellesley had previously married 1873 (div. 1882)  Emma Loftus, granddaughter of the [[Marquess of Ely|2nd Marquess of Ely]], and then married 1884 (div 1897) [[Kate Vaughan|Catherine Candelon]]. He was also her brother-in-law, as the younger brother of the 2nd Earl Cowley, husband of her eldest sister.\n\n==Landownership==\nThe grandson Thomas Peers Williams was a considerable landowner in [[Wales]]\n,<ref>[http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/wal/GreatLandowners.htmla considerable landowner in Wales]</ref> as recorded with {{convert|7010|acre|km2}} in 1873.  He owned estates in Anglesey and Berkshire, and elsewhere.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n* [https://biography.wales/article/s-WILL-THO-1737 Biography of Thomas Williams], the grandfather, from the National Library of Wales. Accessed 24 February 2008.\n* Viva Seton Montgomerie (1954). ''My Scrapbook of Memories''. Original draft. Eglinton Archive.\n* Leigh Rayment. [http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/fathercommons.htm Fathers of the House of Commons]. Last updated 6 December 2006, and accessed 24 February 2008.\n* Leigh Rayment. [http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Gcommons2.htm Members of Parliament for Great Marlow]. Last updated 6 April 2007, and accessed 24 February 2008.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | colonel-thomas-williams | Thomas Peers Williams }}\n*[http://histfam.familysearch.org/getperson.php?personID=I94788&tree=Welsh Ancestry and descendants of Thomas Peers Williams]. Retrieved 27 November 2012.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Marlow (UK Parliament constituency)|Marlow]]\n | years  = 1820\u20131868\n | before = [[Pascoe Grenfell]]\n | before2 = [[Owen Williams (MP)|Owen Williams]]\n | after  = [[Thomas Owen Wethered]]\n | with   = [[Owen Williams (MP)|Owen Williams]] 1820\u20131832\n | with2  = [[William Robert Clayton]] 1832\u20131842\n | with3  = [[Renn Hampden (died 1852)|Renn Hampden]] 1842\u20131847\n | with4  = [[Brownlow William Knox]] 1847\u20131868\n}}\n{{S-hon}}\n{{Succession box | before=[[Henry Lowther (politician)|Henry Lowther]] | title=[[Father of the House]] | after=[[Henry Lowry-Corry (1803\u20131873)|Henry Lowry-Corry]] | years=1867\u20131868}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Fathers of the House}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Thomas Peers}}\n[[Category:1795 births]]\n[[Category:1875 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1820\u20131826]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1826\u20131830]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1830\u20131831]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1831\u20131832]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1832\u20131835]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1835\u20131837]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1837\u20131841]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1841\u20131847]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1847\u20131852]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1852\u20131857]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1857\u20131859]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1859\u20131865]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1865\u20131868]]\n[[Category:British Militia officers]]\n[[Category:People from Anglesey]]\n[[Category:People from Bisham]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarriage and children:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1880-1885 \u2192 1880\u20131885", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Peers_Williams"}
{"title_page": "John Wells (MP for Maidstone)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n'''John Wells''' (1761 \u2013 22 November 1848)<ref name=\"rayment\">{{Rayment-hc|m|1|date=March 2012}}</ref> was an English [[Tory (British political party)|Tory]]<ref name=\"stooks-smith\">{{cite book\n |last=Stooks Smith\n |first=Henry.\n |editor=[[F. W. S. Craig|Craig, F. W. S.]]\n |title=[[The Parliaments of England]]\n |origyear=1844-1850\n |edition=2nd\n |year=1973\n |publisher=Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn=0-900178-13-2\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/parliamentsofeng0000smit/page/168 168]\n }}</ref> politician  who sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1820 to 1830.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', under 'Wells, William (1729\u20131805)'.</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Malling, Kent]] the second son of William Wells, of [[Bickley]] Hall, Bromley in Kent and [[Holme, Cambridgeshire|Holme Hall, Huntingdonshire]], by his wife Elizabeth, sister of [[Sir Richard Neave, 1st Baronet]], [[Governor of the Bank of England]].\n\nHe married in Rochester in 1796 Esther daughter of John Puget, a London banker, by his wife, Esther, daughter of James Dunn, MP for Dublin 1758\u201362. Esther's siblings included John Puget, of Pointer's Grove, near [[Totteridge]], [[Hertfordshire]], Director of the [[Bank of England]], and Rear-Admiral [[Peter Puget]], CB, who [[Vancouver Expedition|explored]] with Captain [[George Vancouver]] and after whom [[Puget Sound]] is named. The family lived at Bickley Hall, built for his uncle John Wells by [[Robert Mylne (architect)|Robert Mylne]] in 1780, and extended to a design by [[Robert Smirke (architect)|Sir Robert Smirke]] in 1810.<ref>H Colvin, ''A Biographical Dictionary of British Architects 1660-1840'', 2008.</ref>\n\nHe also owned the [[East Malling and Larkfield|Malling Heath estate]] in Kent [East and West Malling Tithe Award Schedules 1842].  He was among the leading shipbuilders on the River Thames, a partner in yards at Deptford, Rotherhithe and Blackwall.<ref>P. Banbury, ''Shipbuilders of the Thames and Medway'', 1971.</ref> He served as [[High Sheriff of Kent]] for 1812 and then stood unsuccessfully for parliament at [[Maidstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone]] in [[1818 United Kingdom general election|1818]].<ref name=\"stooks-smith\" /><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=j0AsmWc5zYwC&pg=RA1-PA218&lpg=RA1-PA218&dq=%22John+Wells+%22+Maidstone&source=bl&ots=mgiZxh2702&sig=tt0A0u2n_yJNqNojy-pq-jiKkD0&hl=en&ei=-Lm9TLnpAsyTjAf5pZmcAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22John%20Wells%20%22%20Maidstone&f=false R G Thorne ''The House of Commons 1790-1820'']</ref> He was elected as the Tory [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for Maidstone at the [[1820 United Kingdom general election|general election in March 1820]] and held the seat until [[1830 United Kingdom general election|1830]],<ref name=\"rayment\" /> when he did not stand again in Maidstone.<ref name=\"stooks-smith\" />\n\nWells was a strong opponent of the [[Catholic Emancipation]] Bill in 1828, declaring that he would fight to defend the Protestant Constitution \"until he was up to his knees in blood\".<ref>[http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/religion_in_maidstone.aspx Maidstone Borough Council - Religion in Maidstone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023085939/http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/religion_in_maidstone.aspx |date=23 October 2010 }}</ref> He increasingly moved towards the Whigs and was very much his own man.\n\nWells died two weeks after his wife when he was aged 87. They had three sons and five daughters, of whom one son and three daughters predeceased him. His daughter Eleanor married [[James Browne (1793\u20131854)|James Browne]], [[Mayo (UK Parliament constituency)|MP for Mayo]] 1818\u201331, and his daughter Elizabeth married [[Dyke baronets|Sir Percyval Hart Dyke]], 6th Bt.  His great-great-great-nephew, [[John Wells (20th-century British politician)|Sir John Wells]], was MP for Maidstone 1959\u201387.<ref>Burke's ''Landed Gentry'', 1964.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-wells-1 | John Wells }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[George Longman (MP)|George Longman]]\n | before2 = [[Abraham Wildey Robarts|Abraham Robarts]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Maidstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone]]\n | years = [[1818 United Kingdom general election|1818]] \u2013 [[1837 United Kingdom general election|1837]]\n | with  = [[Abraham Wildey Robarts|Abraham Robarts]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Henry Winchester]]\n | after2 = [[Abraham Wildey Robarts|Abraham Robarts]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wells, John}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1848 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1820\u20131826]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1826\u20131830]]\n[[Category:Tory MPs (pre-1834)]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n'''John Wells''' (1761 \u2013 22 November 1848)<ref name=\"rayment\">{{Rayment-hc|m|1|date=March 2012}}</ref> was an English [[Tory (British political party)|Tory]]<ref name=\"stooks-smith\">{{cite book\n |last=Stooks Smith\n |first=Henry.\n |editor=[[F. W. S. Craig|Craig, F. W. S.]]\n |title=[[The Parliaments of England]]\n |origyear=1844-1850\n |edition=2nd\n |year=1973\n |publisher=Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn=0-900178-13-2\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/parliamentsofeng0000smit/page/168 168]\n }}</ref> politician  who sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1820 to 1830.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', under 'Wells, William (1729\u20131805)'.</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Malling, Kent]] the second son of William Wells, of [[Bickley]] Hall, Bromley in Kent and [[Holme, Cambridgeshire|Holme Hall, Huntingdonshire]], by his wife Elizabeth, sister of [[Sir Richard Neave, 1st Baronet]], [[Governor of the Bank of England]].\n\nHe married in Rochester in 1796 Esther daughter of John Puget, a London banker, by his wife, Esther, daughter of James Dunn, MP for Dublin 1758-62. Esther's siblings included John Puget, of Pointer's Grove, near [[Totteridge]], [[Hertfordshire]], Director of the [[Bank of England]], and Rear-Admiral [[Peter Puget]], CB, who [[Vancouver Expedition|explored]] with Captain [[George Vancouver]] and after whom [[Puget Sound]] is named. The family lived at Bickley Hall, built for his uncle John Wells by [[Robert Mylne (architect)|Robert Mylne]] in 1780, and extended to a design by [[Robert Smirke (architect)|Sir Robert Smirke]] in 1810.<ref>H Colvin, ''A Biographical Dictionary of British Architects 1660-1840'', 2008.</ref>\n\nHe also owned the [[East Malling and Larkfield|Malling Heath estate]] in Kent [East and West Malling Tithe Award Schedules 1842].  He was among the leading shipbuilders on the River Thames, a partner in yards at Deptford, Rotherhithe and Blackwall.<ref>P. Banbury, ''Shipbuilders of the Thames and Medway'', 1971.</ref> He served as [[High Sheriff of Kent]] for 1812 and then stood unsuccessfully for parliament at [[Maidstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone]] in [[1818 United Kingdom general election|1818]].<ref name=\"stooks-smith\" /><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=j0AsmWc5zYwC&pg=RA1-PA218&lpg=RA1-PA218&dq=%22John+Wells+%22+Maidstone&source=bl&ots=mgiZxh2702&sig=tt0A0u2n_yJNqNojy-pq-jiKkD0&hl=en&ei=-Lm9TLnpAsyTjAf5pZmcAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22John%20Wells%20%22%20Maidstone&f=false R G Thorne ''The House of Commons 1790-1820'']</ref> He was elected as the Tory [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for Maidstone at the [[1820 United Kingdom general election|general election in March 1820]] and held the seat until [[1830 United Kingdom general election|1830]],<ref name=\"rayment\" /> when he did not stand again in Maidstone.<ref name=\"stooks-smith\" />\n\nWells was a strong opponent of the [[Catholic Emancipation]] Bill in 1828, declaring that he would fight to defend the Protestant Constitution \"until he was up to his knees in blood\".<ref>[http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/religion_in_maidstone.aspx Maidstone Borough Council - Religion in Maidstone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023085939/http://www.maidstone.gov.uk/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/religion_in_maidstone.aspx |date=23 October 2010 }}</ref> He increasingly moved towards the Whigs and was very much his own man.\n\nWells died two weeks after his wife when he was aged 87. They had three sons and five daughters, of whom one son and three daughters predeceased him. His daughter Eleanor married [[James Browne (1793\u20131854)|James Browne]], [[Mayo (UK Parliament constituency)|MP for Mayo]] 1818-31, and his daughter Elizabeth married [[Dyke baronets|Sir Percyval Hart Dyke]], 6th Bt.  His great-great-great-nephew, [[John Wells (20th-century British politician)|Sir John Wells]], was MP for Maidstone 1959-87.<ref>Burke's ''Landed Gentry'', 1964.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-wells-1 | John Wells }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[George Longman (MP)|George Longman]]\n | before2 = [[Abraham Wildey Robarts|Abraham Robarts]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Maidstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone]]\n | years = [[1818 United Kingdom general election|1818]] \u2013 [[1837 United Kingdom general election|1837]]\n | with  =