 Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 2 January 2004: [[OH-58 Kiowa#OH-58D|OH-58D Kiowa]] 90-0370 from [[82nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|1\u201382 Aviation Brigade]], [[17th Cavalry Regiment|1\u201317 Cavalry Regiment]] shot down near [[Fallujah]], killing a pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armyaircrews.com/kiowa.html|title=Kiowa Crewmembers Line of Duty Deaths|publisher=Army Air Crews|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 8 January 2004: [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk|UH-60 Black Hawk]] 86-24488 from 571st Medical Company (Air Ambulance) was shot down near [[Fallujah]], killing 9 crew and passengers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2004-01-08-iraq-helicopter_x.htm|title=Helicopters shot down or crashed in Iraq|work=USA Today|date=8 January 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007 | first1=Jim | last1=Michaels}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article990772.ece|title=Black Hawk crash in Iraq kills nine US soldiers|work=The Times|date=8 January 2004|accessdate=11 February 2009 | location=London|first=Ed|last=Hawkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1451169/Nine-killed-in-Black-Hawk-crash-in-Iraq.html|title=Nine killed in Black Hawk crash in Iraq|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 January 2004|accessdate=11 February 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 13 January 2004: [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] from [[3rd Cavalry Regiment (United States)#4th Squadron (\"Longknife\")|4th Squadron, 3d Armored Cavalry Regiment]] was shot down near [[Habbaniyah]], the pilots were rescued.<ref>{{cite news |title=Press Release |agency=Reuters|quote=BAGHDAD (Reuters) \u2013 A U.S. Apache helicopter that crashed west of Baghdad on Tuesday may have been shot down by Iraqi guerrillas, a U.S. military spokesman said. \"Our initial information tells us that it's possible that the helicopter was downed by or at least was struck by enemy fire,\" the spokesman said after the helicopter crashed near the town of Habbaniya, about 50 miles west of the capital.|date=13 January 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Boeing AH-64 Apache|url=http://www.militaryaviation.eu/helicopter/Boeing/AH-64.htm|quote=On January 13th, 2004 an Apache was shot down near the western Iraqi town of Habbaniyah. This was the second of the heavily armed gun-ships downed by guerrilla fire since President Bush declared an end to major combat May 1st, 2003.|accessdate=12 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127022954/http://www.militaryaviation.eu/helicopter/Boeing/AH-64.htm|archive-date=2010-11-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 19 March 2004: [[MD Helicopters MH-6 Little Bird#Variants|AH-6J]] 25364, [[160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne)|1-160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment]], shot down vicinity of [[Amiriyah]] by an unknown surface-to-air missile while conducting precision [[close air support]] during day operations. Both pilots were rescued by Special Operations forces. {{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 11 April 2004: [[Boeing AH-64 Apache#AH-64D|AH-64D Apache]] 02-5301 from C Company, [[1st Battalion, 227th Aviation Regiment (United States)|1\u2013227 Aviation Regiment]], 4th BCT, [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] shot down west of [[Baghdad]], killing both pilots.<ref>{{cite web|title=ASN Wikibase Occurrence # 77123|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=77123|publisher=Aviation Safety|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 12 April 2004: [[Sikorsky MH-53#MH-53J/M|MH-53M Pave Low]] 69-5797 of [[20th Special Operations Squadron|16th Special Operations Wing/20th Special Operations Squadron]] was shot down by a [[rocket-propelled grenade]] near [[Fallujah]], three on board were wounded, and the helicopter was later destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joebaugher.com/usaf_serials/1969.html|title=1969 USAF Serial Numbers|accessdate=17 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurlburt.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123018870 |title=Dagger Point: Major Edwards shares his experience of getting shot down |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316153118/http://www.hurlburt.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123018870 |archivedate=2008-03-16 }}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] [[United States Navy]] \u2013 24 June 2004: [[Bell AH-1 SuperCobra|AH-1W SuperCobra]] 163939 was forced to land after receiving hostile fire in [[Fallujah]]. Both pilots were rescued safely, the fate of the helicopter is unknown.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baugher|first1=Joe|title=US Navy and US Marine Corps BuNos Third Series (163050 to 164195)|url=http://www.joebaugher.com/navy_serials/thirdseries22.html|publisher=Joe Baugher|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 4 September 2004: OH-58D Kiowa (3\u201317 CAV) shot down over Tal Afar, Iraq; both pilots safe. Incident highlighted in TV Documentary Kiowa Down.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.strykernews.com/archives/2005/09/25/kiowa_down_documentary.html|title=\"Kiowa Down\" Documentary|date=25 September 2005|accessdate=12 May 2010|quote=A \"routine mission\" in Iraq on 4 September 2004, turned into a raging firefight for Stryker troops with the 3rd Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division, Scout Platoon, and B Company of the 5th Battalion, 20th Infantry Regiment, as they fought off heavy fire (including 60-mm mortars and RPGs) in a rescue mission launched after Iraqi insurgents shot down a Kiowa helicopter and swarmed to capture it and the two pilots.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716160035/http://www.strykernews.com/archives/2005/09/25/kiowa_down_documentary.html|archive-date=16 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Navy \u2013 8 September 2004: [[CH-46 Sea Knight|CH-46E Sea Knight]] 153372 Shot down by RPG Fire South of Camp Fallujah, crashes and is burned out near Al-Buaisa. All four crew members injured.<ref name=\"thirdseries3\">{{cite web|last1=Baugher|first1=Joe|url=http://www.joebaugher.com/navy_serials/thirdseries19.html|title=US Navy and US Marine Corps BuNos-Third Series (150139 to 156169)|publisher=Joe Baugher|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.af.mil/news/story_print.asp?storyID=123008770 |title=Airmen help save lives following UH-60 crash at Tallil |author=Master Sgt. Don Perrien |publisher=Air Force Print News |date=27 September 2004 |accessdate=11 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718112018/http://www.af.mil/news/story_print.asp?storyID=123008770 |archivedate=18 July 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 9 November 2004: US OH-58D Kiowa shot down by rocket fire over Fallujah.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Iraq/US-helicopter-shot-down-over-Falluja/|title=US Helicopter Shot Down Over Falluja|work=The Age |date=November 2004}}{{dead link|date=February 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] [[United States Marine Corps]] \u2013 11 November 2004: AH-1W SuperCobra 161021 from [[HMLA-169]] is shot down by RPG and small arms fire near Fallujah. It is destroyed by Iraqi rebel forces, crew recovered intact.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/nigel.sadler1/Accidents_2004.htm |title=Naval Air Accidents 2004 |accessdate=2 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web