ite press release|publisher=Department of Defense |quote=The Department of Defense announced today the death of two Marines who were supporting Operation Iraqi Freedom. Maj. Gerald M. Bloomfield II, 38, of Ypsilanti, Mich. Capt. Michael D. Martino, 32, of Fairfax, Va. Both Marines died November 2 when their AH-1W Super Cobra helicopter crashed while flying in support of security and stabilization operations near Ar Ramadi, Iraq. Both Marines were with Marine Light-Attack Helicopter Squadron 369, Marine Aircraft Group 39, 3rd Marine Aircraft Wing, I Marine Expeditionary Force, Camp Pendleton, Calif. During Operation Iraqi Freedom, their unit was attached to 2nd Marine Aircraft Wing, II MEF (Forward). |title=DoD Identifies Marine Casualties |date=3 November 2005 |accessdate=29 October 2010 |url=http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=9039 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129115720/http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=9039 |archivedate=29 November 2010 }}</ref>\n\n'''Shootdowns in 2006'''\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 13 January 2006: OH-58D Kiowa 95-0021 from [[10th Aviation Regiment (United States)|1\u201310th Aviation Regiment]] shot down outside Forward Operating Base Courage, outside Mosul, killing the two pilots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armyaircrews.com/kiowa.html|title=ARMY AIR CREWS: Kiowa Crewmembers Line of Duty Deaths|quote=A/C struck top of embankment and cartwheeled into ground after receiving hostile fire while conducting a combat air patrol with another OH-58D just outside FOB Courage.|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 16 January 2006: AH-64D Apache 03-5385 from B Company, 1\u20134th Aviation Regiment shot down north of Baghdad, killing the two pilots.<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2006-01-16-helicopter-down_x.htm|title=U.S. helicopter crashes in Iraq; status of crew unknown|work=USA Today|date=16 January 2006|accessdate=28 January 2009}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 1 April 2006: an AH-64D Apache from 4\u20134th Aviation Regiment shot down southwest of Baghdad, killing the two crewmen.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n* [[File:RAF Lowvis Army roundel.svg|24px|RAF Roundel]] [[Royal Navy]] \u2013 6 May 2006: A [[Westland Lynx]] AH.7 from 847 Squadron is shot down with a [[SA-14]] over Basra, killing five crewmen and crashing into a house.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/04/27/europe/EU-GEN-Britain-Iraq-Helicopter.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080226104306/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/04/27/europe/EU-GEN-Britain-Iraq-Helicopter.php |archivedate=2008-02-26|title=British helicopter that crashed in Iraq last year was shot down, investigation concludes |newspaper=International Herald Tribune|date=27 April 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://news.soc.mil/releases/News%20Archive/2006/06APR/060427-01.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227120844/http://news.soc.mil/releases/News%20Archive/2006/06APR/060427-01.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 February 2009 |title=PRESS RELEASE: Special Operations Soldier dies in Iraq |date=16 May 2006 |accessdate=16 July 2010 |publisher=U.S. Army Special Operations Command Public Affairs Office |quote=Two aviators from the 160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne) died 14 May 2006, when their AH-6M Little Bird helicopter was shot down by enemy fire during combat operations in Yousifiyah, south of Baghdad, Iraq.[...] }}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 14 May 2006: An [[OH-6 Cayuse|AH-6M Little Bird]] (OH-6 Cayuse) from [[160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne)|1\u2013160th SOAR]] shot down during combat operations in [[Yusufiyah]], southwest of Baghdad, killing the two crewmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armyaircrews.com/cayuse.html|title=ARMY AIR CREWS: Cayuse Crewmembers Line of Duty Deaths|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 13 July 2006: AH-64D Apache from 4\u20134th Aviation Regiment shot down south of Baghdad. The two pilots survive.<ref>{{cite news |title=US Army Soldiers Survive Helicopter Crash in Iraq |url=http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?section=nation_world&id=4361747 |publisher=6abc.com |date=13 June 2006 |accessdate=29 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227135539/http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?section=news%2Fnational_world&id=4361747 |archivedate=27 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n'''Shootdowns in 2007'''\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 20 January 2007: A UH-60 Black Hawk from C Company, 1\u2013131 Aviation Regiment<ref name=\"armyaircrewsbh\">{{cite web|url=http://www.armyaircrews.com/blackhawk.html|title=ARMY AIR CREWS: Blackhawk Crewmembers Line of Duty Deaths|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> shot down by a combination of several heavy machine guns and a shoulder-fired missile north-east of Baghdad. All 12 crew and passengers on board are killed in the incident.<ref name=\"armyaircrewsbh\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=2814195|title=Black Hawk Likely Shot Down in Iraq|author=Jonathan Karl|publisher=ABC News|date=22 January 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 25 January 2007: A UH-60 Black Hawk shot down by gunfire near Hit. All aboard survive the incident.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/12/world/middleeast/12copters.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=Insurgents Stepping Up Efforts to Down U.S. Helicopters in Iraq|author=James Glanz|newspaper=The New York Times|date=12 February 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 28 January 2007: AH-64D Apache from 4th Battalion, 227th Aviation Regiment, 1st Air Cavalry Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division shot down by hostile fire during the [[Battle of Najaf (2007)|Battle of Najaf]], killing the two pilots.<ref name=\"The Age\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/world/us-iraqi-forces-kill-250-militants-in-najaf/2007/01/29/1169919241141.html|title=US-Iraqi Forces Kill 250 Militants in Najaf|work=[[The Age]]|date=29 January 2007|accessdate=1 February 2009 | location=Melbourne}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Blackwater USA]] \u2013 23 January 2007: A Blackwater USA MD 530F helicopter is shot down by hostile fire in Baghdad. All of the 5-man crew are killed in the incident, likely executed after surviving the crash. One survivor was also killed under unclear circumstances, when another Blackwater helicopter descended to the crash site.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/5-die-in-private-u-s-helicopter-crash-in-iraq-1.634036|title= 5 die in private U.S. helicopter crash in Iraq\n|publisher=CBC news|date=23 January 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/16783885\n|title= 4 of 5 Blackwater employees shot after crash; fighting flares in Baghdad|publisher=NBC News|date=24 January 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Blackwater USA]] \u2013 31 January 2007: A [[Blackwater USA]] [[Bell 412]] helicopter is shot down under fire near [[Karma, Iraq|Karma]] during a flight between [[Al Hillah]] and [[Baghdad, Iraq|Baghdad]]. A US military helicopter rescues the passengers and crew.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/08/world/middleeast/08helicopter.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title=Loss of Copters Suggests Shift in Iraqi Tactics|author=Richard A. Oppel Jr. & James Glanz|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 February 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L08245305.htm|title=Officials report sixth helicopter downing in Iraq|agency=Reuters|date=8 February 2007|accessdate=1 February 2009}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 2 February 2007: AH-64D Apache 02-5337 from A Company, 1st Battalion, 227th Aviation Regiment, [[1st Air Cavalry Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division]] shot down by a combination of gunfire and a shoulder-fired missile, near Taji, killing the two pilots.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,249798,00.html|title=Military: U.S. Apache Helicopter Shot Down in Iraq|publisher=Fox News Channel|date=3 February 2007|accessdate=11 June 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070530054851/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,249798,00.html|archive-date=30 May 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/6323125.stm|title=US helicopter 'shot down' in Iraq|publisher=BBC News|date=2 February 2007|accessdate=11 June 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003553908_webiraq02.html |title=Fourth Army copter downed in Iraq; 2 crew killed |work=The Seattle Times |author=Bassem Mroue |date=2 February 2007 |accessdate=9 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403091938/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003553908_webiraq02.html |archivedate=3 April 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Marine Corps \u2013 7 February 2007: A [[CH-46E Sea Knight]] from [[HMM-364]] is shot down, by a shoulder-fired missile, in [[al-Karma]], outside [[Fallujah]], killing all 7 on board. (see picture above)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/2007/02/21/us_helicopter_shot_down_in_iraq.html|title=U.S. helicopter crash in Iraq kills seven|work=USA Today|date=7 February 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007| location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://members.forbes.com/global/2007/0423/032.html|title=Light Warfare|work=Forbes|accessdate=31 December 2008|date=23 April 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226190535/http://members.forbes.com/global/2007/0423/032.html|archive-date=26 February 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 21 February 2007: A UH-60 Black Hawk is hit by RPG and small arms fire north of Baghdad and makes a hard landing; all nine military personnel on board were rescued.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/2007/02/21/us_helicopter_shot_down_in_iraq.html|title=U.S. helicopter shot down in Iraq \u2013 Troops aboard all rescued|publisher=The Star.com|date=21 February 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007 | location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-02/22/content_5763385.htm|title=8th U.S. helicopter, Black Hawk, shot down north of Baghdad|agency=Xinhua News Agency|author=Han Lin|date=22 February 2007|accessdate=17 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609185249/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-02/22/content_5763385.htm|archivedate=9 June 2011}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 5 April 2007: A UH-60 Black Hawk carrying nine is shot down in [[Latifiya]] using anti-aircraft heavy machine guns, 4 were wounded.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1173879269710&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull|title=Al-Qaida claims it downed US helicopter in Iraq|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=8 April 2007|accessdate=30 May 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/worldlatest/story/0,,-6535572,00.html |title=U.S. Helicopter Incidents in Iraq |work=The Guardian |date=5 April 2007 |accessdate=30 May 2007 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502200326/http://www.guardian.co.uk/worldlatest/story/0%2C%2C-6535572%2C00.html |archivedate=2 May 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2007/04/mil-070405-voa01.htm|title=4 Injured After US Helicopter Crashes South of Baghdad|publisher=Voice of America|author=Margaret Besheer|date=5 April 2007|accessdate=7 June 2008}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 29 May 2007: An OH-58D(R) Kiowa 93-0978 from B Troop, 2\u20136 Cavalry Regiment is shot down between [[Baquba]] and [[Muqdadiyah]] with small arms, killing the chopper's two pilots.<ref name=\"armyaircrews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.armyaircrews.com/kiowa.html|title=ARMY AIR CREWS: Kiowa Crewmembers Line of Duty Deaths|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/meast/05/29/iraq.main/index.html|title=Chopper attack, bombs kill 10 U.S. troops in Iraq|publisher=CNN|date=29 May 2007|accessdate=30 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/05/30/world/main2866062.shtml|title=10 GIs Die in Iraq on Memorial Day|publisher=CBS News|date=29 May 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 2 July 2007: OH-58D Kiowa 91-0560 from 3\u201317 Cavalry Regiment is shot down along a canal south of Baghdad in [[Babil province]] with small arms, both pilots were rescued by strapping themselves onto the stub wings of an AH-64 Apache. Helicopter was later destroyed.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12665&Itemid=21 |title=Task Force Marne pilots rescued from downed helicopter |publisher=Operation Iraqi Freedom |date=3 July 2007 |accessdate=3 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227024126/http://www.mnf-iraq.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12665&Itemid=21 |archivedate=27 February 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://www.joebaugher.com/usaf_serials/1991.html|title=1991 USAF Serial Numbers|accessdate=17 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''Shootdowns in 2008'''\n* [[File:Iraqi Air Force roundel 2011.svg|20px|Iraqi Air Force Roundel]] [[Iraqi Air Force]] \u2013 27 March 2008: An Iraqi military Mil Mi-17 helicopter is shot down by ground fire during heavy fighting with rebel forces in northern [[Basra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74604&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |title=Iraqi copter shot down by gunmen in Basra |publisher=Aswat Aliraq |date=29 March 2008 |accessdate=30 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402015402/http://www.aswataliraq.info/look/english/article.tpl?IdLanguage=1&IdPublication=4&NrArticle=74604&NrIssue=2&NrSection=1 |archivedate=2 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===[[2006 Lebanon War]]===\n* [[File:Roundel of Israel.svg|20px|Israeli Air Force Roundel]] 12 August 2006 - [[Hezbollah]] fighters shot down an Israeli [[Sikorsky CH-53 Sea Stallion|CH-53 Yas'ur]] with an anti-tank missile, killing five air crew members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Defense/Article.aspx?id=233506|title=Security and Defense: Coordinating capabilities|publisher=Jerusalem Post|date=12 August 2011 |accessdate=2011-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2006/08/22/208558/israel-studies-ch-53-shoot-down.html|title=Israel studies CH-53 shoot-down|publisher=Flightglobal|date=6 August 2006 |accessdate=2011-08-12}}</ref> This was the only combat loss to enemy fire during that war, another three [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] helicopters were lost in crashes during the war.<ref>https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3290239,00.html</ref>\n\n===Russo-Georgian War (2008)===\n* [[File:Roundel of Georgia.svg|20px|Georgian Air Force roundel]] 20 April 2008 \u2013 Georgian officials claimed a Russian [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]] [[2008 Georgian spy plane shootdowns|shot down a Georgian]] [[Hermes 450]] [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] and provided video footage from the ill-fated drone showing an apparent MiG-29 launching an air-to-air missile at it. Russia denies that the aircraft was theirs and says they did not have any pilots in the air that day. Abkhazia's administration claimed its own forces shot down the drone with an [[Aero L-39 Albatros|L-39]] aircraft \"because it was violating Abkhaz airspace and breaching ceasefire agreements\".<ref>Long, Helen. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7358761.stm \"Russia 'shot down Georgia drone'\"]. BBC News, 21 April 2008. Retrieved 10 March 2009.</ref> UN investigation concluded that the video was authentic and that the drone was shot down by a Russian MiG-29 or Su-27 using a [[Vympel R-73|R-73]] heat seeking missile.<ref>Chivers, C.J.{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/05/26/europe/georgia.php |title=Georgia |accessdate=2008-06-05 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013141331/http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/05/26/europe/georgia.php |archivedate=13 October 2008 |df=dmy }}  ''International Herald Tribune'', 26 May 2008. Retrieved 10 March 2009.</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 8 August 2008 \u2013 The first [[Russian Air Force]] loss of the campaign was a [[Sukhoi Su-25|Su-25]], piloted by Lieutenant Colonel Oleg Terebunsky of the 368th Attack Aviation Regiment. It was shot down over [[South Ossetia]] near the Zarsk pass, between [[Java (town)|Dzhava]] and [[Tskhinvali]]. It was hit by friendly fire, a [[MANPADS]] missile fired by South Ossetian militia at around 18:00. Earlier in the day, a flight of four [[Georgian Air Force]] Su-25 planes had attacked a Russian army convoy in the same area. This was one of the few missions conducted by Georgia's Su-25s during the brief conflict Georgia believed its aircraft would soon become easy targets for Russian interceptors. The Georgian aircraft returned to their bases and were hidden under camouflage netting to prevent them from being located.<ref>http://www.cast.ru/files/The_Tanks_of_August_sm_eng.pdf</ref><ref name=\"Jamestown\">{{cite web |title=The Russia-Georgia Conflict as Analyzed by the Center of Analysis of Strategies and Technologies in Moscow |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/ |access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 a Russian [[Tupolev Tu-22M|Tu-22M3]] was shot down in [[South Ossettia]] by a Georgian [[Buk missile system|Buk-M1]] [[surface-to-air-missile]] system during the [[Russo-Georgian War]]. Three of the four crew members were killed, while the co-pilot was taken [[Prisoner of war|POW]] by Georgian forces.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lenta.ru/news/2008/09/16/bodies/ |title=\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0422\u0443-22\u041c3 |publisher=lenta.ru |language=Russian |date=16 September 2008 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/georgia-refuses-to-return-remains-of-russian-pilot/|title=Georgia refuses to return remains of Russian pilot|website=RT International|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 - A Russian [[Sukhoi Su-24|Su-24]] was shot down by Georgian air defense forces with an anti-aircraft missile south of Tskhinvali during the morning. Both pilots ejected, but the co-pilot died impacting the ground when his parachute was damaged by fire. The wounded pilot was captured by Georgian forces. This loss was not initially acknowledged by Russia, while verified later by independent sources.<ref>https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/</ref> The captured pilot, Major Igor Zinov was shown on Georgian TV while being hospitalized together with the co-pilot of the downed Tu-22MR.<ref>https://www.rferl.org/a/Captured_Russian_Pilots_Leave_Georgia_Voicing_Gratitude_Regret/1192311.html</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 A Russian [[Sukhoi Su-25|Su-25]] piloted by Colonel Sergey Kobylash, commander of the 368th Attack Aviation Regiment, was hit by a Georgian MANPADS during an daylight strafing run on a Georgian military formation south of Tskhinvali, on the Gori-Tskhinvali road at 10:30: after making his initial approach, Kolybash's aircraft was struck by a missile that hit his left engine, destroying it.  Not long after, as Kobylash was returning to base at an altitude of 1000 meters, a second [[MANPADS]] missile struck his right engine, leaving the plane without thrust. Kobylash was able to glide to Russian controlled territory before ejecting north of Tskhinvali in a South Ossetian village of the Georgian enclave in the Great Liakh gorge, where he was recovered by a Russian [[combat search and rescue]] team. Shortly after Kobylash was rescued, South Ossetian militants claimed they had downed a Georgian Su-25, however Georgian Air Force did not operate since the day before, likely making the second fatal hit on this Su-25 another friendly fire incident.<ref>http://www.cast.ru/files/The_Tanks_of_August_sm_eng.pdf</ref><ref name=\"Jamestown\">{{cite web |title=The Russia-Georgia Conflict as Analyzed by the Center of Analysis of Strategies and Technologies in Moscow |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/ |access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 at 13:00, another Russian [[Sukhoi Su-25|Su-25]] from the 368th Attack Aviation Regiment, piloted by Major Vladimir Edamenko, was struck by a Russian [[ZSU-23-4 Shilka]] anti-aircraft gun near [[Java (town)|Dzhava]] killing the pilot in another friendly fire incident, due to the failure of the [[Identification friend or foe|IFF system]] on the Su-25. With mounting confusion between Russian Air Force and land foarces, at 15:00, a Russian Su-25 mistakenly attacked a Russian military convoy near Liakhva, destroying a fuel tanker and injuring several troops. The Russian soldiers returned fire with a [[MANPADS]] damaging the Su-25.<ref>http://www.cast.ru/files/The_Tanks_of_August_sm_eng.pdf</ref><ref name=\"Jamestown\">{{cite web |title=The Russia-Georgia Conflict as Analyzed by the Center of Analysis of Strategies and Technologies in Moscow |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/ |access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 The final Russian aircraft lost in combat was a [[Sukhoi Su-24|Su-24]], which was shot down by friendly forces while it was escorting a Russian column on the Tskhinvali-Gori highway, when it was hit by a Russian SAM. The crew ejected and was recovered by a search and rescue helicopter.<ref>https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/</ref>\n\n===War in Donbass (2014\u2013present)===\n{{Main|List of Ukrainian aircraft losses during the Ukrainian crisis}}\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] [[Ukrainian Ground Forces#Airmobile Forces and Army Aviation|Ukrainian Army Aviation]] \u2013 2 May 2014: Two [[Mil Mi-24]] helicopters were shot down during large-scale operations during the [[Siege of Sloviansk]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trust.org/item/20140502034153-9eh7a |title=Pro-Russian rebels in Slaviansk say Ukraine tries to retake town, gunfire heard |publisher=Trust.org |date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> Rebels claimed they had taken one of the pilot captive.<ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/05/2/7024139/ \u0421\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \"\u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u044c\u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430]. ''Ukrayinska Pravda'', 2 May 2014</ref> The [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Ukraine)|Ukrainian Ministry of Internal Affairs]] reported that two helicopters had been shot down, resulting in the deaths of two airmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tass.ru/mezhdunarodnaya-panorama/1162845|publisher=TASS|accessdate=24 May 2016|title=\u0423 \u0421\u043b\u043e\u0432'\u044f\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0443 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u0431\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0454\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0431\u0456\u0439. \u0421\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \"\u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u044c\u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Army Aviation \u2013 5 May 2014: A [[Mil Mi-24]] crashed after it was shot down by a heavy machine gun manned by rebel forces. The helicopter crash landed in a river, which allowed all crew members to survive.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ukraine soldiers killed in renewed Sloviansk fighting|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27280814|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u0423 \u0421\u043b\u043e\u0432'\u044f\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0443 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0456\u0442. \u0417\u0430\u0433\u0438\u043d\u0443\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u0456\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438|url=http://www.gazeta.lviv.ua/2014/05/29/u-slovjansku-teroristi-zbili-vjskovij-vertolt-zaginuli-ploti/|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Army Aviation \u2013 29 May 2014: A [[Mil Mi-8]] helicopter was shot down by rebel forces between [[Kramatorsk]] and Mount Karachun, killing 14 on board, among them General Vladimir Kultchysky. Another soldier was seriously injured but survived the crash.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Paton Walsh|first1=Nick|last2=Smith-Spark|first2=Laura|title=Ukrainian military helicopter shot down; 14 dead, president says|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/05/29/world/europe/ukraine-crisis/ |publisher=CNN|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] [[Ukrainian Air Force]] \u2013 6 June 2014: An [[Antonov An-30]] surveillance plane was shot down by Separatist militias from Slaviansk with two [[Man-portable air-defense system|shoulder-launched missiles]]. Ukrainian authorities initially claimed that the pilots survived,<ref>[http://news.liga.net/news/incident/2048765-samolet_nad_slavyanskom_terroristy_podbili_iz_pzrk_seleznev.htm \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u0437 \u041f\u0417\u0420\u041a \u2013 \u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0432]. Liga News, 6 June 2014</ref><ref>[http://news.liga.net/news/politics/2048820-piloty_an_26_spasli_zhiteley_slavyanska_otvedya_samolet_ot_goroda.htm \u041f\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0442\u044b \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430, \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0434\u044f \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430]. Liga News, 6 June 2014</ref> but they later reported that five crewmembers were killed in the action, and two others missing.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/spokesman-three-pilots-from-downed-an-26-die-in-sloviansk-351056.html Spokesman: Three pilots from downed An-26 die in Sloviansk]. ''Kyiv Post''. 7 June 2014</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 14 June 2014: An [[Ilyushin Il-76]] transport plane was [[Ukrainian Air Force Ilyushin Il-76 shoot-down|shot down]] as it approached an airport in [[Luhansk]], killing nine crew members and 40 troops on board.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/ukraine-ministry-rebels-military-aircraft-article-1.1829598 \"Pro-Russian rebels shoot down Ukraine military plane, killing service personnel\"], Associated Press. 14 June 2014. Retrieved 14 June 2014</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 14 June 2014: Rebels claim to have shot down a [[Sukhoi Su-24]] with a portable anti-aircraft gun after it had dropped cluster munitions on a local police station. They also claim the pilot had bailed out and they sent out a search mission after him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Defenders launch counteroffensive in Lugansk region|url=http://tass.ru/en/world/736052 |publisher=TASS|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 19 June 2014: A spokesman for the militia in Donetsk stated that they downed a Ukrainian Air Force [[Sukhoi Su-25]] during the battle in Yampil.<ref>[http://rian.com.ua/incidents/20140619/353606933.html \u041d\u0430\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u043c \u042f\u043c\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0443-25 \u2013 \u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b] (Su-25 shot down above the village of Yampil \u2013 militia) RIA Novosti. 20 June 2014. Retrieved 20 June 2014</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 24 June 2014: The Ukrainian military says one of its helicopters, a [[Mil Mi-8]], had been shot down by pro-Russian rebels in the east near [[Sloviansk]], killing all nine people on board,<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28002993 \"Ukraine army helicopter 'shot down' despite ceasefire\"] [[BBC World News]], 24 June 2014.</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 14 July 2014: A Ukrainian [[Antonov An-26]] transport aircraft was shot down by a surface-to-air missile over eastern Ukraine while flying at {{convert|6500|m|ft}}. The Ukrainian defence minister claimed that the altitude is far from the reach of a shoulder-launched missile, suggesting that the aircraft was downed by Russian forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ukraine-military-plane-shot-down-by-russia-1456632|title=Ukraine: Military Plane 'Shot Down By Russia'|date=14 July 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|work=International Business Times|last=Bacchi|first=Umberto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28299334 |title=Ukraine military plane shot down as fighting rages |publisher=BBC News |date=14 July 2014|accessdate=14 July 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC28309034\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28309034 |title=Ukraine conflict: Jet bombs rebel-held town of Snizhne |publisher=BBC News |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=15 July 2014 }}</ref> Two crewmembers were captured by pro-Russian militiamen, four were rescued by Ukrainian forces and the other two were unaccounted for.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ua.korrespondent.net/ukraine/politics/3392830-dolia-dvokh-luidei-zi-zbytoho-an-26-poky-scho-nevidoma-seleznov|title=\u0414\u043e\u043b\u044f \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0445 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0456 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0410\u043d-26 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0438 \u0449\u043e \u043d\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043e\u043c\u0430 \u2013 \u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u044c\u043e\u0432|date=15 July 2014 |accessdate= 12 April 2015|publisher=Korrespondent.net}}</ref> The missing aviators were found dead on 17 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/two-crewmembers-from-an-26-downed-in-luhansk-region-killed-356423.html|title=Two crewmembers from An-26 downed in Luhansk region killed|date=17 July 2014 |accessdate= 12 April 2015|work=Kyiv Post}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 16 July 2014: A Ukrainian [[Sukhoi Su-25]] was shot down over eastern Ukraine, and the pilot ejected successfully. [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine|National Security Council]] spokesman Andriy Lysenko said that it was shot down by a [[R-27 (air-to-air missile)|R-27T]] missile fired from a Russian [[Sukhoi Su-27]] or [[MiG-29]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://korrespondent.net/ukraine/politics/3393663-rossyiskyi-samolet-sbyl-raketoi-ukraynskyi-su-25-snbo|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b \u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0443-25 \u2013 \u0421\u041d\