430 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f|date=7 August 2014 |accessdate= 12 April 2015|agency=Interfax}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 17 August 2014: A [[Mikoyan MiG-29]] was shot down by rebels in the Luhansk region of eastern Ukraine returning after completing a successful mission. The pilot managed to eject and was found by a search and rescue operation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Magnenou|first1=Fabien|title=DIRECT. Un avion de chasse ukrainien abattu par des s\u00e9paratistes prorusses|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/monde/europe/manifestations-en-ukraine/direct-un-avion-de-chasse-ukrainien-abattu-par-des-separatistes-prorusses_671453.html|publisher=France TV Info|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 20 August 2014: A [[Sukhoi Su-24]]M was shot down by rebel forces in the Luhansk region of eastern Ukraine. The two crewmembers ejected successfully.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.liga.net/news/politics/2995693-v_snbo_utochnili_chto_pod_luganskom_byl_sbit_samolet_su_24m.htm|title=\u0412 \u0421\u041d\u0411\u041e \u0443\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u041b\u0443\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0443-24\u041c|date=24 May 2016 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|publisher=Liga News}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Army Aviation \u2013 20 August 2014: A [[Mil Mi-24]] helicopter was shot down in near the town of [[Horlivka]] according to the [[Ministry of Defence (Ukraine)|Ukrainian Ministry of Defence]]. Both pilots died in the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/14,114912,16513713,Czesc__bialego_konwoju__z_Rosji_jest_juz_na_Ukrainie_.html?PageNumber=2|title=Cz\u0119\u015b\u0107 'bia\u0142ego konwoju' z Rosji jest ju\u017c na Ukrainie. Kij\u00f3w: 'Nie wydali\u015bmy zgody' |language=pl|publisher=Wiadomosci.gazeta.pl |accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 29 August 2014: A [[Sukhoi Su-25]] was shot down by a surface-to-air missile in the Luhansk region of eastern Ukraine. The pilot ejected safely and was recovered by a unit of the [[National Guard of Ukraine|Ukrainian National Guard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.liga.net/news/politics/3106003-v_donbasse_iz_rossiyskogo_zrk_sbili_ukrainskiy_samolet_su_25.htm|title = \u0412 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u0438\u0437 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0417\u0420\u041a \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0443-25|date = 29 August 2014 |accessdate= 24 May 2016|publisher = Liga News}}</ref>\n\n===Syrian Civil War (2011\u2013present)===\n{{Main|List of aviation shootdowns and accidents during the Syrian Civil War}}\n\n===Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen (2015\u2013present)===\n{{Main|List of aviation shootdowns and accidents during the Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen}}\n\n==Civilian aircraft==\n* [[List of airliner shootdown incidents]] \u2013 dealing with civilian airliners\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Russian aircraft losses in the Second Chechen War]]\n* [[List of aviation shootdowns and accidents during the Iraq War]]\n* [[List of combat losses of United States military aircraft since the Vietnam War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Lists of aviation accidents and incidents}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft shootdown incidents| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of aviation accidents and incidents|Shootdowns]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{more footnotes|date=November 2015}}\n\n\nThis is a '''list of aircraft shootdowns''', [[dogfight]]s and other incidents during wars since [[World War II]]. An aircraft shootdown is when an [[aircraft]] is struck by a [[projectile]] launched or fired from an aircraft or from the ground (see [[anti-aircraft warfare]]) which causes the aircraft to no longer be able to continue maintain altitude and strike the ground, often causing the death of the occupants.\n{{inc-transport}}\n\n==Military aircraft==\n===Iraq (1930s)===\n* \"K1124\" a [[Westland Wapiti]] of [[No. 55 Squadron RAF|55 Squadron Royal Air Force]] was shot down by rebel tribesman at [[Al-Rumaitha]], [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraq]].\n\n===Cold War (1947\u20131991)===\n*[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 8 April 1950 \u2013 A [[United States Navy|US Navy]] [[Consolidated PB4Y-2 Privateer|PB4Y-2 Privateer]] of [[VP-26]] launched from [[Wiesbaden]], [[West Germany]] is shot down during a patrol mission over the Baltic by four [[Soviet Air Forces|Soviet Air Force]] [[Lavochkin La-11|La-11 ''\u201cFangs\u201d'']] off of [[Liep\u0101ja]], [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|Latvia]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://sw.propwashgang.org/shootdown_list.html|title=Aircraft Downed During the Cold War and Thereafter|website=sw.propwashgang.org|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n*[[Catalina affair]] (June 1952)\n* [[Air battle over Merkl\u00edn]] (March 10, 1953)\n* [[1953 Avro Lincoln shootdown incident|Avro Lincoln shootdown incident]] (March 12, 1953)\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 27 January 1954 \u2013 An engagement over the yellow sea between eight [[People's Liberation Army Air Force|PLAAF]] [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagots\"'']] and a flight of [[United States Air Force|USAF]] [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] escorting an [[North American B-45 Tornado|RB-45 Tornado]] ends in the downing of one of the attacking MiG-15 by first lieutenant Bertram Beecroft .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aces.safarikovi.org/victories/usa-cold.html|title=Jan J. Safarik: Air Aces Home Page|website=aces.safarikovi.org|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nNK4vhI1T8sC&pg=PA15|title=Aerial Victories of the Jet Era|last=Wyllie|first=Arthur|date=2005-11-01|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-4116-6598-9|page=15}}</ref>\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 26 July 1954 \u2013 Off of [[Hainan|Hainan island]] two PLAAF [[Lavochkin La-11|La-11 ''\"Fangs\"'']] attack two USN [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|AD-4 Skyraiders]] from [[Second VA-54 (U.S. Navy)|VF-54]] lanched off the [[USS Philippine Sea (CV-47)|USS Philippine Sea (CV 47)]] while they are searching for survivors of the [[1954 Cathay Pacific Douglas DC-4 shootdown|Cathay Pacific DC-4 shot down]] by the PLAAF four days earlier. Under attack, pilots William Alexander and John Zarious were soon aided by more AD-4 Skyraiders of their own squadron as well as one [[F4U-5NL Corsair|F4U-5N]] of VC-3. One Lavochkin was downed by two AD-4 piloted by Roy Tatham and Richard Cooks, the other by F4U pilot Edgar Salsig and AD-4 pilots John Damien, John Rochford, Paul Wahlstrom and Richard Ribble.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of North Korea.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 5 February 1955 \u2013 Sixty Km west of [[Pyongyang]] over the [[Yellow Sea]] an [[RB-45 Tornado]] of the [[91st Strategic Reconnaissance Squadron|91st Strategic reconnaissance squadron]] escorted by eight USAF [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] found themselves under attack by twelve [[Korean People's Army Air and Anti-Air Force|KPAF]] [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15''\"Fagots\"'']] , the engagement resulted in the downing of two of the attacking Mikoyan by Sabre pilots Charles Salmon and George Williams.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IVG-v7lgRmoC&pg=PA194|title=A MiG-15 to Freedom: Memoir of the Wartime North Korean Defector who First Delivered the Secret Fighter Jet to the Americans in 1953|last=No|first=Kum-Sok|last2=Osterholm|first2=J. Roger|date=1996-01-01|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-0210-6|page=194}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 17 April 1955 \u2013 A USAF [[RB-47E Stratojet]] of the [[4th Strategic Reconnaissance Squadron]] took off from Eielson AFB and was later shot down off [[Kamchatka Peninsula|Kamchatka]] by two Soviet [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagots\"'']] flown by Korotkov and Sazhinwith. All crew of Lacie C. Neighbors, Robert N. Brooks and Richard E. Watkins Jr are reported missing presumed dead.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]]'''/'''[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]]('''2''') 10 May 1955 \u2013 Over the Yellow Sea eighty kilometers southwest of [[Sinuiju]]  a group of eight USAF [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] finds itself under attack by twelve PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagots\"'']], pilot Xizhong Ni claims the downing of one Sabre. USAF pilots Robert Fulton and Burt Phythyon each claim to have downed a MiG themselves.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 18 August 1955 \u2013 After accidentally flying above the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]], a USAF [[North American T-6 Texan|LT-6 Texan]] Trainer was downed by North Korean ground fire killing the pilot and observer on board.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 1 May 1960 \u2013 [[1960 U-2 incident|U-2 shootdown incident]]\n*[[File:Roundel of Iraq.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 16 August 1962 \u2013 two [[Turkish Air Force]] [[Republic F-84F Thunderstreak|F-84F Thunderstreaks]] shot down two [[Iraqi Air Force]] [[Ilyushin Il-28|Il-28 ''\"Beagle\"'']] bombers that crossed the Turkish border by mistake during a bombing operation against Iraqi Kurdish insurgents.\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 27 October 1962 \u2013 in the morning, a [[Lockheed U-2|U-2F]] (the third CIA U-2A, modified for air-to-air refueling) piloted by USAF Major [[Rudolf Anderson]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Pocock |first=Chris |title=50 Years of the U-2: The Complete Illustrated History of the 'Dragon Lady' |publisher=Schiffer Publishing, Ltd. |location=[[Atglen, Pennsylvania]] |lccn=2005927577 |isbn=978-0-7643-2346-1 |page=406|year=2005 }}</ref> departed its forward operating location at [[McCoy AFB]], Florida. At approximately 12:00&nbsp;pm EDT, the aircraft was struck by a [[S-75 Dvina]] ([[NATO]] designation ''[[SA-2 Guideline]]'') [[surface-to-air missile]] launched from Cuba. The aircraft was shot down, and Anderson was killed.\n*[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 28 January 1964 \u2013 [[1964 T-39 shootdown incident]]\n*[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 15 April 1969 \u2013 [[1969 EC-121 shootdown incident]]\n*[[File:Roundel of Iran.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]]'''/'''[[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 28 November 1973 \u2013 Soviet MiG-21 pilot Captain Gennadii N. Eliseev killed after [[Project Dark Gene#Detailed incident|ramming an IIAF RF-4C]] intruding into Soviet airspace on behalf of CIA Project Dark Gene, USAF Colonel John Saunders was in the rear seat. Both ejected and were captured by Soviet authorities.\n* [[File:Roundel of Iran.svg|20px|Iranian Air Force roundel]] ('''2''') 21 June 1978 \u2013 [[1978 Iranian Chinook shootdown]]\n* [[File:Roundel of Turkey.svg|20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 14 September 1983 \u2013 a pair of [[Turkish Air Force]] [[F-100F Super Sabre]] fighter jets of 182 Filo \u201cAtmaca\u201d penetrated Iraqi airspace. A [[Mirage F-1EQ]] of the Iraqi Air Force intercepted the flight and fired a [[Super 530]]F-1 missile at them. One of the Turkish fighter jets (s/n 56-3903) was shot down and crashed in [[Zakho]] valley near the Turkish-Iraqi border. The plane's pilots reportedly survived the crash and were returned to Turkey. The incident was not made public by either side, although some details surfaced in later years. The incident was revealed in 2012 by Turkish Defence Minister [[\u0130smet Y\u0131lmaz]], in response to a parliamentary question by [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP) MP Metin L\u00fctfi Baydar in the aftermath of the [[June 2012 interception of Turkish aircraft|downing of a Turkish F-4 Phantom II in Syria]], in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theaviationist.com/2012/09/06/tuaf-incidents/ |title=The Aviationist \u00bb 30 years later, Ankara admits Turkish Air Force jet was shot down by Iraq |publisher=The Aviationist |accessdate=23 December 2014|date=2012-09-06 }}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Iran.svg|20px|Iranian Air Force roundel]] ('''2''') In 1988, Soviet [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-23|MiG-23MLDs]] using [[R-23 (missile)|R-23s]] downed two Iranian [[AH-1 SuperCobra|AH-1J Cobras]] that had intruded into Afghan airspace.\n\n=== Taiwan Straits Conflicts (1950-1967) ===\n\n* [[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 29 July 1950 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire from [[Xiamen]] shoots down a [[Republic of China Air Force|RoCAF]] [[P-47N|P-47N Thunderbolt]] killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 16 June 1953 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire from [[Dongshan County|Dongshan Island]] shoots down a RoCAF [[P-47N|P-47N Thunderbolt]] killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 17 December 1953 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire in [[Zhejiang|Jejiang]] shoots down a RoCAF [[P-47N|P-47N Thunderbolt]] killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 22 May 1954 \u2013 in an engagement involving six PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagots\"'']], RoCAF pilots Chien and Yen shoot down one of the MiGs with machinegun fire from their [[Republic P-47 Thunderbolt|P-47N Thunderbolts]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 26 May 1954 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire from [[Fujian]] downs an RoCAF [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress|B-17 Flying Fortress]] with all of its four crewmen killed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 3 June 1954 \u2013 A [[Lavochkin La-11|La-11 ''\"Fang\"'']] ''of the PLAAF'' downs an RoCAF [[P-47N Thunderbolt]] killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 6 July 1954 \u2013 Cannonfire of a [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 \"Fagot\"]] ''of the PLAAF'' downs an RoCAF [[P-47N Thunderbolt]] killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 12 September 1954 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire from [[Xiamen]] downs an RoCAF PB4Y Privateer killing all nine crew.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 19 January 1955 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire downs an RoCAF [[F-84G Thunderjet]] over the PRC killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 21 January 1955 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire downs an RoCAF [[P-47N Thunderbolt]] over the PRC killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 9 February 1955 \u2013 During the evacuation of nationalist Chinese from the [[Tachen Islands|Tachen islands]] covered by aircraft launched from [[USS Wasp (CV-18)]], a USN [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|AD-5W Skyraider]] on antisubmarine patrol from VC-11 is heavily damaged by PRC Antiaircraft fire and forced to ditch at sea. its crew of three are rescued by patrol boats of the ROC.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 22 June 1955 \u2013 A [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Fresco\"'']] of the PLAAF shoots down an [[RT-33A Shooting Star|RT-33A]] of the RoCAF killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 4 July 1955 \u2013 A [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagot\"'']] among a group of four PLAAF Mikoyan is shot down in combat with four [[F-84G Thunderjet]]s of the RoCAF.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 16 July 1955 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire from [[Kinmen]] downs an RoCAF [[F-84G Thunderjet]] killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 15 October 1955 \u2013 A PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagot\"'']] is shot down by Tzu-Wan Sun of the RoCAF in his [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabre]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 14 April 1956 \u2013 A [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagot\"'']] among a group of four PLAAF Mikoyan is shot down in combat with four [[F-84G Thunderjet]]s of the RoCAF.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 22 June 1956 \u2013 A RoCAF [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress|B-17 Flying Fortress]] is shot down during a nighttime mission by cannonfire from an intercepting [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Fresco\"'']]  of the PLAAF. All eleven crew on board perish.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.utdallas.edu/library/specialcollections/hac/cataam/Leeker/history/Taiwan3.pdf|publisher=[[University of Texas at Dallas]]|title=CAT, Air Asia, Air America \u2013 the Company on Taiwan III: Work for the US Government|last=Leeker|first=Joe|date= 24 August 2015|access-date=2018-12-31}}</ref>\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 20 July 1956 \u2013 A [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagot\"'']] among a group of four PLAAF Mikoyan is shot down in combat with four [[F-84G Thunderjet]]s of the RoCAF.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 21 July 1956 \u2013 Two [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 \"Fagots\"]] among a group of three PLAAF Mikoyan are shot down by pilot I-Fang Ouyang flying among four RoCAF [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 10 November 1956 \u2013 During an airdrop over Jejigxi a [[Curtiss C-46 Commando|C-46 Commando]] of the RoCAF is shot down by a PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-19|MiG-19 ''\"Farmer\"'']] killing its nine crewmen.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 1 July 1957 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire downs an RoCAF [[P-47N Thunderbolt]] over the PRC killing its pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 18 February 1958 \u2013 A [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-15|MiG-15 ''\"Fagot\"'']] of the People's Liberation Army Naval Air Force brings down a RoCAF [[RB-57D]] above [[Shandong]] killing the pilot.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] ('''2''') 29 July 1958 \u2013 Four [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']] engaged four [[F-84G Thunderjet]]s patrolling near [[Nan'ao Island|Nan Ao Island]] resulting in the downing of two Thunderjets by pilots Gao ChangJi and Zhang YiLing of the PLAAF 54th Regiment\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''3''') 14 August 1958 \u2013 Three PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']]  are shot down by a group of four RoCAF [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]], With pilots Ping-Chun Chin and Chung-Li Li each shooting down one themselves. A third Mikoyan being brought down by two other Sabres flown by Hsien-Wu Liu and Fu-The Pan. afterwards Sabre No. 307 involved in the shootdown failed to return to base.\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 25 August 1958 \u2013 Two PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']] are engaged and shot down by RoCAF [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] piloted by Tien-En Chiang and Hsu-Hsiang Ku\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]]'''/'''[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''7''') 8 September 1958 \u2013 Seven PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']] are shot down by numerous [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] of the RoCAF. Five pilots, Ping-Chun Chin, Yi-Chien Li, Chin-Chung Liang, Chung-Tsi Yu and Wai-Ming Chu each being credited one kill, Hsien-Wu Liu downs two more himself. On the PLAAF side pilot Zhang Yi destroys one F-86 Sabre in his MiG-17 ''\"Fresco\"''\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]]'''/'''[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''6''') 18 September 1958 \u2013 Above [[Haifeng County|Haicheng]]  Guangdong Six PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']] are shot down by a number of RoCAF [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] flown by Wan-Li Lin, Yang-Chung Lu, Che-Shing Mao, Tzu-Wan Sun, Kuang-Hsing Tung and Hsin-Yeh Liu with each downing one Mikoyan. One Sabre is brought down by cannon fire from a PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Fresco\"'']] piloted by Chang Zhu You.\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''11''') 24 September 1958 \u2013 Shortly after their aircraft had been retrofitted by technicians of the United States Marine Corps to carry the [[AIM-9 Sidewinder|AIM-9B Sidewinder]] air to air missiles, Numerous missile armed RoCAF [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] took off and gave chase to a group of PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']] that had cruised above them. Due to the superior rate of climb, vertical maneuverability, thrust to weight ratio and service ceiling the Fresco pilots did not perceive any danger in doing this as they were unaware of this newly installed armament. Sabre pilots began to fire their missiles at the MiG's destroying some. Others broke into a dive and entered a horizontal turning engagement with their pursuers who held an advantage in horizontal turn-rate allowing them to engage with guns shooting down more of the PRC jets. Pilots Jing-Chuen Chen, Chun-Hsein Fu, Jie-Tsu Hsia, Shu-Yuen Li, Ta-Peng Ma, Hong-Yan Sung shot down one MiG-17 each, Yi-Chiang Chien shot down two himself and two pairs of pilots Tasi-Chuen Liu with Tang Jie-Min and Hsin-Yung Wang with Yuen-Po Wang shared in the downing of one MiG by each duo. During this engagement one further Fresco sustained notable damage being impacted by an AIM-9 that did not detonate. It escaped with an intact missile within the airframe that was extracted after returning to its base and hesitantly transferred to the Soviet Union for reverse engineering.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ewarbirds.org/missiles/aim9sidewinder.shtml|title=Raytheon AIM-9 Sidewinder|website=www.ewarbirds.org|access-date=2018-12-31}}</ref>\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 2 October 1958 \u2013 Antiaircraft fire from [[Kinmen]] knocks down a [[Curtiss C-46 Commando|C-46 Commando]] killing all five crewmen.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]]'''/'''[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''4''') 10 October 1958 \u2013 Over the PRC four RoCAF F-86F Sabre Pilots engage and shoot down four [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']] of the PLAAF, As one of the Fresco burn it explodes launching chunks of debris towards and striking one of its attackers causing heavy damage, An RoCAF pilot ejects and is captured and placed in detention until his release on 30 June 1959.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 29 May 1959 \u2013 Above [[Guangdong|Guandong]] a PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Fresco\"'']] intercepts and shoots down a RoCAF [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress|B-17 Flying Fortress]] killing all 14 on board.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 5 July 1959 \u2013 Above the Taiwan Straits twenty four PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Frescos\"'']] are engaged by four [[North American F-86 Sabre|F-86 Sabres]] of the RoCAF ending in the destruction of two Frescos.\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 7 October 1959 \u2013 Above [[Beijing]] an RoCAF [[RB-57D]] piloted by Wang Ying Chin is the first plane to ever be shot down by a surface to air missile. Chin dies after his plane was destroyed by an [[SA-2 Guideline|SA-2 ''Guideline'']] missile.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=94357|title=Accident Martin RB-57D Canberra 5643, 07 Oct 1959|last=Ranter|first=Harro|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2018-12-31}}</ref>\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 6 November 1961 \u2013 Above [[Shandong|Shantung]] province an [[RB-69|RB-69A Neptune]] is destroyed by an [[S-75 Dvina|SA-2 ''Guideline'']] missile killing all 13 aboard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 9 September 1962 \u2013 Fifteen Kilometers south of [[Nanchang|Nunchang]] an RoCAF [[Lockheed U-2|Lockheed U-2A]]  is shot down by an [[S-75 Dvina|SA-2 ''Guideline'']] missile. Pilot Chen Huai Sheng bails out and is captured after landing but dies some time later in a PRC hospital.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=82qbx2g-DQkC&pg=PA272|title=Historical Dictionary of Chinese Intelligence|last=Smith|first=Ivian C.|last2=West|first2=Nigel|date=2012|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7174-8|page=272}}</ref>\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 14 June 1963 \u2013 Above [[Nanchang]] a RoCAF [[Lockheed P-2 Neptune|RB-69A Neptune]] is shot down by 23&nbsp;mm [[Nudelman-Rikhter NR-23|NR-23]] cannon-fire from a PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17PF ''\"Fresco\"'']] killing all 14 crew aboard<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skytamer.com/MiG-17PF.html|title=Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17PF Fresco-D specifications and photos|website=www.skytamer.com|access-date=2018-12-31}}</ref>\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 1 November 1963 \u2013 Above [[Jiaxing|Jiagxi]] an [[S-75 Dvina|SA-2 ''Guideline'']] shoots down an RoCAF [[Lockheed U-2|Lockheed U-2C]]. Pilot Yeh Chang Yi was returning from an intelligence mission where he took aerial photos of [[Jiayuguan City|Jiayuguan]] missile test site and [[Lanzhou]] nuclear weapons plant. After detecting the first Guideline had been launched at him he made evasive maneuvers and avoided the first only to be struck by a second missile moments later knocking off his right wing. after bailing out and falling into captivity of the PRC he was held until 10 November 1982 when he was released into Hong Kong, He was eventually admitted into the United States after ROC officials denied his attempts to be repatriated.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\"/>\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 11 June 1964 \u2013 Near [[Yantai]] on the [[Shandong Peninsula|Shantung Peninsula]] Coordination between a [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17F ''\"Fresco\"'']] and an [[Ilyushin Il-28|Iluyshin Il-28 ''\"Beagle\"'']] of the PLAAF supports the nighttime interception of an RoCAF [[Lockheed P-2 Neptune|RB-69A Neptune]] by dropping flares to illuminate the target plane allowing the fighter to shoot it down with cannon-fire.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 7 July 1964 \u2013 Flying above Fujian, RoCAF pilot Lee Nan Lee is shot down and killed after his [[Lockheed U-2|Lockheed U-2G]] is targeted and struck by an [[S-75 Dvina|SA-2 ''Guideline'']] missile.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 18 December 1964 \u2013 Above [[Wenzhou]], an RoCAF [[RF-101A Voodoo]] piloted by Hsieh Hsiangho is shot down by a People's Liberation Army Naval Air Force [[Shenyang J-6]]. He is captured by fishermen when he ejects above the ocean and detained until July 1985.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 10 January 1965 \u2013 Southwest of Beijing, On a mission to capture aerial photos of Paotow uranium enrichment plant using an infrared camera RoCAF pilot Chang Liyi is shot down after being struck by an [[S-75 Dvina|SA-2 ''Guideline'']] missile. He survives the crash with both legs broken, Captured he is held until 10 November 1982 when released into Hong Kong. He was eventually admitted into the United States after ROC officials denied his attempts to be repatriated.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\"/>\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 18 March 1965 \u2013 Above [[Guangdong]] near [[Shantou]], a PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-19|MiG-19 ''\"Farmer\"'']] piloted by Gao Chang Ji shoots down and kills RoCAF pilot Chang Yupao flying an [[RF-101C Voodoo]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 10 January 1966 \u2013 Above Matsu, PLAAF [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-17|MiG-17 ''\"Fresco\"'']] shoots down an RoCAF [[Grumman HU-16 Albatross|HU-16 Albatross]] attempting to carry defectors to Taiwan.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*10 January 1966 \u2013 A HU-16 of the Republic of China Air Force was shot down by People's Republic of China PLAAF MiG-17 over Matsu whilst transporting defectors to Taiwan.\n*[[File:National Emblem of the Republic of China.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]]'''/'''[[File:Roundel of China.svg|25x25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 13 January 1967 \u2013 Four [[F-104G Starfighter]]s of the RoCAF are engaged by Twelve [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-19|MiG-19 ''\"Farmers\"'']] of the PLAAF. Two Farmers are claimed shot by Hu Shih-Lin and one by Bei-Puo Shih. F-104G No. 64-17779 involved in the engagement does not return and is believed to have been shot down.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== [[South African Border War]] (1966-1990) ===\n\n* [[File:Flag of UNITA.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 13 March 1976 \u2013 A [[Fokker F27 Friendship|Fokker F-27 Friendship]] parked on the ground offloading arms at [[UNITA|UNITA's]] Gago Coutinho aerodrome is caught surprised by a group of four [[Cuban Revolutionary Air and Air Defense Force|Cuban Air Force]] [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21|MiG-21 FM ''\"Fishbed\"'']]. Pilot Rafael Del Pino fires an [[S-24 rocket|S-24]] unguided rocket destroying it.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.laahs.com/the-cuban-migs/|title=The Cuban MiGs|last=Urribarres|first=Rub\u00e9n|last2=Little|first2=Mike|date=2018-04-15|website=LAAHS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Cuba.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 6 November 1981 \u2013 [[South African Air Force]] Major Johan Rankin flying a [[Mirage F1C|Mirage F-1CZ]] engaged a Cuban [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21|MiG-21 FM ''\"Fishbed\"'']] flown by Major Leonel Ponce, Downing his MiG with a burst of 30&nbsp;mm cannon.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[File:Roundel of Cuba.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] ('''2''') 5 October 1982 \u2013 Flying his [[Mirage F1C|Mirage F-1CZ]], Major Johan Rankin engages two Cuban [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21|MiG-21 FM ''\"Fishbed\"'']] flown by Lieutenants Raciel Marrero Rodr\u00edguez and Gilberto Ortiz P\u00e9rez somewhere over Angola. Rankin downs the lead MiG with 30&nbsp;mm cannon-fire followed by a lanch of a [[R.550 Magic|Matra 550]] missile taking down the wingman. Cuba contested reporting the two pilots returned to their base at [[Lubango Airport|Lubango airport]] with some battle damage.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*[[File:Roundel of Cuba.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 28 October 1987 \u2013 [[UNITA]] ground fire near Luvuei, Angola shoots down a Cuban [[MIG 21UM|MiG-21UM]] a two-seat variant of the type. both crew eject and are captured by UNITA forces.\n\n=== [[Football War]] (1969) ===\n\n*[[File:Roundel of El Salvador.svg|20x20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] ('''3''') 17 July 1969 \u2013 [[Honduran Air Force]] [[Vought F4U Corsair|Corsair]] pilots Captain Fernando and his wingman Captain Edgardo Acosta Soto engaged two [[Air Force of El Salvador|Salvadoran]] [[Cavalier Mustang|TF-51D Cavalier Mustang II]] who were attacking another Corsair while it was strafing targets south of [[Tegucigalpa]]. Soto entered a turning engagement with one mustang and blew off its left wing with three bursts of 20&nbsp;mm cannon, Killing pilot Captain Douglas Varela when his parachute did not fully deploy. Later that day the pair spotted two Salvadoran [[Vought F4U Corsair|FG-1D Goodyear Corsair.]] They jettisoned hard point stores before climbing and made a diving attack, Soto set one Corsair on fire only to find its wingman on his tail. An intense dogfight  between them ended when Soto entered a [[Split S|Split-S]] giving him a firing solution which he used to shoot down Captain Guillermo Reynaldo Cortez who died when his Corsair exploded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.airspacemag.com/history-of-flight/last-piston-engine-dogfights-180956250/|title=The Last Piston-Engine Dogfights|last=Lerner|first=Preston|website=Air & Space Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n=== [[The Troubles]] (1968\u20131998) ===\n\n* [[1978 British Army Gazelle downing|British Army Gazelle downing]] (February 17, 1978)\n* [[1990 British Army Gazelle shootdown|British Army Gazelle shootdown]] (February 11, 1990)\n* [[1994 British Army Lynx shootdown|British Army Lynx shootdown]] (March 20, 1994)\n\n===Yom Kippur War (1973)===\n* [[Ofira Air Battle]] (6 October 1973)\n* [[Air battle of Mansoura|Al Mansoura Air Battle]] (14 October 1973)\n\n===Kurdish\u2013Turkish conflict (1978\u2013present)===\n* [[File:Roundel of Turkey.svg|20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 23 February 2008 \u2013 a [[Turkish Land Forces|Turkish Army]] [[Bell AH-1 Cobra|AH-1 Cobra]] helicopter crashed with [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]] militants claiming the downing and posting a video.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iEsQsH054B0|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref> Turkey confirmed this later in the day, saying that the incident happened \"due to an unknown reason\".<ref name=\"bbcobra\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7261797.stm |publisher=BBC News |title=Turkey admits loss of helicopter |date=2008-02-24 |accessdate=27 March 2008  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080229041911/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7261797.stm |archivedate=February 29, 2008 |url-status=live |df=mdy}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Turkey.svg|20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 13 May 2016 \u2013 [[Kurdistan Workers' Party|PKK]] militants shot down a Turkish Army [[Bell AH-1 SuperCobra|AH-1W SuperCobra]] using a [[9K38 Igla]] (SA-18 Grouse) MANPADS. In the published video, the missile severed the tail section from the rest of the helicopter, causing it to spin, fragment in midair and crash, killing the two pilots on board. The Turkish government initially claimed that it fell due to technical failure, it later became obvious that it had been shot down.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cunningham |first1=Erin |title=Kurdish militants reportedly shoot down Turkish security forces helicopter |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/05/14/kurdish-militants-just-challenged-turkish-air-power-in-a-major-way/ |accessdate=May 20, 2019 |date=May 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===[[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] (1979\u20131989)===\n{{Main|List of Soviet aircraft losses in Afghanistan}}\n\n===[[Iran\u2013Iraq War]] (1980\u20131988)===\n* [[File:Roundel of Iran.svg|20px|Iranian Air Force roundel]] 20 February 1986 \u2013 [[Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force|Iranian Air Force]] [[Fokker F27 Friendship]] [[Abdolbaghi Darvish#End of life|shot down]] by an Iraqi Air Force [[MiG-23]] and all 49 crew and passengers were killed.\n\n===Falklands War (1982)===\n* [[1982 British Army Gazelle friendly fire incident|British Army Gazelle friendly fire incident]] (June 6, 1982)\n* [[Argentine air forces in the Falklands War|Argentine air forces shot down in the Falklands War]] (1982)\n\n===Libyan Gulf of Sidra territorial water dispute===\n* [[File:Roundel of Libya (1977\u20132011).svg|20px|Libyan Air Force]] ('''2''') 19 August 1981 \u2013 [[Gulf of Sidra incident (1981)]]\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 15 April 1986 \u2013 One [[General Dynamics F-111 Aardvark|F-111F]] of the [[48th Fighter Wing]] of the [[United States Air Force]] was shot down over [[History of Libya under Muammar Gaddafi|Libya]] by ground fire during the [[1986 United States bombing of Libya]].<ref name=AF_mag_El_Dorado>[[Walter J. Boyne|Boyne, Walter J.]] [http://www.airforce-magazine.com/MagazineArchive/Pages/1999/March%201999/0399canyon.aspx \"El Dorado Canyon\"]. ''Air Force Magazine'', March 1999.</ref> [[1986 United States bombing of Libya]]\n* [[File:Roundel of Libya (1977\u20132011).svg|20px|Libyan Air Force]] ('''2''') 4 January 1989 [[1989 air battle near Tobruk]]\n\n===Nagorno-Karabakh War (1988\u20131994)===\n* [[File:Roundel of Azerbaijan.svg|20px|Roundel of Azerbaijani Air Force]]  20 November 1991 \u2013 [[1991 Azerbaijani Mil Mi-8 shootdown|Azerbaijani Mil Mi-8 shootdown]]\n* [[File:Roundel of Iran.svg|20px|Iranian Air Force roundel]]  17 March 1994 \u2013 [[1994 Iranian Air Force C-130 shootdown|Iranian Air Force C-130 shootdown]]\n* [[File:Roundel of Armenia.svg|20px|Armenian Air Force]] 12 November 2014 \u2013 [[2014 Armenian Mil Mi-24 shootdown]]\n* [[File:Roundel of Azerbaijan.svg|20px|Roundel of Azerbaijani Air Force]]  2 April 2016 \u2013 during a [[2016 Nagorno-Karabakh clashes|clash between Azerbaijani and Armenian forces]], an Azerbaijani Mil Mi-24 helicopter was shot down by [[Republic of Artsakh|Artsakh Republic]] forces. The downing was confirmed by the Azerbaijani defense ministry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/nation/94597.html|title=Azerbaijani armed forces destroy 10 Armenian tanks and servicemen-UPDATE|date=3 April 2016|website=AzerNews.az|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://armenpress.am/eng/news/844717/nkr-defense-army-releases-fresh-data-on-downed-azerbaijani-helicopter.html|title=NKR Defense Army releases fresh data on downed Azerbaijani helicopter|website=armenpress.am|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"wsjapril2\">{{cite news|last1=Hodge|first1=Nathan|title=A Dozen Dead in Heavy Fighting Reported in Nagorno-Karabakh|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/heavy-fighting-reported-in-nagorno-karabakh-1459597114|accessdate=2 April 2016|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=April 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=By aida sultanova, associated press |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/armenia-heavy-fighting-nagorno-karabakh-helicopter-hit-38102214 |title=Azerbaijan Says 12 of Its Soldiers Killed in Fighting |publisher=ABC News |date= |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>\n\n===Gulf War (1990\u20131991)===\n{{See also|Air engagements of the Gulf War}}\n*\nUSAF F-15C vs. IRAF MiG-29\n\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF Mirage F1s\nLater on the same night, an F-15C scored a double-kill against two Mirages with AIM-7 Sparrow missile. His wingman scored another kill on a third Mirage F1, for a total of three kills in the dogfight.\n\nUSN F/A-18s vs. IRAF MiG-25s\nOn the first night of the war, two F/A-18s from the carrier USS Saratoga were flying outside of Baghdad when two Iraqi MiG-25PDs interceptors from the 96th Squadron engaged them. In the beyond-visual-range (BVR), one of the Iraqi MiGs, piloted by Lieutenant Colonel Zuhair Dawood, fired an R-40 missile, shooting down one of the F/A-18's as it was travelling Mach 0.92. The pilot, Lieutenant Commander [[Scott Speicher]], was killed. It is widely believed he died upon the impact of the missile.\n\nUSN F/A-18s vs. IRAF MiG-21s\nTwo F/A-18s from VFA-81 shot down two Iraqi MiG-21s, one with an AIM-7 Sparrow missile and one with an AIM-9 Sidewinder missile, in a brief dogfight with their bombs still latched on.\n\nUSAF F-15Es vs IRAF MiG-29s\nOn the opening night of the war two Iraqi MiG-29s attempted to engage a flight of USAF F-15Es. One of the MiGs crashed while flying at low altitude but the other MiG pressed on. One of the F-15Es fired an AIM-9 Sidewinder when the MiG locked him up but missed. Several other F-15Es simultaneously tried to engage the lone MiG-29 but were unable to get the kill. One F-15E was actually flying past the Iraqi jet and maneuvered in for the kill but the pilot hesitated to take the shot because he was unsure of his wingmen's location and because he did not get a good tone with the Sidewinder missile.\n\nUSAF EF-111 vs. IRAF Mirage F-1\nOn the first night of the war a USAF EF-111A Raven \"Spark Vark\", flown by pilot Captain James Denton and Electronic Warfare Officer (EWO) Captain Brent Brandon, was on an electronic warfare mission ahead of a group of jets on a bombing run. Several IRAF Dassault Mirage F1s came in and engaged the flight. One of them went after the unarmed EF-111. Denton executed a tight turn while Brandon launched chaff to avoid missiles fired by the Mirage. An F-15C on the same flight, piloted by Robert Graeter, went after the Mirage to protect the EF-111. The Mirage launched a missile, spotted by Brandon, which the Raven avoided by turning and launching chaff. Denton decided to head for the deck to try to evade his pursuer. As he went down he pulled up to avoid the ground, the Mirage followed him through, but did not pull up in time and crashed. An unarmed EF-111 had thus scored an air-air victory against a Dassault Mirage F1, although Graeter was credited with a kill. The EF-111A crew were awarded the Distinguished Flying Cross.\n\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF MiG-25s\nTwo IRAF MiG-25s fired missiles at a group of F-15Cs escorting a bombing run in Iraq (which were evaded by the F-15s). The F-15Cs gave chase, but were forced to give up when the MiGs outran them. A total of 10 missiles were fired at the MiGs.\n\nUSAF F-111s vs. IRAF MiG-23\nAn Iraqi MiG-23 fired a R-24T missile at a F-111 on a bombing run and scored a hit, although the bomber made it safely back to base. Another similar incident occurred with the same Iraqi interceptor several minutes later, this F-111 also made it back to base despite the severe damage to the aircraft. This is Iraq's only success of the Persian Gulf War using MiG-23s.\n\nIRAF MiG-29 vs USAF F-111 and B-52G\nAn Iraqi MiG-29 struck an F-111 aircraft with an R60 missile, though the sturdy F-111 stayed airworthy. Several minutes later the same pilot fired a R27 missile at a B-52G on a bombing run, severely damaging it.\n\n19 January 1991\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF MiG-25s\nIn a brief dogfight, two F-15Cs engaged and shot down two Iraqi MiG-25s attempting to engage them, both using AIM-7 missiles. One was destroyed by Captain Rick Tuleni and the second by Captain Larry Pitts.\n\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF MiG-29s\nTwo F-15Cs, piloted by Captains Craig Underhill and Cesar Rodriguez gave chase to a pair of MiG-29s detected by AWACS. The Iraqi aircraft, one piloted by Captain Jameel Sayhood, promptly turned and engaged the two American fighters, and one of the most dramatic dogfights of the Persian Gulf War ensued. The two MiGs and F-15s flew straight at each other, each attempting to visually identify the other. Underhill was facing Sayhood's wingman, while Sayhood himself was facing Rodriguez. Underhill fired an AIM-7 at Sayhood's wingman, scoring a head-on hit and killing the opposing pilot instantly. Simultaneously, Sayhood gained a lock on Rodriguez, throwing him onto the defensive. Rodriguez dove to low altitude in order to clutter Sayhood's radar and break the lock-on, and dropped flares to counter his adversary's infra-red search-and-track. However, after seeing his wingman shot down, Sayhood disengaged and fled to the north. Considering the engagement over, Rodriguez and Underhill turned south to rendezvous with a KC-135 tanker in order to refuel, but Sayhood reversed course and set off after them, prompting them to reengage. With the now lone MiG-29 closing head-on with the pair of F-15s, Underhill gained radar lock-on, but did not fire due to a glitch in his IFF interrogator system keeping him from being certain he wasn't about to shoot down a Coalition aircraft. Underhill initially thought he shot down an allied aircraft. Sayhood sliced into the American formation, causing a classic merge. Underhill kept Sayhood locked-on and climbed, while Rodriguez committed to the merge in order to visually identify the opposing aircraft as hostile. As they passed head-on, Rodriguez identified it as an Iraqi, and each pilot turned left to engage the other. Sayhood was relying on his MiG's better turning radius to get into a firing position on Rodriguez' tail but Rodriguez was very close to firing position on him. Both aircraft lost altitude through the sustained hard turning, bringing them perilously close to the ground. Fearing that Rodriguez would obtain infra-red lock-on and shoot him down with an AIM-9, Sayhood attempted to disengage using a split-s. Rodriguez didn't match Sayhood's manoeuver, and observed him eject just prior to his MiG impacting the ground \u2013 he'd commenced his escape maneuver too low. It was reported years later by Iraqi sources that the Captain was rescued by some farmers after he broke his leg and evacuated to a local hospital.\n\nRAF Tornado GR.1 vs. IRAF MiG-29\nIt has been claimed by some sources that an RAF Tornado (ZA467) crewed by Squadron Leader Gary Lennox and Squadron Leader Adrian Weeks was shot down on 19 January by an R-60MK (NATO reporting name: AA-8 Aphid) missile fired from an Iraqi MiG-29 piloted by Jameel Sayhood, however this aircraft is officially recorded as having crashed on 22 January on a mission to Ar Rutbah.\n\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF Mirage F1s\nTwo F-15Cs destroyed two Mirage F1s with AIM-7 missiles.\n\n24 January 1991\nRSAF F-15C vs. IRAF Mirage F1s\nThe Iraqi Air Force attempted to mount a rare offensive bombing operation and loaded two F1s with incendiary bombs. The Royal Saudi Air Force sent up two F-15Cs to intercept the bombers. One of the F-15s piloted by Captain Ayedh Al-Shamrani maneuvered behind the F1s and shot them both down with AIM-9 missiles.\n\n26 January 1991\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF MiG-23s\nIn what is considered a textbook \"beyond visual range\" or BVR kill, four MiG-23s took off from an Iraqi airbase. One of them turned back with mechanical problems, however the other three pressed on. Four F-15Cs were flying when AWACS reported the MiGs. The four F-15s lined up, were assigned targets and fired AIM-7 missiles at all of them, destroying all three MiGs within seconds of each other. Only three of the F-15C pilots were granted kills, as the fourth missile didn't reach the MiG until after it had already been brought down.\n\n27 January 1991\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF MiG-23s and Mirage F1\nTwo F-15Cs managed to get kills on three MiG-23s and one Mirage F1, after they caught them trying to flee to Iran. They were brought down with AIM-9 and AIM-7 missiles after a brief dogfight.\n\n29 January 1991\nUSAF F-15C vs. IRAF MiG-23\nAn American F-15C shot down a MiG-23 fleeing to Iran with an AIM-7 missile.\n\nUSAF F-15C vs. IRAF MiG-23\nA USAF F-15C eliminates an Iraqi MiG-23 in a short-lived dogfight with an AIM-7 missile.\n\n2 February 1991\nUSAF F-15C vs. IRAF IL-76\nAn F-15C kills an Iraqi transport, an IL-76, that was parked by strafing it with 20&nbsp;mm bullets.\n\n6 February 1991\nUSAF F-15C vs. IRAF MiG-21s\nA lone F-15C takes down two Iraqi MiG-21s with AIM-7 missiles after they both engage him. These MiGs were escorting the Su-25s mentioned below.\n\nUSAF F-15C vs. IRAF Su-25s\nA F-15C spots two Iraqi Su-25s and gives chase, locking on, and shooting down both planes with AIM-9 missiles.\n\nUSAF A-10A vs. IRAF Bo-105\nA USAF A-10 ground attack aircraft, shoots down an Iraqi Bo-105 helicopter using its GAU-8 30&nbsp;mm cannon.\n\n7 February 1991\nUSN F-14 vs. IRAF Mi-8\nA USN F-14 shoots down an IRAF Mi-8 helicopter with an AIM-9 missile. It is the last USN F-14 air-to-air kill.\n\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF Su-22s and Su-7\nTwo USAF F-15Cs shoot down two IRAF Su-22s and one Su-7 as they attempt to flee Iraq. All with AIM-7 missiles.\n\nUSAF F-15C vs. IRAF Mil-24\nA F-15C shoots down an IRAF Mi-24 with an AIM-7 missile.\n\n11 February 1991\nUSAF F-15Cs vs. IRAF helicopters\nTwo F-15Cs shoot down two unidentified Iraqi helicopters by using AIM-7 missiles for both.\n\n14 February 1991\nUSAF F-15E vs. IRAF Hughes 500\nAn F-15E Strike Eagle fighter/bomber dropped a laser-guided bomb onto a Hughes 500 helicopter in the air. The helicopter was on the ground initially loading up commandos, though it took off. Even with it taking off they left the laser on it and the bomb hit it when it was \"200 or so\" feet in the air. A special forces team on the ground witnessed the event.\n\n15 February 1991\nUSAF A-10A vs. IRAF Mi-8\nAn A-10A ground attack aircraft shoots down an Iraqi Mi-8 helicopter with its GAU-8 30&nbsp;mm cannon.\n\n===Iraqi no-fly zones (1991\u20132003)===\n* [[File:Roundel of Iraq.svg|24px|Iraqi Air Force Roundel]] 20 March 1991 \u2013 USAF F-15C vs. IRAF Su-22 \u2013 In accordance with the ceasefire, an F-15C shoots down an Iraqi Su-22 bomber with an AIM-9 missile.\n* [[File:Roundel of Iraq.svg|24px|Iraqi Air Force Roundel]]27 December 1992 \u2013 USAF F-16 vs. IRAF MiG-25 \u2013 A MiG-25 crossed the no-fly zone and an F-16D shot it down with an AIM-120 AMRAAM missile. It is the first kill with an AIM-120, and also the first USAF F-16 kill.\n* [[File:Roundel of Iraq.svg|24px|Iraqi Air Force Roundel]] 17 January 1993 \u2013 USAF F-16 vs. IRAF MiG-23 \u2013 A USAF F-16C shoots down a MiG-23 when the MiG locks the F-16 up.\n* 17 January 1993 \u2013 USAF F-16s vs. IRAF Su-22s \u2013 Two IRAF Su-22 \"Fitters\" open fire on two USAF F-16s in protest of the no-fly zones. No aircraft are damaged in the encounter.\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] ('''2''') 14 April 1994 \u2013 [[1994 Black Hawk shootdown incident|UH-60 Black Hawk friendly fire shootdown incident]]\n* 5 January 1999 \u2013 USAF F-15Cs and USN F-14Ds vs. IRAF MiG-25s \u2013 A group of four Iraqi MiG-25s crossed the no-fly zones and sparked a dogfight with two patrolling F-15Cs and two patrolling F-14Ds. A total of six missiles were fired at the MiGs, none of which hit them. The MiGs then bugged out.\n* 9 September 1999 \u2013 USN F-14 vs IRAF MiG-23 \u2013 A lone MiG-23 crossed the no-fly zone heading towards a flight of F-14s. One F-14 fired an AIM-54 Phoenix at the MiG but missed and the MiG headed back north.\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 23 December 2002 \u2013 USAF RQ-1 Predator vs. IRAF MiG-25 \u2013 In what was the last aerial victory for the Iraqi Air Force before [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]], an Iraqi MiG-25 shot down an American UAV RQ-1 Predator after the drone opened fire on the Iraqi aircraft with a [[FIM-92 Stinger|Stinger missile]].\n\n===Croatian War of Independence (1991\u20131995)===\n* [[1992 European Community Monitor Mission helicopter downing]] (January 7, 1992)\n\n===Bosnian War (1992\u20131995)===\n* [[File:Roundel of Italy \u2013 Low Visibility \u2013 Type 1.svg|24px|Italian Air Force Roundel]] 3 September 1992 \u2013 An [[Italian Air Force]] (''Aeronautica Militare Italiana'') [[Aeritalia G.222|G.222]] was shot down when approaching Sarajevo airfield, while conducting a United Nations relief mission. It crashed {{convert|18|mi|km}} from the airfield; a NATO rescue mission was aborted when 2 USMC CH-53 helicopters came under small arms fire. The cause of the crash was determined to be a surface-to-air missile, but it was not clear who fired it. Everyone on board \u2013 four Italian crew members and four French passengers \u2013 died in the crash.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sudetic |first=Chuck |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/04/world/un-relief-plane-reported-downed-on-bosnia-mission.html?pagewanted=all |title=U.N. Relief Plane Reported Downed on Bosnia Mission |work=The New York Times |date=1992-09-04 |accessdate=2009-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/un-fears-aid-aircraft-was-shot-down-by-missile-1549141.html |title=UN fears aid aircraft was shot down by missile |work=The Independent |date=1992-09-04 |accessdate=2009-10-05 |location=London |first1=Robert |last1=Fisk}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Yugoslavia 1992-2003.svg|24px|Serbia and Montenegro (FR Yugoslavia) Roundel]] ('''5''') 28 February 1994 \u2013 [[Banja Luka incident]]\n* [[File:RAF Lowvis Army roundel.svg|24px|RAF Roundel]] 16 April 1994 \u2013 A [[Sea Harrier]] of the [[801 Naval Air Squadron]], operating from the aircraft carrier [[HMS Ark Royal (R07)|HMS ''Ark Royal'']], was brought down by a [[Igla-1]] surface-to-air missile<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3146139.stm|title=Igla missile's potent force|date=13 August 2003|publisher=|accessdate=20 May 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> fired by the [[Army of Republika Srpska]] while attempting to bomb two Bosnian Serb tanks over [[Gora\u017ede|Gorazde]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-85169622.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104002521/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-85169622.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2012 |title=Plus ca change ..? NATO aircraft are still particularly vulnerable to attack from certain forms of guided missiles |first=Nick |last=Cook |publisher=Interavia Business & Technology |via=[[HighBeam Research]] {{Subscription required}}|date=1 March 2002}}</ref> The pilot, Lieutenant Nick Richardson, ejected and landed in territory controlled by friendly [[Bosniaks|Bosnian Muslims]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PG&p_theme=pg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADEFB3DD0502E7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Downed British Jet's Pilot Rescued in Bosnia |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=17 April 1994}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]] 2 June 1995 \u2013 [[Mrkonji\u0107 Grad incident]]\n* [[File:Roundel of France.svg|20px|French Air Force Roundel]] 30 August 1995 \u2013 one [[French Air Force]] [[Dassault Mirage 2000N/2000D|Mirage 2000N-K2]] was shot down over Bosnia by a MANPADS heat-seeking [[9K38 Igla]] missile fired by air defence units of [[Army of Republika Srpska]] during operation [[Deliberate Force]]. Both pilots were captured by Serbian forces.<ref>{{cite web|author=ROGER COHENPublished: 11 December 1995 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/11/world/french-deadline-passes-with-no-word-from-serbs-on-pilots.html |title=French Deadline Passes With No Word From Serbs on Pilots |work=The New York Times |date=11 December 1995}}</ref>\n\n===United Nations Operation in Somalia (1992\u20131995)===\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|25px|Roundel of the USAF]]('''2''') 3 October 1993 \u2013 [[Battle of Mogadishu (1993)]]\n\n===Aegean dispute===\n* [[File:Roundel of Turkey.svg|20px|Roundel of Turkey.svg]] 8 October 1996 \u2013 7 months after the escalation of the dispute with Turkey over the [[Imia/Kardak]] islands, a Greek [[Mirage 2000]] fired an [[R.550 Magic]] II missile and shot down a Turkish F-16D<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4362620.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104212512/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4362620.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2012 |title=Turkish F-16 jet crashes after Greek interception |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|date=9 October 1996 |publisher=High beam}}.</ref> over the [[Aegean Sea]]. The Turkish pilot died, while the co-pilot ejected and was rescued by Greek forces.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://f-16.net/ |contribution-url=http://www.f-16.net/f-16_fighting_falcon_airframe-3371.html |publisher=F-16 |title=Aircraft Database |type=airframe details |contribution=91-0023 |accessdate=18 May 2008}}.</ref> In August 2012, after [[Turkish-Syrian relations#Friction due to Syrian civil war|the downing of a RF-4E]] on the Syrian Coast, Turkish Defence Minister \u0130smet Y\u0131lmaz confirmed that the Turkish F-16D was shot down by a Greek [[Dassault Mirage 2000|Mirage 2000]] with an R.550 Magic II in 1996 after reportedly violating Greek airspace near [[Chios]] island.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tuaf incidents |url=http://theaviationist.com/2012/09/06/tuaf-incidents/ |publisher=The Avionist|date=Sep 6, 2012}}</ref> Greece denies that the F-16 was shot down.<ref>https://www.rt.com/news/343467-turkey-greek-pilot-sentence/  Athens also denies the downing of the jet, and says that Turkish pilot reported a control failure. It also claims that the jet violated Greece's airspace because one of the Turkish pilots was rescued in the Greek flight information region.</ref> Both [[Mirage 2000]] pilots reported that the [[F-16]] caught fire and they saw one [[parachute]].<ref>http://www.newsbomb.gr/ellada/ethnika/story/697371/katarripsi-toyrkikoy-f-16-ti-dilose-o-ellinas-pilotos Greek TV: Pilot reports after the crash. Both reports were sent to Ankara.</ref>\n\n===NATO bombing of Yugoslavia (1999)===\n* [[File:Roundel of Yugoslavia 1992-2003.svg|24px|Serbia and Montenegro (FR Yugoslavia) Roundel]] ('''2''') 24 March 1999 \u2013 two [[Air Force of Serbia and Montenegro|Yugoslav Air Force]] [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]] were shot down by two USAF [[F-15]]C with AMRAAM missiles.<ref>{{Cite report |url=https://media.defense.gov/2016/Mar/17/2001481638/-1/-1/0/PAGES%20FROM%20AIR_POWER_HISTORY_SUMMER-2015.PDF |title=The U.S. Air Force in the Air War Over Serbia, 1999 |last=Haulman |first=Daniel |date=Summer 2015 |work=Air Power}}</ref> Different sources claim one of the MiG-29 was downed by friendly ground fire.\n* [[File:Roundel of Yugoslavia 1992-2003.svg|24px|Serbia and Montenegro (FR Yugoslavia) Roundel]] 24 March 1999 \u2013 During [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|Operation Allied Force]], Dutch [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16AM]] J-063 flown by Major Peter Tankink shot down one Yugoslavian [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]], flown by Lt. Colonel Milutinovic, with an [[AMRAAM]] missile. The pilot of the stricken jet ejected safely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ejection-history.org.uk/Aircraft_by_Type/mig-29.htm|title=MiG-29|publisher=ejection-history.org.uk|accessdate=16 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017035011/http://www.ejection-history.org.uk/Aircraft_by_Type/mig-29.htm|archive-date=2007-10-17|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_380.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214094718/http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_380.shtml|title=Yugoslav & Serbian MiG-29s|publisher=acig.org|date=30 November 2003|accessdate=17 February 2016|archivedate=14 February 2014}}</ref> This marked the first air-to-air kill made by a Dutch fighter since WW2.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Debi|url=http://www.f-16.net/f-16-news-article4892.html|title=ENJJPT Star Awarded to Dutch Pilot|publisher=f-16.net|date=17 September 2014|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Yugoslavia 1992-2003.svg|24px|Serbia and Montenegro (FR Yugoslavia) Roundel]] ('''2''') 26 March 1999 \u2013 two Yugoslavian [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]] were shot down by two USAF [[F-15]]C with AMRAAM missiles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/WORLD/europe/9903/27/nato.strike.03/|title=CNN - Downed NATO pilot rescued, U.S. officials say - March 27, 1999|website=edition.cnn.com|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] 27 March 1999 \u2013 [[1999 F-117A shoot-down]] An American F-117A Nighthawk stealth bomber was shot down over Belgrade by a Soviet made S-125E. The pilot ejected safely and the plane's wreckage was recovered by Serbian special forces.\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] 2 May 1999 \u2013 a USAF [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16CG]] was shot down over Serbia. It was downed by an [[S-125]] ''Neva'' SAM (NATO: SA-3) near Nakucani. Its pilot; Lt. Col [[David L. Goldfein|David Goldfein]], [[555th Fighter Squadron]] commander, managed to eject and was later rescued by a [[Search and rescue|combat search-and-rescue]] (CSAR) mission.<ref name=\"holloman\">Roberts, Chris. [http://www.f-16.net/news_article2167.html \"Holloman commander recalls being shot down in Serbia\"]. F-16.net, 7 February 2007. Retrieved: 16 May 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.f-16.net/f-16_fighting_falcon_airframe-2787.html \"F-16 Aircraft Database: F-16 Airframe Details for 88-0550\"]. '-16.net. Retrieved: 16 May 2008.</ref> The remains of this aircraft are on display in the [[Museum of Aviation in Belgrade|Yugoslav Aeronautical Museum]], [[Belgrade International Airport]].\n* [[File:Roundel of Yugoslavia 1992-2003.svg|24px|Serbia and Montenegro (FR Yugoslavia) Roundel]] 4 May 1999 \u2013 A lone Yugoslav [[MiG-29]] flown by Lt. Col. [[Milenko Pavlovi\u0107]] attempted to intercept a large NATO formation that was returning to base having just bombed [[Valjevo]] (the pilot's home town). It was engaged by a pair of USAF F-16CJs from the 78th Fighter Squadron<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_380.shtml Yugoslav & Serbian MiG-29s<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214094718/http://www.acig.org/artman/publish/article_380.shtml |date=February 14, 2014 }}</ref> and shot down with AIM-120,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f-16.net/aircraft-database/F-16/airframe-profile/3396|title=Airframe Details for F-16 #91-0353|publisher=f-16.net|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> killing the pilot with the falling wreckage also being hit by a [[Strela 2]]M fired by the Yugoslav army in error.\n\n===India\u2013Pakistan military confrontation (1999 and 2019)===\n{{See also|Operation Safed Sagar|2019 Jammu and Kashmir airstrikes}}\n* [[File:Roundel of India.svg|24px|Indian Air Force Roundel]] 27 May 1999 \u2013 During the [[Kargil War]] in the [[Kashmir]] region, one [[Indian Air Force]] [[Mikoyan MiG-27|MiG-27]] was lost to an engine problem.<ref>https://theprint.in/opinion/kargils-little-known-fact-how-iaf-used-helicopters-to-target-intruders-at-high-altitudes/263391/</ref> Its wingman, flying in a [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21|MiG-21]] was shot down by a [[MANPADS]] while trying to locate the downed MiG-27 pilot.<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/kargil-99.htm \"1999 Kargil Conflict\"]. ''GlobalSecurity.org''. Retrieved 18 October 2009.</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of India.svg|24px|Indian Air Force Roundel]] 28 May 1999 - An Indian Air Force strike formation composed by four [[Mil Mi-17|Mi-17]] helicopters came under fire by [[MANPADS]], one was hit and shot down, killing all four onboard.<ref>https://theprint.in/opinion/kargils-little-known-fact-how-iaf-used-helicopters-to-target-intruders-at-high-altitudes/263391/</ref><ref>http://bharat-rakshak.com/IAF/History/Kargil/1055-VedShenag.html</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Pakistan \u2013 Naval Aviation.svg|24px|Pakistan Naval Air Arm Roundel]] 10 August 1999 \u2013 [[Pakistan Naval Air Arm Atlantique shootdown]].The Atlantique plane was shot down by an IAF [[MiG-21]] using a [[R-60 (missile)|R-60]] infrared homing missile. \n* [[File:Roundel of India.svg|24px|Indian Air Force Roundel]] 27 February 2019 \u2013 India confirmed that it lost one [[Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21|MiG-21]] in [[2019 Jammu and Kashmir airstrikes|an air skirmish]] with the [[Pakistan Air Force]] (PAF).<ref>{{cite web|last=Biswas|first=Soutik|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-47414490|title=Narendra Modi v Imran Khan: Who won the war of perception?|date=1 March 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2019-05-24}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of India.svg|24px|Indian Air Force Roundel]] 27 February 2019 \u2013 a [[Mil Mi-17|Mi-17 V5]] of the Indian Air Force (IAF) was shot down as result of [[friendly-fire]] by an Indian owned Israeli-manufactured [[SPYDER]] air defense system killing six on board and one civilian on ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indian-air-force-budgam-chopper-crash-friendly-fire-officers-guilty-1590764-2019-08-23|title=Indian Air Force probe finds friendly fire caused February 27 Budgam chopper crash, 5 officers in dock|date=23 August 2019|website=[[India Today]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprint.in/defence/iaf-probe-confirms-27-february-budgam-chopper-crash-was-caused-by-friendly-fire/280553/|title=IAF probe confirms 27 February Budgam chopper crash was caused by friendly fire|website=ThePrint|date=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Second Chechen War (1999\u20132009)===\n{{Main|List of Russian aircraft losses in the Second Chechen War}}\n* [[2002 Khankala Mi-26 crash|Khankala Mi-26 shootdown]] (August 19, 2002)\n\n===War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)===\n{{Main|List of Coalition aircraft losses in Afghanistan}}\n\n===Iraq War (2003\u20132011)===\n{{Main|List of aviation shootdowns and accidents during the Iraq War}}\n\n'''Shootdowns in 2003'''\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] [[United States Army Aviation Branch|United States Army Aviation]] \u2013 23 March 2003: [[Boeing AH-64 Apache#AH-64D|AH-64D Apache]] 85-25407 from C Company, [[1st Battalion, 227th Aviation Regiment (United States)|1st Battalion, 227th Aviation Regiment]], 4th BCT, [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] was shot down during attack on the [[Republican Guard (Iraq)|Iraqi Republican Guard]]. The two pilots were taken prisoner.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.people.com.cn/200304/03/eng20030403_114518.shtml|title=Iraq Shot down US F/A-18 Hornet, Black Hawk Helicopter|work=People's Daily|date=23 March 2003|accessdate=30 January 2009}}</ref> The helicopter was supposedly destroyed by Coalition forces, but Iraqi TV showed an AH-64 being taken to Baghdad on a low loader.<ref>{{cite web|title=1999 USAF Serial Numbers|url=http://www.joebaugher.com/usaf_serials/1999.html|publisher=Joe Baugher|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:RAF Lowvis Army roundel.svg|24px|RAF Roundel]] [[Royal Air Force]] \u2013 23 March 2003: [[RAF Tornado GR4|Tornado GR.4A]] ZG710 'D' of [[No. XIII Squadron RAF|13 Squadron]] was shot down by a US [[Patriot missile]] in a friendly fire incident, killing the pilot and navigator, both from [[No. IX Squadron RAF|9 Squadron]]. The aircraft's electronic signature was not recognized by the Patriot's [[identification friend or foe]] system, resulting in the shootdown.<ref name=autogenerated9 />\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 2 April 2003: [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk#Variants|UH-60L Black Hawk]] 94-26557 from B Company, 2nd Battalion, [[3rd Aviation Regiment (United States)|3rd Aviation Regiment]], 3rd [[Combat Aviation Brigade|CAB]], [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Infantry Division]] was shot down near [[Karbala]], killing 7 soldiers and injuring 4 more.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.people.com.cn/200304/03/eng20030403_114518.shtml|work=People's Daily|date=3 April 2003|accessdate=1 December 2007|title=Iraq Shot down US F/A-18 Hornet, Black Hawk Helicopter}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Navy \u2013 2 April 2003: F/A-18C Block 46 Hornet 164974 of [[VFA-195]] was shot down by either a US Patriot missile or an Iraqi missile at which the patriot missile was launched in a possible friendly fire incident, killing the pilot.<ref name=autogenerated9>{{cite news|url=http://www.pugwashgroup.ca/events/documents/2004/2004.04.29-Buckley.Dorn_open.letter.htm|title=Open Letter to Canadian Ministers|author=Canadian Pugwash Group|date=26 April 2004|accessdate=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113195624/http://www.pugwashgroup.ca/events/documents/2004/2004.04.29-Buckley.Dorn_open.letter.htm|archive-date=13 January 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/15/national/15friendly.html|title=A Trail of Pain From a Botched Attack in Iraq in 2003|newspaper=The New York Times|author=James Dao|date=15 April 2003|accessdate=3 February 2009}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Air Force \u2013 8 April 2003: [[A-10 Thunderbolt II|A-10A]] 78-0691 of 124th Wing/190th FS shot down by an Iraqi [[Roland (air defence)|Roland]] surface to air missile; the pilot survived and was rescued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://klu.tigerteam-security.net/topicsIraqifreedom.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419043803/http://klu.tigerteam-security.net/topicsIraqifreedom.htm|archivedate=2008-04-19|title=Operation Iraqi Freedom}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|BGR}} Civil operator \u2013 21 April 2003: A [[Bulgaria]]n [[Mil Mi-8]] is shot down north of Baghdad, killing the 11 civilians on board. Casualties consisted of six American contractors, three Bulgarian pilots \u2013 one of whom is executed shortly after the crash \u2013 and two Fijian gunners.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/4468959.stm|title=Helicopter shot down near Baghdad|publisher=BBC News|date=21 April 2005|accessdate=8 June 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/archive/2005/04/2008410112348925325.html|title=Bulgarian helicopter shot down in Iraq|publisher=Al Jazeera |date=24 April 2005|accessdate=1 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=11 killed as civilian helicopter is shot down in Iraq|work=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/Iraq/Story/0,,1466275,00.html|author=Rory Carroll|date=22 April 2005|accessdate=4 February 2008 | location=London|author-link=Rory Carroll}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 12 June 2003: An [[Boeing AH-64 Apache#AH-64D|AH-64D Apache]] of [[101st Combat Aviation Brigade|101st Aviation Brigade]], [[101st Airborne Division]] was shot down near Duluiyah, north of [[Baghdad]], both crewmembers survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/iraq/2003/06/iraq-030613-rfel-063358.htm|title=Iraq: U.S. Central Command Says Apache Was Downed By Hostile Fire}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Boeing AH-64 Apache|url=http://www.militaryaviation.eu/helicopter/Boeing/AH-64.htm|publisher=Military Aviation|accessdate=25 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304212410/http://www.militaryaviation.eu/helicopter/Boeing/AH-64.htm|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 25 October 2003: [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk#Variants|UH-60L Black Hawk]] 96-26653 From B company, 3rd Battalion, [[158th Aviation Regiment|158 Aviation Regiment]] of the [[12th Combat Aviation Brigade|12th Aviation BDE]] crashes and burns out after being hit by an [[9K32 Strela-2|SA-7 missile]] near [[Tikrit]], 1 soldier injured.<ref name=autogenerated10>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2004-01-08-helicopter-list_x.htm|title=Helicopters shot down or crashed in Iraq | work=USA Today | date=13 January 2004 | accessdate=8 May 2010|quote=A rocket-propelled grenade forces down a Black Hawk north of Baghdad, and five soldiers are injured.}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 2 November 2003: [[Boeing CH-47 Chinook#CH-47D|CH-47D Chinook]] 91-0230 of Detachment 1, F Company, 106th Aviation Brigade shot down with an [[9K32 Strela-2|SA-7 missile]] near [[Fallujah]]; 16 soldiers killed, 26 wounded.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/11/02/sprj.irq.main/index.html\n |title=Helicopter crash kills 16 soldiers headed for leave\n |publisher=CNN\n |date=3 November 2007\n |accessdate=8 June 2007\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224020929/http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/11/02/sprj.irq.main/index.html\n |archivedate=24 December 2007\n |url-status=dead\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/meast/11/02/sprj.irq.int.main/index.html|title=U.S. helicopter shot down in Iraq|publisher=CNN|date=2 November 2007|accessdate=6 April 2010|quote=The helicopter was shot down by a shoulder-type missile, about 60 kilometers west of the Iraqi capital Baghdad, at 8&nbsp;am Sunday, witnesses told CNN.}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |date=3 November 2003 |accessdate=11 August 2012 |title=DoD Identifies Army Casualties |quote=The Department of Defense announced today the deaths of eight soldiers who were supporting Operation Iraqi Freedom. The soldiers were on board a CH-47 Chinook Helicopter when it went down on November 2 in Al Fallujah, Iraq. |url=http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=5756 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026013214/http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=5756 |archivedate=26 October 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 7 November 2003: [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk#Variants|UH-60L Black Hawk]] 92-26431 from [[101st Aviation Regiment (United States)|5\u2013101 Aviation Regiment]] shot down by a MANPADS near [[Tikrit]]; all four crew, and both passengers from the [[Department of the Army]] are killed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/org/news/2003/031108-blackhawk-shot01.htm|title=Crash Kills 6 GIs|author=Mohamad Bazzi|publisher=Newsday (New York) |date=8 November 2003|accessdate=30 January 2009}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 9 December 2003: An [[OH-58 Kiowa]] helicopter is hit by a [[rocket-propelled grenade]], forcing a crash landing. Both crewmembers survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenselink.mil/news/Dec2003/n12092003_200312093.html |title=DefenseLink News Article: U.S. Army Helicopter Forced Down in Iraq; Crew OK |accessdate=30 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929224609/http://www.defenselink.mil/news/Dec2003/n12092003_200312093.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2004-01-08-helicopter-list_x.htm|title=Helicopters shot down or crashed in Iraq|work=USA Today|date=1 August 2004|accessdate=16 July 2010|quote=Guerrillas hit an OH-58 Kiowa helicopter with a rocket-propelled grenade near Fallujah, forcing it to make an emergency landing. The two crewmen on board are uninjured.}}</ref>\n\n'''Shootdowns in 2004'''\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 2 January 2004: [[OH-58 Kiowa#OH-58D|OH-58D Kiowa]] 90-0370 from [[82nd Aviation Regiment (United States)|1\u201382 Aviation Brigade]], [[17th Cavalry Regiment|1\u201317 Cavalry Regiment]] shot down near [[Fallujah]], killing a pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armyaircrews.com/kiowa.html|title=Kiowa Crewmembers Line of Duty Deaths|publisher=Army Air Crews|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 8 January 2004: [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk|UH-60 Black Hawk]] 86-24488 from 571st Medical Company (Air Ambulance) was shot down near [[Fallujah]], killing 9 crew and passengers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/iraq/2004-01-08-iraq-helicopter_x.htm|title=Helicopters shot down or crashed in Iraq|work=USA Today|date=8 January 2007|accessdate=31 May 2007 | first1=Jim | last1=Michaels}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article990772.ece|title=Black Hawk crash in Iraq kills nine US soldiers|work=The Times|date=8 January 2004|accessdate=11 February 2009 | location=London|first=Ed|last=Hawkins}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1451169/Nine-killed-in-Black-Hawk-crash-in-Iraq.html|title=Nine killed in Black Hawk crash in Iraq|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 January 2004|accessdate=11 February 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 13 January 2004: [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache]] from [[3rd Cavalry Regiment (United States)#4th Squadron (\"Longknife\")|4th Squadron, 3d Armored Cavalry Regiment]] was shot down near [[Habbaniyah]], the pilots were rescued.<ref>{{cite news |title=Press Release |agency=Reuters|quote=BAGHDAD (Reuters) \u2013 A U.S. Apache helicopter that crashed west of Baghdad on Tuesday may have been shot down by Iraqi guerrillas, a U.S. military spokesman said. \"Our initial information tells us that it's possible that the helicopter was downed by or at least was struck by enemy fire,\" the spokesman said after the helicopter crashed near the town of Habbaniya, about 50 miles west of the capital.|date=13 January 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Boeing AH-64 Apache|url=http://www.militaryaviation.eu/helicopter/Boeing/AH-64.htm|quote=On January 13th, 2004 an Apache was shot down near the western Iraqi town of Habbaniyah. This was the second of the heavily armed gun-ships downed by guerrilla fire since President Bush declared an end to major combat May 1st, 2003.|accessdate=12 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127022954/http://www.militaryaviation.eu/helicopter/Boeing/AH-64.htm|archive-date=2010-11-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 19 March 2004: [[MD Helicopters MH-6 Little Bird#Variants|AH-6J]] 25364, [[160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment (Airborne)|1-160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment]], shot down vicinity of [[Amiriyah]] by an unknown surface-to-air missile while conducting precision [[close air support]] during day operations. Both pilots were rescued by Special Operations forces. {{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 11 April 2004: [[Boeing AH-64 Apache#AH-64D|AH-64D Apache]] 02-5301 from C Company, [[1st Battalion, 227th Aviation Regiment (United States)|1\u2013227 Aviation Regiment]], 4th BCT, [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] shot down west of [[Baghdad]], killing both pilots.<ref>{{cite web|title=ASN Wikibase Occurrence # 77123|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=77123|publisher=Aviation Safety|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|24px|USAF Roundel]] United States Army Aviation \u2013 12 April 2004: [[Sikorsky MH-53#MH-53J/M|MH-53M Pave Low]] 69-5797 of [[20th Special Operations Squadron|16th Special Operations Wing/20th Special Operations Squadron]] was shot down by a [[rocket-propelled grenade]]