als claimed a Russian [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]] [[2008 Georgian spy plane shootdowns|shot down a Georgian]] [[Hermes 450]] [[unmanned aerial vehicle]] and provided video footage from the ill-fated drone showing an apparent MiG-29 launching an air-to-air missile at it. Russia denies that the aircraft was theirs and says they did not have any pilots in the air that day. Abkhazia's administration claimed its own forces shot down the drone with an [[Aero L-39 Albatros|L-39]] aircraft \"because it was violating Abkhaz airspace and breaching ceasefire agreements\".<ref>Long, Helen. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7358761.stm \"Russia 'shot down Georgia drone'\"]. BBC News, 21 April 2008. Retrieved 10 March 2009.</ref> UN investigation concluded that the video was authentic and that the drone was shot down by a Russian MiG-29 or Su-27 using a [[Vympel R-73|R-73]] heat seeking missile.<ref>Chivers, C.J.{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/05/26/europe/georgia.php |title=Georgia |accessdate=2008-06-05 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013141331/http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/05/26/europe/georgia.php |archivedate=13 October 2008 |df=dmy }}  ''International Herald Tribune'', 26 May 2008. Retrieved 10 March 2009.</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 8 August 2008 \u2013 The first [[Russian Air Force]] loss of the campaign was a [[Sukhoi Su-25|Su-25]], piloted by Lieutenant Colonel Oleg Terebunsky of the 368th Attack Aviation Regiment. It was shot down over [[South Ossetia]] near the Zarsk pass, between [[Java (town)|Dzhava]] and [[Tskhinvali]]. It was hit by friendly fire, a [[MANPADS]] missile fired by South Ossetian militia at around 18:00. Earlier in the day, a flight of four [[Georgian Air Force]] Su-25 planes had attacked a Russian army convoy in the same area. This was one of the few missions conducted by Georgia's Su-25s during the brief conflict Georgia believed its aircraft would soon become easy targets for Russian interceptors. The Georgian aircraft returned to their bases and were hidden under camouflage netting to prevent them from being located.<ref>http://www.cast.ru/files/The_Tanks_of_August_sm_eng.pdf</ref><ref name=\"Jamestown\">{{cite web |title=The Russia-Georgia Conflict as Analyzed by the Center of Analysis of Strategies and Technologies in Moscow |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/ |access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 a Russian [[Tupolev Tu-22M|Tu-22M3]] was shot down in [[South Ossettia]] by a Georgian [[Buk missile system|Buk-M1]] [[surface-to-air-missile]] system during the [[Russo-Georgian War]]. Three of the four crew members were killed, while the co-pilot was taken [[Prisoner of war|POW]] by Georgian forces.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lenta.ru/news/2008/09/16/bodies/ |title=\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0422\u0443-22\u041c3 |publisher=lenta.ru |language=Russian |date=16 September 2008 |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/georgia-refuses-to-return-remains-of-russian-pilot/|title=Georgia refuses to return remains of Russian pilot|website=RT International|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 - A Russian [[Sukhoi Su-24|Su-24]] was shot down by Georgian air defense forces with an anti-aircraft missile south of Tskhinvali during the morning. Both pilots ejected, but the co-pilot died impacting the ground when his parachute was damaged by fire. The wounded pilot was captured by Georgian forces. This loss was not initially acknowledged by Russia, while verified later by independent sources.<ref>https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/</ref> The captured pilot, Major Igor Zinov was shown on Georgian TV while being hospitalized together with the co-pilot of the downed Tu-22MR.<ref>https://www.rferl.org/a/Captured_Russian_Pilots_Leave_Georgia_Voicing_Gratitude_Regret/1192311.html</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 A Russian [[Sukhoi Su-25|Su-25]] piloted by Colonel Sergey Kobylash, commander of the 368th Attack Aviation Regiment, was hit by a Georgian MANPADS during an daylight strafing run on a Georgian military formation south of Tskhinvali, on the Gori-Tskhinvali road at 10:30: after making his initial approach, Kolybash's aircraft was struck by a missile that hit his left engine, destroying it.  Not long after, as Kobylash was returning to base at an altitude of 1000 meters, a second [[MANPADS]] missile struck his right engine, leaving the plane without thrust. Kobylash was able to glide to Russian controlled territory before ejecting north of Tskhinvali in a South Ossetian village of the Georgian enclave in the Great Liakh gorge, where he was recovered by a Russian [[combat search and rescue]] team. Shortly after Kobylash was rescued, South Ossetian militants claimed they had downed a Georgian Su-25, however Georgian Air Force did not operate since the day before, likely making the second fatal hit on this Su-25 another friendly fire incident.<ref>http://www.cast.ru/files/The_Tanks_of_August_sm_eng.pdf</ref><ref name=\"Jamestown\">{{cite web |title=The Russia-Georgia Conflict as Analyzed by the Center of Analysis of Strategies and Technologies in Moscow |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/ |access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 at 13:00, another Russian [[Sukhoi Su-25|Su-25]] from the 368th Attack Aviation Regiment, piloted by Major Vladimir Edamenko, was struck by a Russian [[ZSU-23-4 Shilka]] anti-aircraft gun near [[Java (town)|Dzhava]] killing the pilot in another friendly fire incident, due to the failure of the [[Identification friend or foe|IFF system]] on the Su-25. With mounting confusion between Russian Air Force and land foarces, at 15:00, a Russian Su-25 mistakenly attacked a Russian military convoy near Liakhva, destroying a fuel tanker and injuring several troops. The Russian soldiers returned fire with a [[MANPADS]] damaging the Su-25.<ref>http://www.cast.ru/files/The_Tanks_of_August_sm_eng.pdf</ref><ref name=\"Jamestown\">{{cite web |title=The Russia-Georgia Conflict as Analyzed by the Center of Analysis of Strategies and Technologies in Moscow |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |url=https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/ |access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of the Soviet Union (1945\u20131991).svg|20px|Russian Air Force roundel (1992\u20132010)]] 9 August 2008 \u2013 The final Russian aircraft lost in combat was a [[Sukhoi Su-24|Su-24]], which was shot down by friendly forces while it was escorting a Russian column on the Tskhinvali-Gori highway, when it was hit by a Russian SAM. The crew ejected and was recovered by a search and rescue helicopter.<ref>https://jamestown.org/program/the-russia-georgia-conflict-as-analyzed-by-the-center-of-analysis-of-strategies-and-technologies-in-moscow/</ref>\n\n===War in Donbass (2014\u2013present)===\n{{Main|List of Ukrainian aircraft losses during the Ukrainian crisis}}\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] [[Ukrainian Ground Forces#Airmobile Forces and Army Aviation|Ukrainian Army Aviation]] \u2013 2 May 2014: Two [[Mil Mi-24]] helicopters were shot down during large-scale operations during the [[Siege of Sloviansk]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trust.org/item/20140502034153-9eh7a |title=Pro-Russian rebels in Slaviansk say Ukraine tries to retake town, gunfire heard |publisher=Trust.org |date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=21 August 2014}}</ref> Rebels claimed they had taken one of the pilot captive.<ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2014/05/2/7024139/ \u0421\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \"\u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u044c\u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430]. ''Ukrayinska Pravda'', 2 May 2014</ref> The [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Ukraine)|Ukrainian Ministry of Internal Affairs]] reported that two helicopters had been shot down, resulting in the deaths of two airmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tass.ru/mezhdunarodnaya-panorama/1162845|publisher=TASS|accessdate=24 May 2016|title=\u0423 \u0421\u043b\u043e\u0432'\u044f\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0443 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u0431\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0454\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0431\u0456\u0439. \u0421\u0435\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \"\u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043b\u044c\u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Army Aviation \u2013 5 May 2014: A [[Mil Mi-24]] crashed after it was shot down by a heavy machine gun manned by rebel forces. The helicopter crash landed in a river, which allowed all crew members to survive.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ukraine soldiers killed in renewed Sloviansk fighting|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27280814|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u0423 \u0421\u043b\u043e\u0432'\u044f\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0443 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0456\u0442. \u0417\u0430\u0433\u0438\u043d\u0443\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u0456\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0438|url=http://www.gazeta.lviv.ua/2014/05/29/u-slovjansku-teroristi-zbili-vjskovij-vertolt-zaginuli-ploti/|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Army Aviation \u2013 29 May 2014: A [[Mil Mi-8]] helicopter was shot down by rebel forces between [[Kramatorsk]] and Mount Karachun, killing 14 on board, among them General Vladimir Kultchysky. Another soldier was seriously injured but survived the crash.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Paton Walsh|first1=Nick|last2=Smith-Spark|first2=Laura|title=Ukrainian military helicopter shot down; 14 dead, president says|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/05/29/world/europe/ukraine-crisis/ |publisher=CNN|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] [[Ukrainian Air Force]] \u2013 6 June 2014: An [[Antonov An-30]] surveillance plane was shot down by Separatist militias from Slaviansk with two [[Man-portable air-defense system|shoulder-launched missiles]]. Ukrainian authorities initially claimed that the pilots survived,<ref>[http://news.liga.net/news/incident/2048765-samolet_nad_slavyanskom_terroristy_podbili_iz_pzrk_seleznev.htm \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u0437 \u041f\u0417\u0420\u041a \u2013 \u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0432]. Liga News, 6 June 2014</ref><ref>[http://news.liga.net/news/politics/2048820-piloty_an_26_spasli_zhiteley_slavyanska_otvedya_samolet_ot_goroda.htm \u041f\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0442\u044b \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0421\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430, \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0434\u044f \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430]. Liga News, 6 June 2014</ref> but they later reported that five crewmembers were killed in the action, and two others missing.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/spokesman-three-pilots-from-downed-an-26-die-in-sloviansk-351056.html Spokesman: Three pilots from downed An-26 die in Sloviansk]. ''Kyiv Post''. 7 June 2014</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 14 June 2014: An [[Ilyushin Il-76]] transport plane was [[Ukrainian Air Force Ilyushin Il-76 shoot-down|shot down]] as it approached an airport in [[Luhansk]], killing nine crew members and 40 troops on board.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/ukraine-ministry-rebels-military-aircraft-article-1.1829598 \"Pro-Russian rebels shoot down Ukraine military plane, killing service personnel\"], Associated Press. 14 June 2014. Retrieved 14 June 2014</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 14 June 2014: Rebels claim to have shot down a [[Sukhoi Su-24]] with a portable anti-aircraft gun after it had dropped cluster munitions on a local police station. They also claim the pilot had bailed out and they sent out a search mission after him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Defenders launch counteroffensive in Lugansk region|url=http://tass.ru/en/world/736052 |publisher=TASS|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 19 June 2014: A spokesman for the militia in Donetsk stated that they downed a Ukrainian Air Force [[Sukhoi Su-25]] during the battle in Yampil.<ref>[http://rian.com.ua/incidents/20140619/353606933.html \u041d\u0430\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u043c \u042f\u043c\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0443-25 \u2013 \u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b] (Su-25 shot down above the village of Yampil \u2013 militia) RIA Novosti. 20 June 2014. Retrieved 20 June 2014</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 24 June 2014: The Ukrainian military says one of its helicopters, a [[Mil Mi-8]], had been shot down by pro-Russian rebels in the east near [[Sloviansk]], killing all nine people on board,<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28002993 \"Ukraine army helicopter 'shot down' despite ceasefire\"] [[BBC World News]], 24 June 2014.</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 14 July 2014: A Ukrainian [[Antonov An-26]] transport aircraft was shot down by a surface-to-air missile over eastern Ukraine while flying at {{convert|6500|m|ft}}. The Ukrainian defence minister claimed that the altitude is far from the reach of a shoulder-launched missile, suggesting that the aircraft was downed by Russian forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/ukraine-military-plane-shot-down-by-russia-1456632|title=Ukraine: Military Plane 'Shot Down By Russia'|date=14 July 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|work=International Business Times|last=Bacchi|first=Umberto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28299334 |title=Ukraine military plane shot down as fighting rages |publisher=BBC News |date=14 July 2014|accessdate=14 July 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC28309034\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28309034 |title=Ukraine conflict: Jet bombs rebel-held town of Snizhne |publisher=BBC News |date=15 July 2014 |accessdate=15 July 2014 }}</ref> Two crewmembers were captured by pro-Russian militiamen, four were rescued by Ukrainian forces and the other two were unaccounted for.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ua.korrespondent.net/ukraine/politics/3392830-dolia-dvokh-luidei-zi-zbytoho-an-26-poky-scho-nevidoma-seleznov|title=\u0414\u043e\u043b\u044f \u0434\u0432\u043e\u0445 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0456 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0410\u043d-26 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0438 \u0449\u043e \u043d\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043e\u043c\u0430 \u2013 \u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u044c\u043e\u0432|date=15 July 2014 |accessdate= 12 April 2015|publisher=Korrespondent.net}}</ref> The missing aviators were found dead on 17 July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/two-crewmembers-from-an-26-downed-in-luhansk-region-killed-356423.html|title=Two crewmembers from An-26 downed in Luhansk region killed|date=17 July 2014 |accessdate= 12 April 2015|work=Kyiv Post}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 16 July 2014: A Ukrainian [[Sukhoi Su-25]] was shot down over eastern Ukraine, and the pilot ejected successfully. [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine|National Security Council]] spokesman Andriy Lysenko said that it was shot down by a [[R-27 (air-to-air missile)|R-27T]] missile fired from a Russian [[Sukhoi Su-27]] or [[MiG-29]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://korrespondent.net/ukraine/politics/3393663-rossyiskyi-samolet-sbyl-raketoi-ukraynskyi-su-25-snbo|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b \u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0443-25 \u2013 \u0421\u041d\u0411\u041e|date =17 July 2014  |accessdate= 25 May 2016|publisher=Korrespondent.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20khvylyn.com/news/incident/news_9738.html|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0448\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a \u0432 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0421\u043d\u0435\u0436\u043d\u044b\u043c|date=17 July 2014 |accessdate= 25 May 2016|publisher=20Khvylyn.ua}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kyivpost.com/article/content/murder-in-the-sky-malaysia-airlines-flight-17/sbu-releases-more-conversations-implicating-russia-in-shooting-down-malaysia-airlines-flight-video-transcript-2-356778.html|title=SBU releases more conversations implicating Russia in shooting down Malaysia Airlines flight (VIDEO, TRANSCRIPT) - Jul. 19, 2014|date=19 July 2014|website=KyivPost|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 23 July 2014: Two [[Sukhoi Su-25]] strike fighters were shot down in the rebel-held area of [[Savur-Mohyla]]. Ukrainian authorities claimed that they were hit by long-range anti-aircraft missiles launched from Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unian.net/politics/943073-dva-ukrainskih-su-25-sbili-s-territorii-rf-na-vyisote-bolee-5-tyisyach-metrov-snbo.html|title=\u0414\u0432\u0430 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0423-25 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0441 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0420\u0424 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u043e\u0442\u0435 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 5 \u0442\u044b\u0441\u044f\u0447 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u2013 \u0421\u041d\u0411\u041e|date=23 July 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|agency=Ukrainian Independent Information Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/07/23/ukraine-rebels-separatists-fighter-jet-shot-down/13034005/|title=2 Ukrainian jet fighters shot down in rebel-held region|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> Ukrainian Prime Minister, [[Arseniy Yatsenyuk]], said later in an interview that one of the fighters was probably shot down by an air-to-air missile.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/russian/international/2014/07/140723_ukraine_yatseniuk_su25_downed_missile.shtml|title = \u042f\u0446\u0435\u043d\u044e\u043a: \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0443-25 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0439 \"\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0445-\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0445\"|date = 24 July 2014 |accessdate= 12 April 2015 |publisher = BBC Ukraine}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 7 August 2014: Pro-Russian forces shot down a Ukrainian Air Force [[Mikoyan MiG-29]] with a \"[[Buk missile system|Buk]]\" surface-to-air missile near the town of [[Yenakievo]]. The pilot managed to eject.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://korrespondent.net/ukraine/politics/3402982-vozle-enakyevo-sbyly-ystrebytel-myh-29-seleznev|title=\u0412\u043e\u0437\u043b\u0435 \u0415\u043d\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u041c\u0438\u0413-29 \u2013 \u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0432|date=7 August 2014 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|publisher=Korrespondent.net}}</ref> and separatist sources later claimed he was captured and interrogated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interfax.ru/390232|title=\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0437\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441 \u044d\u043a\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0436\u0430 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f|date=7 August 2014 |accessdate= 12 April 2015|agency=Interfax}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 17 August 2014: A [[Mikoyan MiG-29]] was shot down by rebels in the Luhansk region of eastern Ukraine returning after completing a successful mission. The pilot managed to eject and was found by a search and rescue operation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Magnenou|first1=Fabien|title=DIRECT. Un avion de chasse ukrainien abattu par des s\u00e9paratistes prorusses|url=http://www.francetvinfo.fr/monde/europe/manifestations-en-ukraine/direct-un-avion-de-chasse-ukrainien-abattu-par-des-separatistes-prorusses_671453.html|publisher=France TV Info|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 20 August 2014: A [[Sukhoi Su-24]]M was shot down by rebel forces in the Luhansk region of eastern Ukraine. The two crewmembers ejected successfully.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.liga.net/news/politics/2995693-v_snbo_utochnili_chto_pod_luganskom_byl_sbit_samolet_su_24m.htm|title=\u0412 \u0421\u041d\u0411\u041e \u0443\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u041b\u0443\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0443-24\u041c|date=24 May 2016 |accessdate= 11 April 2015|publisher=Liga News}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Army Aviation \u2013 20 August 2014: A [[Mil Mi-24]] helicopter was shot down in near the town of [[Horlivka]] according to the [[Ministry of Defence (Ukraine)|Ukrainian Ministry of Defence]]. Both pilots died in the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/14,114912,16513713,Czesc__bialego_konwoju__z_Rosji_jest_juz_na_Ukrainie_.html?PageNumber=2|title=Cz\u0119\u015b\u0107 'bia\u0142ego konwoju' z Rosji jest ju\u017c na Ukrainie. Kij\u00f3w: 'Nie wydali\u015bmy zgody' |language=pl|publisher=Wiadomosci.gazeta.pl |accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[File:Roundel of Ukraine.svg|20px|Roundel of Ukraine.svg]] Ukrainian Air Force \u2013 29 August 2014: A [[Sukhoi Su-25]] was shot down by a surface-to-air missile in the Luhansk region of eastern Ukraine. The pilot ejected safely and was recovered by a unit of the [[National Guard of Ukraine|Ukrainian National Guard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.liga.net/news/politics/3106003-v_donbasse_iz_rossiyskogo_zrk_sbili_ukrainskiy_samolet_su_25.htm|title = \u0412 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u0438\u0437 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0417\u0420\u041a \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0421\u0443-25|date = 29 August 2014 |accessdate= 24 May 2016|publisher = Liga News}}</ref>\n\n===Syrian Civil War (2011\u2013present)===\n{{Main|List of aviation shootdowns and accidents during the Syrian Civil War}}\n\n===Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen (2015\u2013present)===\n{{Main|List of aviation shootdowns and accidents during the Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen}}\n\n==Civilian aircraft==\n* [[List of airliner shootdown incidents]] \u2013 dealing with civilian airliners\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Russian aircraft losses in the Second Chechen War]]\n* [[List of aviation shootdowns and accidents during the Iraq War]]\n* [[List of combat losses of United States military aircraft since the Vietnam War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Lists of aviation accidents and incidents}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft shootdown incidents| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of aviation accidents and incidents|Shootdowns]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo; mos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_aircraft_shootdowns"}
{"title_page": "Laid paper", "text_new": "{{Citations needed|date=October 2011}}'''Laid paper''' is a type of [[paper]] having a ribbed texture imparted by the manufacturing process. In the pre-mechanical period of European [[papermaking]] (from the 12th century into the 19th century), laid paper was the predominant kind of paper produced. Its use, however, diminished in the 19th century, when it was largely supplanted by [[wove paper]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hunter|first=Dard|title=Papermaking: The History and Technique of an Ancient Craft|publisher=Dover Publications, Inc.|year=1978|isbn=0-486-23619-6|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> Laid paper is still commonly used by [[artist]]s as a support for [[charcoal]] [[drawing]]s.\n\n==History==\n[[File:SN-p837.jpg|thumb|Laid paper from before the era of machine-made paper\u2014leaf from [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]]'s ''Systema naturae'' (1758)]]\n[[File:Antique Laid Paper, Paris 1746.jpg|alt=An example of \"antique laid\" paper, showing darker regions along the chain lines.|thumb|220x220px|An example of \"antique laid\" paper, showing darker regions along the chain lines.]]\nBefore the mechanization of [[papermaking]], paper was made by hand using a wire [[sieve]] mounted in a rectangular mould used to produce a single sheet at a time. A papermaker would dip the mould into a vat containing diluted pulp of hemp or [[linen]] fibers then lift it out, tilt it to spread the pulp evenly over the sieve and, as the water drained out between the wires, shake the mould to lock the fibers together. In the process, the pattern of the wires in the sieve was imparted to the sheet of paper.<ref>[[Philip Gaskell]], ''A New Introduction to Bibliography'' (New York & Oxford: Oxford UP, 1972), pp. 57\u201358, 60.</ref> Up until the invention of [[wove paper]] around 1756, these screens were made up of thicker, more widely spaced wires around which were woven finer and more tightly packed wires. The traditional laid pattern consists of a series of wide-spaced lines (chain lines) parallel to the shorter sides of the sheet and more narrowly spaced lines (laid lines) adjacent to the chain lines. In machine mould-made paper (which is produced in rolls rather than individual sheets), the chain lines run in the machine direction, along the length of the roll, while in handmade papers, they run parallel to the arms of the papermaker on either side of the mould. The grain direction of a sheet (the orientation along which the majority of the cellulose fibers settle) is generally parallel to these chain lines.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/chain+line|title=Definition of CHAIN LINE|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neenahpaper.com/|title=Neenah Paper|website=www.neenahpaper.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nA further distinction exists between what are called 'antique laid' and 'modern laid' papers. From the 12th century on the \"chain wires\" of a paper mould were attached directly to the wooden ribs of the frame itself. When pulling a sheet from the vat, these ribs produce a slight suction which pulls the water out of the newly formed sheet and a slightly thicker layer of pulp is left across the top of the ribs. When the sheets dry, darker strips can be seen running along these chain lines when the sheet is held to the light. Improvements in mould making in the early 1800s lifted the chain wires slightly, resulting in a more evenly toned sheet.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collation.folger.edu/2012/06/learning-to-read-old-paper/|title=Learning to \"read\" old paper|date=2012-06-25|website=The Collation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Modern Production Methods ==\n[[File:Randolph Caldecott illustration2.jpg|left|thumb|Visible laid pattern effect in a [[picture book]] illustration by [[Randolph Caldecott]].  Published 1887, digitally restored.]]\nModern papermaking techniques use a [[Watermark#Dandy roll process|dandy roll]] to create the laid pattern during the early stages of manufacture, similar to the way a [[watermark]] is added to handmade papers. While in the wet state, the paper stock (a dilute dispersion of the cellulose fibers in water) is drained on a wire mesh to de-water the stock. During this process, a dandy roll with a laid mesh pattern is pressed into the wet stock, displacing the cellulose fiber.<ref>U.S. Dept. of Commerce, ''Circular of the Bureau of Standards'', No. 70 (Washington: GPO, 1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=spMPAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA169 p. 169].</ref> This pattern has to be applied at a particular stock consistency; otherwise the pattern will be lost as the fiber flows back while the stock moves past the dandy (too wet), or fiber will pick out of the stock (too dry), causing surface disruption. As the fiber is displaced, localized areas of higher and lower density are produced in a laid pattern, and the pattern is also created on the paper's surface. The pattern is therefore apparent both as one looks through the sheet and as one views its surface. Applying the laid pattern as a mechanical emboss would not create the ribbed pattern seen on looking through the sheet, as this is achieved only by watermarking techniques.\n\n<br />\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Paper}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laid Paper}}\n[[Category:Paper]]\n", "text_old": "{{Citations needed|date=October 2011}}'''Laid paper''' is a type of [[paper]] having a ribbed texture imparted by the manufacturing process. In the pre-mechanical period of European [[papermaking]] (from the 12th century into the 19th century), laid paper was the predominant kind of paper produced. Its use, however, diminished in the 19th century, when it was largely supplanted by [[wove paper]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hunter|first=Dard|title=Papermaking: The History and Technique of an Ancient Craft|publisher=Dover Publications, Inc.|year=1978|isbn=0-486-23619-6|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> Laid paper is still commonly used by [[artist]]s as a support for [[charcoal]] [[drawing]]s.\n\n==History==\n[[File:SN-p837.jpg|thumb|Laid paper from before the era of machine-made paper\u2014leaf from [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]]'s ''Systema naturae'' (1758)]]\n[[File:Antique Laid Paper, Paris 1746.jpg|alt=An example of \"antique laid\" paper, showing darker regions along the chain lines.|thumb|220x220px|An example of \"antique laid\" paper, showing darker regions along the chain lines.]]\nBefore the mechanization of [[papermaking]], paper was made by hand using a wire [[sieve]] mounted in a rectangular mould used to produce a single sheet at a time. A papermaker would dip the mould into a vat containing diluted pulp of hemp or [[linen]] fibers then lift it out, tilt it to spread the pulp evenly over the sieve and, as the water drained out between the wires, shake the mould to lock the fibers together. In the process, the pattern of the wires in the sieve was imparted to the sheet of paper.<ref>[[Philip Gaskell]], ''A New Introduction to Bibliography'' (New York & Oxford: Oxford UP, 1972), pp. 57\u201358, 60.</ref> Up until the invention of [[wove paper]] around 1756, these screens were made up of thicker, more widely spaced wires around which were woven finer and more tightly packed wires. The traditional laid pattern consists of a series of wide-spaced lines (chain lines) parallel to the shorter sides of the sheet and more narrowly spaced lines (laid lines) adjacent to the chain lines. In machine mould-made paper (which is produced in rolls rather than individual sheets), the chain lines run in the machine direction, along the length of the roll, while in handmade papers, they run parallel to the arms of the papermaker on either side of the mould. The grain direction of a sheet (the orientation along which the majority of the cellulose fibers settle) is generally parallel to these chain lines.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/chain+line|title=Definition of CHAIN LINE|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neenahpaper.com/|title=Neenah Paper|website=www.neenahpaper.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nA further distinction exists between what are called 'antique laid' and 'modern laid' papers. From the 12th century on the \"chain wires\" of a paper mould were attached directly to the wooden ribs of the frame itself. When pulling a sheet from the vat, these ribs produce a slight suction which pulls the water out of the newly formed sheet and a slightly thicker layer of pulp is left across the top of the ribs. When the sheets dry, darker strips can be seen running along these chain lines when the sheet is held to the light. Improvements in mould making in the early 1800s lifted the chain wires slightly, resulting in a more evenly toned sheet.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collation.folger.edu/2012/06/learning-to-read-old-paper/|title=Learning to \"read\" old paper|date=2012-06-25|website=The Collation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Randolph Caldecott illustration2.jpg|left|thumb|Visible laid pattern effect in a [[picture book]] illustration by [[Randolph Caldecott]].  Published 1887, digitally restored.]]\nModern papermaking techniques use a [[Watermark#Dandy roll process|dandy roll]] to create the laid pattern during the early stages of manufacture, similar to the way a [[watermark]] is added to handmade papers. While in the wet state, the paper stock (a dilute dispersion of the cellulose fibers in water) is drained on a wire mesh to de-water the stock. During this process, a dandy roll with a laid mesh pattern is pressed into the wet stock, displacing the cellulose fiber.<ref>U.S. Dept. of Commerce, ''Circular of the Bureau of Standards'', No. 70 (Washington: GPO, 1917), [https://books.google.com/books?id=spMPAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA169 p. 169].</ref> This pattern has to be applied at a particular stock consistency; otherwise the pattern will be lost as the fiber flows back while the stock moves past the dandy (too wet), or fiber will pick out of the stock (too dry), causing surface disruption. As the fiber is displaced, localized areas of higher and lower density are produced in a laid pattern, and the pattern is also created on the paper's surface. The pattern is therefore apparent both as one looks through the sheet and as one views its surface. Applying the laid pattern as a mechanical emboss would not create the ribbed pattern seen on looking through the sheet, as this is achieved only by watermarking techniques.\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Paper}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laid Paper}}\n[[Category:Paper]]\n", "name_user": "MeeshKapiche", "label": "safe", "comment": "Article formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laid_paper"}
{"title_page": "Renault Alpine GTA/A610", "text_new": "The '''Renault Alpine GTA''' and the succeeding A610<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/|title=Car News: Breaking News, Automotive Trends, and Model Announcements|website=Car and Driver|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> was a sports [[coupe]] [[automobile]] produced by the [[Renault]]-owned [[France|French]] manufacturer [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]] between late 1984 and 1995. It replaced the slow-selling [[Alpine A310]], with which it shared many features including the layout and engine.<ref name=\"Mon813\">{{cite journal | ref=super | journal=Le Moniteur de l'Automobile | page = 13 | title= La renaissance | trans-title = The rebirth | last= Cornaert | first= Jean-Jacques | location=Brussels, Belgium | language=French | volume=36 | number=813 | date=1985-01-24 | publisher=Editions Auto-Magazine }}</ref> The car underwent a substantive redesign in 1991, which is also when the new model name A610 was given.\n\n==First generation==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = Renault Alpine GTA\n| image          = Renault Alpine V6 GT Gen3 D500 1984-1991 frontright 2011-04-10 A.jpg\n| manufacturer   = [[Renault]] [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]]\n| aka            = {{unbulleted list | Renault Alpine V6 GT | Renault Alpine V6 Turbo | Renault GTA (UK) }}\n| production     = November 1984-February 1991\n| class          = [[Sports car]]\n| predecessor    = [[Alpine A310]]\n| body_style     = 2+2, 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout         = [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|RR layout]]\n| successor      = [[Alpine A610]]\n| assembly       = [[Dieppe, Seine-Maritime|Dieppe]], [[France]]\n| engine         = {{unbulleted list | 2.5L (2458&nbsp;cc) ''[[V6 PRV engine|PRV Z7U]]'' [[Turbocharger|turbo]] [[V6 engine|V6]] | 2.9L (2849&nbsp;cc) ''[[V6 PRV engine|PRV Z6W]]'' V6 }}\n| designer       = Yves Legal\n}}\n\nIt was the first car launched by Alpine under Renault ownership (though Alpine had been affiliated with Renault for many years, with its earlier models using many Renault parts). Longer, wider, and taller, it effectively updated the design of its predecessor, the [[Alpine A310]], updating that car's silhouette with modern design features like body-integrated bumpers and a triangular C-pillar with large rear windshield. Like its predecessor, it used the [[V6 PRV engine]] in a rear-engined layout, with extensive use of Polyester plastics and [[Fiberglass|fibreglass]] for the body panels making it lighter and quicker than rivals such as the [[Porsche 944]]. Passenger room increased, making the rear seat more of a useful proposition, while equipment was much more complete and now included items such as power locks.<ref name=\"Mon813b\">[[#super|Cornaert]], p. 14</ref> It was one of the most aerodynamic cars of its time, the naturally aspirated version achieved a record 0.28 drag coefficient in its class.<ref name=\"Mon813b\"/> Due to its bigger tires and need for more cooling intakes, the Turbo's drag coefficient was a bit higher: 0.30 <math>\\scriptstyle C_\\mathrm x\\,</math>. The GTA name, used to denote the entire range of this generation, stands for \"Grand Tourisme Alpine\" but in most markets the car was marketed as the Renault Alpine V6 GT or as the Renault Alpine V6 Turbo.<ref name=Echap>{{cite journal | journal = Echappement | date = April 1985 | number = 198 | ref = PB85 | title = L'usine Alpine: renaissance ou r\u00e9volution? | trans-title = The Alpine works: renaissance or revolution? | last = Barbaza | first = Pierre | page = 88 | publisher = Michael Hommell | location = Paris, France | language = French }}</ref> In Great Britain it was sold simply as the Renault GTA,<ref>{{citation | first = Stuart | last = Bladon | title = Observer's Cars 1987 | publisher = Penguin Books Ltd | date = 1987-05-07 | page = 144 | isbn = 978-0723234593 }}</ref> as Sunbeam (and then [[Simca 1307|Chrysler/Talbot]]) had been using the \"[[Sunbeam Alpine|Alpine]]\" badge since the 1950s.\n\n[[File:1988 Renault GTA Turbo rear (UK).jpg|thumb|left|1988 Renault GTA Turbo (UK), rear view]]\nRather than being moulded in a single piece as for the preceding A310, the new Alpine's body was moulded in a large number of small separate panels.<ref name=Echap/> This required a major overhaul of the Alpine plant, leaving only the sandblasting machinery intact. The car was also considerably more efficient to manufacture, with the time necessary to build a finished car dropping from 130 to 77 hours - which was still a long time, but acceptable for a small-volume specialty car.<ref name=PB2>[[#PB|Barbaza]], p. 89</ref> The PRV engine in the naturally aspirated model was identical to the version used in the [[Renault 25]], a 2849&nbsp;cc unit producing {{Convert|160|PS|hp|0|abbr=on}}. The small power gain compensated for the weight increase, up by {{convert|92|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Also available was the more powerful [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] model, which used a smaller (2.5 liter) displacement.\n\nThe central backbone chassis (with outriggers for side impact protection) was built by Heuliez and then transferred to Dieppe - aside from the body, most of the car was subcontracted to various suppliers.<ref name=PB2/> The drivetrain was mounted on a separate subframe, meaning it can be removed in as little as two hours.<ref name=MK129>{{cite magazine | ref = MK717 | title = Sportlich & g\u00fcnstig? | trans-title = Sporty and cheap? | language = German | page = 129 | date = July 2017 | last = Woytal | first = Bernd | magazine = Motor Klassik | publisher = Motor Presse Stuttgart | location = Stuttgart, Germany | issn = 0177-8862 }}</ref> It was also moved {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} forward (making the rear overhang shorter while nearly all other dimensions increased) compared to the A310, improving somewhat on that car's tailwards weight distribution.<ref name=\"Mon813\"/> The transmission was the same [[Renault 30]]-based unit that the A310 had used, with some minor changes and somewhat longer fourth and fifth gears. Those gears were taller yet for the GT Turbo model.<ref name=\"Mon813b\"/> At the time of introduction, daily production number amounted to ten cars.<ref name=PB3>[[#PB|Barbaza]], p. 90</ref> This soon dropped considerably, as the somewhat less than prestigious Renault had a hard time in the sports car marketplace. The average production for the six full years of production was just above 1000 per annum, or just above three per day - almost identical to the A310 V6's annual production.\n\n===Models===\n[[File:Alpine-p1040134.jpg|thumb|left|Renault Alpine Le Mans (1990-1991)]]\nThe first model introduced was the naturally aspirated V6 GT (D&nbsp;500), which entered production in November 1984, although press photos had been released in September 1984.<ref name=TAM85>{{Cite book | title = Quattroruote: Tutte le Auto del Mondo 1985 | editor = Mastrostefano, Raffaele | publisher = Editoriale Domus S.p.A | ref = TAM85 | year = 1985 | language = Italian | page = 847 | location = Milano | isbn = 88-7212-012-8 }}</ref> The car was first shown at the 1985 Amsterdam Rai, immediately after which it also went on sale.<ref name=MilleM>{{cite web | url = http://alpine.v6.turbo.free.fr/guide/alpine-v6-turbo-mille-miles.php | title = Alpine V6 Turbo Mille Miles | work = Le site des amateurs et passionn\u00e9s des Alpine Renault GTA | last = Liszewski | first = Nicolas | language = French | accessdate = 2014-09-08 }}</ref> In July 1985 the Europa Cup model appeared; this limited edition model was intended for a single-make racing championship and 69 cars were built (54 in 1985 and 15 more in 1987).<ref name=perso>{{cite web | url = http://alpine-gta-europacup.pagesperso-orange.fr/ | title = Alpine GTA, GTA Europa Cup et A610 (de s\u00e9rie - en course) | publisher = Philippe du 77 | trans-title = street - competition | language = French | accessdate = 2014-09-08 }}</ref> In September 1985 the turbo model (D&nbsp;501) followed, which increased the power of the PRV unit to {{Convert|200|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Sales of the naturally aspirated model were always sluggish, but with the more powerful turbo, things picked up considerably.<ref name=MK129/> At the 1986 [[British International Motor Show#Birmingham years|Birmingham Show]] the right-hand-drive version was presented and UK sales, as the Renault GTA, commenced.<ref name=MilleM/>\n\nIn early 1987 a catalyzed version appeared, with fifteen less horsepower. This meant that the Turbo could finally be sold in Switzerland, and later in other European countries such as Germany and the Netherlands when they adopted stricter legislation. The catalyzed model had lower gearing in fourth and fifth gears, in order to somewhat mask its power deficit.<ref name=\"AR87\">{{cite book | ref = AR87 | title = Automobil Revue 1987 | editor-last = B\u00fcschi | editor-first = Hans-Ulrich | publisher = Hallwag AG | location = Berne, Switzerland | language = German, French | page = 497 | volume = 82 | date = 5 March 1987 | isbn = 3-444-00458-3 }}</ref> In 1988 anti-lock brakes became available.<ref name=RenAlp>{{cite web | url = http://www.alpine-renault.net/gta.htm | publisher = Avenue de Br\u00e9aut\u00e9 | first = Etienne | last = Lhoste | title = Mod\u00e8les (S\u00e9rie) > GTA V6 GT & GT Turbo | trans-title = Production models | language = French | accessdate = 2014-09-09 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195406/http://www.alpine-renault.net/gta.htm | archivedate = 2014-09-10 }}</ref> For the 1989 model year the Mille Miles version appeared. With the non-catalyzed engine, this model heralded a re-focus on the Alpine name. The Renault logo was gone from the car, with an alpine logo up front and a large \"Alpine\" print appearing between the taillights. However, as the name 'Alpine' could not be used in the UK the name Alpine was removed from cars destined for the UK; there was no large print at the back of these cars and a UK specific logo was fitted to the front of the car. The Mille Miles, a limited edition of 100 cars, also featured a special dark red metallic paintjob, polished aluminium wheels, and a large silver-gray triangular stripe with the Alpine \"A\" across the left side of the front.<ref name=RenAlp/>\n\nIn February 1990 the limited edition Le Mans arrived, this car had a more aggressive body kit with polyester wheel arch extensions and a one piece front with smaller headlights. Wheels were 3 piece BBS style produced by ACT, 8x16\" front & 10x17\" rear. Many of these changes were adopted for the succeeding A610. The regular V6 GT and V6 Turbo ended production during 1990, while the Le Mans version continued to be produced until February 1991. 325 of these were built in total. Also in 1990, Renault was forced to install the less powerful catalyzed engine in cars destined for the home market, leading to grumbling amongst Alpine enthusiasts about the loss of power (down to {{Convert|185|PS|kW|abbr=on|disp=or}}) while the [[Renault 25|25 Turbo]] saloon actually gained power when it became catalyzed. In response Danielson SA, a famous French tuner, created an upgraded version of the Le Mans with {{convert|210|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nRenault had planned a federalized version of the Alpine V6 Turbo all along, originally for the 1986 model year, but development proceeded slowly.<ref name=tough>{{cite magazine | magazine = [[Autoweek]] | last = Lovell | first = Bill | pages = 10\u201312 | date = 1984-04-08 | title = Tough Company | issn = 0192-9674 | volume = 35 | number = 14 | publisher = Crain Press Inc. }}</ref> The US model had an emissions cleaned engine with {{Convert|180|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}, bigger bumpers, and flip-up headlamps ([http://www.renaultalpine.co.uk/gallery/album.php?album_id=2&sk=t&sd=a&st=0&start=11 photo]).<ref name=tough/> Various crash safety improvements were also carried out, and it was planned to install a softer suspension. In 1987, however, Renault withdrew from the US market. Commentators had also expressed concern about AMC dealers being able to handle such an expensive and complicated car.<ref name=tough/> By then 21 pre-series cars had been finished. 12 of these were sold by Alpine directly to specially selected customers at home.\n\n{{clear_left}}\n\n===Specifications ===\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" cellpadding=\"0\"  cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:91%;\"\n! Model\n|'''V6 GT<br>D500 05'''\n|'''V6 Turbo<br>D501 05'''\n|'''V6 Turbo<br>D50 A (USA)'''\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat<br>D501 05 (Swiss)'''<ref name=\"AR87\"/>\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat<br>D502 05'''\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat<br>\"Le Mans\" D502 05 A'''\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat tuning<br>\"Le Mans\" D502 05 A (Danielson)'''\n|-\n! Engine\n| colspan=\"7\" | [[V6 PRV engine|PRV V6]]\n|-\n! Type\n| colspan=\"7\" | Longitudinal\n|-\n! Cylinders\n| colspan=\"7\" | 6 cylinders\n|-\n! [[Valve]]s\n| colspan=\"7\" | 12 valves\n|-\n! [[Camshaft]]\n| colspan=\"7\" | top\n|-\n! Engine size\n| 2849&nbsp;cc\n| colspan=\"6\" | 2458&nbsp;cc\n|-\n! Compression ratio\n| 9.5 : 1\n| 8.6 :1\n| colspan=\"5\" | 8 : 1\n|-\n! Max power\n| {{Convert|160|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|200|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|182|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5900&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|185|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5500&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|185|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|185|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|210|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5200&nbsp;rpm\n|-\n! Max [[torque]]\n| {{Convert|221|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 3500&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|285|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2500&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|276|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|288|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2250&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|288|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2200&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|288|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2200&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|350|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2200&nbsp;rpm\n|-\n! [[Catalytic converter]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | No\n| colspan=\"5\" | Yes\n|-\n! Fuel\n| colspan=\"2\" | RON 97\n| colspan=\"5\" | RON 95 or 98 unleaded\n|-\n! [[Carburetor]]\n| [[Carburetor]] SC 34 + DC 35\n| colspan=\"6\" | electronic injection\n|-\n! Air supply\n| atmospheric\n| Turbocharged {{Convert|0.65|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n| Turbocharged {{Convert|0.65|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n| colspan=\"3\" | Turbocharged {{Convert|0.70|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n| Turbocharged {{Convert|1.0|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Kilometer start-stop\n| 28.4 s\n| 26.8 s\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| 27.5 s\n| 26.7 s\n|-\n! 0 to 100&nbsp;km/h\n| 8.0 s\n| 7.0 s\n| -\n| 7.0 s\n| 7.0 s\n| 6.7 s\n| 5.7 s\n|-\n! Max speed\n| {{convert|235|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|250|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| - \n| {{convert|238|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|243|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|240|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|247|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Consumption 90&nbsp;km/h<br>120&nbsp;km/h<br>Town\n| \n7.0 l/100&nbsp;km<br>7.9 l/100&nbsp;km <br>14.7 l/100&nbsp;km\n| \n6.4 l/100&nbsp;km<br>8.1 l/100&nbsp;km<br>12.8 l/100&nbsp;km\n|\n-<br>-<br>-\n| \n-<br>-<br>-\n| \n-<br>-<br>-\n| \n7.1 l/100&nbsp;km<br>9.0 l/100&nbsp;km<br>13.9 l/100&nbsp;km\n| \n8.3 l/100&nbsp;km<br>10.1 l/100&nbsp;km<br>13.7 l/100&nbsp;km\n|-\n! Fuel tank\n| {{convert|72|L|1|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|72|L|1|abbr=on}} + {{convert|1|L|1|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|57|L|1|abbr=on}}\n| colspan=\"4\" | {{convert|72|L|1|abbr=on}} + {{convert|1|L|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Aerodynamic\n| [[Drag coefficient|Cx]] : 0.28<br>SCx : 0.48\n| colspan=\"4\" | Cx : 0.30<br>SCx : 0.51\n| colspan=\"2\" | Cx : 0.30<br>SCx :  0.59\n|-\n|}\n\n== Alpine A610 ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = Alpine A610\n| image          = 1992 Alpine A610 Turbo 3.0.jpg\n| manufacturer   = [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]]\n| production     = 1991\u20131995\n| class          = [[Sports car]] \n| predecessor    = [[Alpine GTA]]\n| successor      = [[Alpine A110 (2017)]] \n| body_style     = 2+2, 2-door [[coupe]]\n| layout         = [[Longitudinal engine|Longitudinally-mounted]], [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| assembly       = [[Dieppe, Seine-Maritime|Dieppe]], [[France]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/auto/nachrichten/renault-alpine-a610-donnerkeil-aus-dieppe-/6711944.html|title=Renault-Alpine A610: Donnerkeil aus Dieppe|website=www.handelsblatt.com|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n| engine         = {{convert|2975|cc|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[PRV engine|''PRV'']]<ref>http://www.fast-classics.com/cars/renault-alpine-a610-for-sale/</ref> [[turbo]] [[V6 engine|V6]]\n| powerout       = {{convert|250|PS|bhp kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]]\n| transmission   = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]}}\n[[File:Alpine A610..0.jpg|thumb|left|Alpine A610 red]]\n[[File:Alpine A610..7.jpg|thumb|left|Alpine A610 yellow]]\n[[File:Alpine A610 Turbo Magny-Cours.JPG|thumb|left|Alpine A610 Magny-Cours]]\nThe successor to the Alpine GTA, the '''Alpine A610''' was produced by the [[Renault]]-owned [[France|French]] manufacturer [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]] from 1991 to 1995. Due to a limited budget at the beginning of the project, its appearance does not differ much from the GTA, and it looks quite similar to the USA GTA with its pop-up headlights. Nonetheless, it is a completely different car, sharing only the windows with the GTA. The basic concepts of all Alpine cars are there (e.g. the [[rear engine]], and the steel backbone chassis that all Alpines since the A110 have had). The car was solely branded as an '''Alpine''', as linking Alpine and Renault together (first as Alpine-Renault then Renault-Alpine) seemed to detract from the Alpine brand's sporty image. The [[PRV engine]] remained, but it was enlarged to {{convert|2975|cc|L|1|order=flip}},<ref name = officialrenaultpage>{{cite web|url=https://www.renault.de/entdecken-sie-renault/ueber-renault/modellgeschichte.html|title=Modellgeschichte|website=Renault|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> which enabled it to produce {{Convert|250|PS|bhp kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5,750 rpm<ref name = officialrenaultpage/> and {{Convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[Torque#Machine torque|torque]] at 2,900 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/auto/nachrichten/renault-alpine-a610-donnerkeil-aus-dieppe-/6711944.html|title=Renault-Alpine A610: Donnerkeil aus Dieppe|website=www.handelsblatt.com|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> The engine was originally {{convert|2975|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}}, but as with all PRV engines, it was downsized to {{convert|2963|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} in March 1993 to better fit the Swiss taxation system.\n\nThe '''A610 [[Albertville]] 92''' was presented in 1991 for the [[1992 Winter Olympic Games|Olympic Games]]. Two examples, and other Renault cars, were used to drive VIPs, before being sold. They had a specific color (Gardenia White) and interior, but used the standard engine and technical specifications.\n\nThe '''A610 Magny-Cours''' was created for the [[WilliamsF1|Williams]]-[[Renault Sport|Renault]] Formula One victory in the [[French Grand Prix]] at [[Circuit de Nevers Magny-Cours|Magny-Cours]] in [[1991 French Grand Prix|July 1991]]. 31 cars were built, with specific color and interior. They carry a \"Magny-Cours\" legend on the doors and have body-colored rims.\n\nThe A610 did not result in an improvement in sales over the commercially disappointing GTA and the car was discontinued in 1995, despite acclaim from the motoring press, and approval from the British car show [[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]]. The A610 was to be the last car to carry the Alpine name until the 2017 release of the new [[Alpine A110 (2017)|Alpine A110]]. After production of the A610 ended, the Alpine factory in Dieppe produced the [[Renault Spider]]. 818 were built, 67 of which were right-hand-drive. Sales the first two years were acceptable, but from 1993 until production ended in 1995 a mere 80 cars were built.\n\nIn Jeremy Clarkson\u2019s 2007 direct to DVD film \u2018Supercar Showdown\u2019, the production infamously destroyed a particularly rare right-hand-drive example of the A610, by driving it into a concrete K-rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=LWGchdsJaA0|title=A610 on Top Gear 2007|website=www.youtube.com|accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Specifications===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"0\"  cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:91%;\"\n! Model\n|'''A610''' - '''D 503 05'''\n|-\n! [[Engine type]]\n| [[PRV engine|PRV]] 90\u00ba [[V6 engine|V6]] Code: Z7X-744\n|-\n! [[Automobile layout|Position]]\n| [[Longitudinal engine|Longitudinally-mounted]],<br/>[[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout]]\n|-\n! Fuel feed\n| [[Renix#Renault applications|Renix Bendix-Siemens]] [[fuel injection]]\n|-\n! [[Valvetrain]]\n| [[Overhead camshaft#Single overhead camshaft|SOHC]] [[Multi-valve#Four-valve cylinder head|4 valves]] per [[Cylinder (engine)|cylinder]]\n|-\n! [[Bore (engine)|Bore]] X [[Stroke (engine)|Stroke]]\n| {{convert|93x73|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Engine displacement|Displacement]]\n| {{convert|2975|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}}<br/>({{convert|2963|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} since March 1993)\n|-\n! [[Compression ratio]]\n| 7.6:1\n|-\n! Max. [[Power (physics)|power]]\n| {{Convert|250|PS|bhp kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5,750 rpm\n|-\n! Max. [[Torque#Machine torque|torque]]\n| {{convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 2,900 rpm\n|-\n! [[Catalytic converter]]\n| 3 ways [[Oxygen sensor|Lambda-sensor]]\n|-\n! [[Fuel#Chemical|Fuel type]]\n| [[Research Octane Number|RON]] 95 or 98 unleaded [[petrol]]\n|-\n! [[Engine aspiration method|Aspiration]]\n| [[Garrett AiResearch]] T3 [[Turbocharger]] {{Convert|0.76|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Gearbox]]\n| 5 speed [[manual transmission]]\n|-\n! Kilometer start-stop\n| 25 to 26 s\n|-\n! 0 to {{convert|100|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n| 5.9 s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=26070|website=carfolio.com|title=1992 Renault Alpine A610|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> or 5.7 s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1992/224090/alpne_renault_a610_turbo.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1992 Alpine Renault A610 Turbo|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! Max. speed\n| {{convert|265|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Fuel consumption in automobiles|Consumption]] {{convert|90|km/h|0|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|120|km/h|0|abbr=on}}<br>Town\n|\n{{convert|7.3|l/100 km|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|9.2|l/100 km|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|14.7|l/100 km|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Fuel tank]]\n| {{convert|80|L|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Aerodynamic [[Drag coefficient]]\n| Cx : 0.30 - SCx :  0.54\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|Renault Alpine A610/GTA}}\n\n{{Renault}}\n{{Renault vehicles timeline 1945 to 1989}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renault Alpine GTA A610}}\n[[Category:Renault vehicles|Alpine A610 GTA]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1984]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with backbone chassis]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Renault Alpine GTA''' and the succeeding A610<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/|title=Car News: Breaking News, Automotive Trends, and Model Announcements|website=Car and Driver|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> was a sports [[coupe]] [[automobile]] produced by the [[Renault]]-owned [[France|French]] manufacturer [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]] between late 1984 and 1995. It replaced the slow-selling [[Alpine A310]], with which it shared many features including the layout and engine.<ref name=\"Mon813\">{{cite journal | ref=super | journal=Le Moniteur de l'Automobile | page = 13 | title= La renaissance | trans-title = The rebirth | last= Cornaert | first= Jean-Jacques | location=Brussels, Belgium | language=French | volume=36 | number=813 | date=1985-01-24 | publisher=Editions Auto-Magazine }}</ref> The car underwent a substantive redesign in 1991, which is also when the new model name A610 was given.\n\n==First generation==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = Renault Alpine GTA\n| image          = Renault Alpine V6 GT Gen3 D500 1984-1991 frontright 2011-04-10 A.jpg\n| manufacturer   = [[Renault]] [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]]\n| aka            = {{unbulleted list | Renault Alpine V6 GT | Renault Alpine V6 Turbo | Renault GTA (UK) }}\n| production     = November 1984-February 1991\n| class          = [[Sports car]]\n| predecessor    = [[Alpine A310]]\n| body_style     = 2+2, 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout         = [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|RR layout]]\n| successor      = [[Alpine A610]]\n| assembly       = [[Dieppe, Seine-Maritime|Dieppe]], [[France]]\n| engine         = {{unbulleted list | 2.5L (2458&nbsp;cc) ''[[V6 PRV engine|PRV Z7U]]'' [[Turbocharger|turbo]] [[V6 engine|V6]] | 2.9L (2849&nbsp;cc) ''[[V6 PRV engine|PRV Z6W]]'' V6 }}\n| designer       = Yves Legal\n}}\n\nIt was the first car launched by Alpine under Renault ownership (though Alpine had been affiliated with Renault for many years, with its earlier models using many Renault parts). Longer, wider, and taller, it effectively updated the design of its predecessor, the [[Alpine A310]], updating that car's silhouette with modern design features like body-integrated bumpers and a triangular C-pillar with large rear windshield. Like its predecessor, it used the [[V6 PRV engine]] in a rear-engined layout, with extensive use of Polyester plastics and [[Fiberglass|fibreglass]] for the body panels making it lighter and quicker than rivals such as the [[Porsche 944]]. Passenger room increased, making the rear seat more of a useful proposition, while equipment was much more complete and now included items such as power locks.<ref name=\"Mon813b\">[[#super|Cornaert]], p. 14</ref> It was one of the most aerodynamic cars of its time, the naturally aspirated version achieved a record 0.28 drag coefficient in its class.<ref name=\"Mon813b\"/> Due to its bigger tires and need for more cooling intakes, the Turbo's drag coefficient was a bit higher: 0.30 <math>\\scriptstyle C_\\mathrm x\\,</math>. The GTA name, used to denote the entire range of this generation, stands for \"Grand Tourisme Alpine\" but in most markets the car was marketed as the Renault Alpine V6 GT or as the Renault Alpine V6 Turbo.<ref name=Echap>{{cite journal | journal = Echappement | date = April 1985 | number = 198 | ref = PB85 | title = L'usine Alpine: renaissance ou r\u00e9volution? | trans-title = The Alpine works: renaissance or revolution? | last = Barbaza | first = Pierre | page = 88 | publisher = Michael Hommell | location = Paris, France | language = French }}</ref> In Great Britain it was sold simply as the Renault GTA,<ref>{{citation | first = Stuart | last = Bladon | title = Observer's Cars 1987 | publisher = Penguin Books Ltd | date = 1987-05-07 | page = 144 | isbn = 978-0723234593 }}</ref> as Sunbeam (and then [[Simca 1307|Chrysler/Talbot]]) had been using the \"[[Sunbeam Alpine|Alpine]]\" badge since the 1950s.\n\n[[File:1988 Renault GTA Turbo rear (UK).jpg|thumb|left|1988 Renault GTA Turbo (UK), rear view]]\nRather than being moulded in a single piece as for the preceding A310, the new Alpine's body was moulded in a large number of small separate panels.<ref name=Echap/> This required a major overhaul of the Alpine plant, leaving only the sandblasting machinery intact. The car was also considerably more efficient to manufacture, with the time necessary to build a finished car dropping from 130 to 77 hours - which was still a long time, but acceptable for a small-volume specialty car.<ref name=PB2>[[#PB|Barbaza]], p. 89</ref> The PRV engine in the naturally aspirated model was identical to the version used in the [[Renault 25]], a 2849&nbsp;cc unit producing {{Convert|160|PS|hp|0|abbr=on}}. The small power gain compensated for the weight increase, up by {{convert|92|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Also available was the more powerful [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] model, which used a smaller (2.5 liter) displacement.\n\nThe central backbone chassis (with outriggers for side impact protection) was built by Heuliez and then transferred to Dieppe - aside from the body, most of the car was subcontracted to various suppliers.<ref name=PB2/> The drivetrain was mounted on a separate subframe, meaning it can be removed in as little as two hours.<ref name=MK129>{{cite magazine | ref = MK717 | title = Sportlich & g\u00fcnstig? | trans-title = Sporty and cheap? | language = German | page = 129 | date = July 2017 | last = Woytal | first = Bernd | magazine = Motor Klassik | publisher = Motor Presse Stuttgart | location = Stuttgart, Germany | issn = 0177-8862 }}</ref> It was also moved {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} forward (making the rear overhang shorter while nearly all other dimensions increased) compared to the A310, improving somewhat on that car's tailwards weight distribution.<ref name=\"Mon813\"/> The transmission was the same [[Renault 30]]-based unit that the A310 had used, with some minor changes and somewhat longer fourth and fifth gears. Those gears were taller yet for the GT Turbo model.<ref name=\"Mon813b\"/> At the time of introduction, daily production number amounted to ten cars.<ref name=PB3>[[#PB|Barbaza]], p. 90</ref> This soon dropped considerably, as the somewhat less than prestigious Renault had a hard time in the sports car marketplace. The average production for the six full years of production was just above 1000 per annum, or just above three per day - almost identical to the A310 V6's annual production.\n\n===Models===\n[[File:Alpine-p1040134.jpg|thumb|left|Renault Alpine Le Mans (1990-1991)]]\nThe first model introduced was the naturally aspirated V6 GT (D&nbsp;500), which entered production in November 1984, although press photos had been released in September 1984.<ref name=TAM85>{{Cite book | title = Quattroruote: Tutte le Auto del Mondo 1985 | editor = Mastrostefano, Raffaele | publisher = Editoriale Domus S.p.A | ref = TAM85 | year = 1985 | language = Italian | page = 847 | location = Milano | isbn = 88-7212-012-8 }}</ref> The car was first shown at the 1985 Amsterdam Rai, immediately after which it also went on sale.<ref name=MilleM>{{cite web | url = http://alpine.v6.turbo.free.fr/guide/alpine-v6-turbo-mille-miles.php | title = Alpine V6 Turbo Mille Miles | work = Le site des amateurs et passionn\u00e9s des Alpine Renault GTA | last = Liszewski | first = Nicolas | language = French | accessdate = 2014-09-08 }}</ref> In July 1985 the Europa Cup model appeared; this limited edition model was intended for a single-make racing championship and 69 cars were built (54 in 1985 and 15 more in 1987).<ref name=perso>{{cite web | url = http://alpine-gta-europacup.pagesperso-orange.fr/ | title = Alpine GTA, GTA Europa Cup et A610 (de s\u00e9rie - en course) | publisher = Philippe du 77 | trans-title = street - competition | language = French | accessdate = 2014-09-08 }}</ref> In September 1985 the turbo model (D&nbsp;501) followed, which increased the power of the PRV unit to {{Convert|200|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}. Sales of the naturally aspirated model were always sluggish, but with the more powerful turbo, things picked up considerably.<ref name=MK129/> At the 1986 [[British International Motor Show#Birmingham years|Birmingham Show]] the right-hand-drive version was presented and UK sales, as the Renault GTA, commenced.<ref name=MilleM/>\n\nIn early 1987 a catalyzed version appeared, with fifteen less horsepower. This meant that the Turbo could finally be sold in Switzerland, and later in other European countries such as Germany and the Netherlands when they adopted stricter legislation. The catalyzed model had lower gearing in fourth and fifth gears, in order to somewhat mask its power deficit.<ref name=\"AR87\">{{cite book | ref = AR87 | title = Automobil Revue 1987 | editor-last = B\u00fcschi | editor-first = Hans-Ulrich | publisher = Hallwag AG | location = Berne, Switzerland | language = German, French | page = 497 | volume = 82 | date = 5 March 1987 | isbn = 3-444-00458-3 }}</ref> In 1988 anti-lock brakes became available.<ref name=RenAlp>{{cite web | url = http://www.alpine-renault.net/gta.htm | publisher = Avenue de Br\u00e9aut\u00e9 | first = Etienne | last = Lhoste | title = Mod\u00e8les (S\u00e9rie) > GTA V6 GT & GT Turbo | trans-title = Production models | language = French | accessdate = 2014-09-09 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140910195406/http://www.alpine-renault.net/gta.htm | archivedate = 2014-09-10 }}</ref> For the 1989 model year the Mille Miles version appeared. With the non-catalyzed engine, this model heralded a re-focus on the Alpine name. The Renault logo was gone from the car, with an alpine logo up front and a large \"Alpine\" print appearing between the taillights. However, as the name 'Alpine' could not be used in the UK the name Alpine was removed from cars destined for the UK; there was no large print at the back of these cars and a UK specific logo was fitted to the front of the car. The Mille Miles, a limited edition of 100 cars, also featured a special dark red metallic paintjob, polished aluminium wheels, and a large silver-gray triangular stripe with the Alpine \"A\" across the left side of the front.<ref name=RenAlp/>\n\nIn February 1990 the limited edition Le Mans arrived, this car had a more aggressive body kit with polyester wheel arch extensions and a one piece front with smaller headlights. Wheels were 3 piece BBS style produced by ACT, 8x16\" front & 10x17\" rear. Many of these changes were adopted for the succeeding A610. The regular V6 GT and V6 Turbo ended production during 1990, while the Le Mans version continued to be produced until February 1991. 325 of these were built in total. Also in 1990, Renault was forced to install the less powerful catalyzed engine in cars destined for the home market, leading to grumbling amongst Alpine enthusiasts about the loss of power (down to {{Convert|185|PS|kW|abbr=on|disp=or}}) while the [[Renault 25|25 Turbo]] saloon actually gained power when it became catalyzed. In response Danielson SA, a famous French tuner, created an upgraded version of the Le Mans with {{convert|210|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nRenault had planned a federalized version of the Alpine V6 Turbo all along, originally for the 1986 model year, but development proceeded slowly.<ref name=tough>{{cite magazine | magazine = [[Autoweek]] | last = Lovell | first = Bill | pages = 10\u201312 | date = 1984-04-08 | title = Tough Company | issn = 0192-9674 | volume = 35 | number = 14 | publisher = Crain Press Inc. }}</ref> The US model had an emissions cleaned engine with {{Convert|180|hp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}, bigger bumpers, and flip-up headlamps ([http://www.renaultalpine.co.uk/gallery/album.php?album_id=2&sk=t&sd=a&st=0&start=11 photo]).<ref name=tough/> Various crash safety improvements were also carried out, and it was planned to install a softer suspension. In 1987, however, Renault withdrew from the US market. Commentators had also expressed concern about AMC dealers being able to handle such an expensive and complicated car.<ref name=tough/> By then 21 pre-series cars had been finished. 12 of these were sold by Alpine directly to specially selected customers at home.\n\n{{clear_left}}\n\n===Specifications ===\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" cellpadding=\"0\"  cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:91%;\"\n! Model\n|'''V6 GT<br>D500 05'''\n|'''V6 Turbo<br>D501 05'''\n|'''V6 Turbo<br>D50 A (USA)'''\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat<br>D501 05 (Swiss)'''<ref name=\"AR87\"/>\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat<br>D502 05'''\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat<br>\"Le Mans\" D502 05 A'''\n|'''V6 Turbo Cat tuning<br>\"Le Mans\" D502 05 A (Danielson)'''\n|-\n! Engine\n| colspan=\"7\" | [[V6 PRV engine|PRV V6]]\n|-\n! Type\n| colspan=\"7\" | Longitudinal\n|-\n! Cylinders\n| colspan=\"7\" | 6 cylinders\n|-\n! [[Valve]]s\n| colspan=\"7\" | 12 valves\n|-\n! [[Camshaft]]\n| colspan=\"7\" | top\n|-\n! Engine size\n| 2849&nbsp;cc\n| colspan=\"6\" | 2458&nbsp;cc\n|-\n! Compression ratio\n| 9.5 : 1\n| 8.6 :1\n| colspan=\"5\" | 8 : 1\n|-\n! Max power\n| {{Convert|160|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|200|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|182|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5900&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|185|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5500&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|185|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|185|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5750&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|210|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5200&nbsp;rpm\n|-\n! Max [[torque]]\n| {{Convert|221|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 3500&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|285|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2500&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|276|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 4000&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|288|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2250&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|288|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2200&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|288|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2200&nbsp;rpm\n| {{Convert|350|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}} at 2200&nbsp;rpm\n|-\n! [[Catalytic converter]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | No\n| colspan=\"5\" | Yes\n|-\n! Fuel\n| colspan=\"2\" | RON 97\n| colspan=\"5\" | RON 95 or 98 unleaded\n|-\n! [[Carburetor]]\n| [[Carburetor]] SC 34 + DC 35\n| colspan=\"6\" | electronic injection\n|-\n! Air supply\n| atmospheric\n| Turbocharged {{Convert|0.65|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n| Turbocharged {{Convert|0.65|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n| colspan=\"3\" | Turbocharged {{Convert|0.70|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n| Turbocharged {{Convert|1.0|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Kilometer start-stop\n| 28.4 s\n| 26.8 s\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| 27.5 s\n| 26.7 s\n|-\n! 0 to 100&nbsp;km/h\n| 8.0 s\n| 7.0 s\n| -\n| 7.0 s\n| 7.0 s\n| 6.7 s\n| 5.7 s\n|-\n! Max speed\n| {{convert|235|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|250|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| - \n| {{convert|238|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|243|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|240|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|247|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Consumption 90&nbsp;km/h<br>120&nbsp;km/h<br>Town\n| \n7.0 l/100&nbsp;km<br>7.9 l/100&nbsp;km <br>14.7 l/100&nbsp;km\n| \n6.4 l/100&nbsp;km<br>8.1 l/100&nbsp;km<br>12.8 l/100&nbsp;km\n|\n-<br>-<br>-\n| \n-<br>-<br>-\n| \n-<br>-<br>-\n| \n7.1 l/100&nbsp;km<br>9.0 l/100&nbsp;km<br>13.9 l/100&nbsp;km\n| \n8.3 l/100&nbsp;km<br>10.1 l/100&nbsp;km<br>13.7 l/100&nbsp;km\n|-\n! Fuel tank\n| {{convert|72|L|1|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|72|L|1|abbr=on}} + {{convert|1|L|1|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|57|L|1|abbr=on}}\n| colspan=\"4\" | {{convert|72|L|1|abbr=on}} + {{convert|1|L|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Aerodynamic\n| [[Drag coefficient|Cx]] : 0.28<br>SCx : 0.48\n| colspan=\"4\" | Cx : 0.30<br>SCx : 0.51\n| colspan=\"2\" | Cx : 0.30<br>SCx :  0.59\n|-\n|}\n\n== Alpine A610 ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name           = Alpine A610\n| image          = 1992 Alpine A610 Turbo 3.0.jpg\n| manufacturer   = [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]]\n| production     = 1991\u20131995\n| class          = [[Sports car]] \n| predecessor    = [[Alpine GTA]]\n| successor      = [[Alpine A110 (2017)]] \n| body_style     = 2+2, 2-door [[coupe]]\n| layout         = [[Longitudinal engine|Longitudinally-mounted]], [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| assembly       = [[Dieppe, Seine-Maritime|Dieppe]], [[France]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/auto/nachrichten/renault-alpine-a610-donnerkeil-aus-dieppe-/6711944.html|title=Renault-Alpine A610: Donnerkeil aus Dieppe|website=www.handelsblatt.com|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n| engine         = {{convert|2975|cc|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} [[PRV engine|''PRV'']]<ref>http://www.fast-classics.com/cars/renault-alpine-a610-for-sale/</ref> [[turbo]] [[V6 engine|V6]]\n| powerout       = {{convert|250|PS|bhp kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]]\n| transmission   = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]}}\n[[File:Alpine A610..0.jpg|thumb|left|Alpine A610 red]]\n[[File:Alpine A610..7.jpg|thumb|left|Alpine A610 yellow]]\n[[File:Alpine A610 Turbo Magny-Cours.JPG|thumb|left|Alpine A610 Magny-Cours]]\nThe successor to the Alpine GTA, the '''Alpine A610''' was produced by the [[Renault]]-owned [[France|French]] manufacturer [[Alpine (car)|Alpine]] from 1991 to 1995. Due to a limited budget at the beginning of the project, its appearance does not differ much from the GTA, and it looks quite similar to the USA GTA with its pop-up headlights. Nonetheless, it is a completely different car, sharing only the windows with the GTA. The basic concepts of all Alpine cars are there (e.g. the [[rear engine]], and the steel backbone chassis that all Alpines since the A110 have had). The car was solely branded as an '''Alpine''', as linking Alpine and Renault together (first as Alpine-Renault then Renault-Alpine) seemed to detract from the Alpine brand's sporty image. The [[PRV engine]] remained, but it was enlarged to {{convert|2975|cc|L|1|order=flip}},<ref name = officialrenaultpage>{{cite web|url=https://www.renault.de/entdecken-sie-renault/ueber-renault/modellgeschichte.html|title=Modellgeschichte|website=Renault|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> which enabled it to produce {{Convert|250|PS|bhp kW|0|abbr=on}} at 5,750 rpm<ref name = officialrenaultpage/> and {{Convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[Torque#Machine torque|torque]] at 2,900 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/auto/nachrichten/renault-alpine-a610-donnerkeil-aus-dieppe-/6711944.html|title=Renault-Alpine A610: Donnerkeil aus Dieppe|website=www.handelsblatt.com|accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> The engine was originally {{convert|2975|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}}, but as with all PRV engines, it was downsized to {{convert|2963|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} in March 1993 to better fit the Swiss taxation system.\n\nThe '''A610 [[Albertville]] 92''' was presented in 1991 for the [[1992 Winter Olympic Games|Olympic Games]]. Two examples, and other Renault cars, were used to drive VIPs, before being sold. They had a specific color (Gardenia White) and interior, but used the standard engine and technical specifications.\n\nThe '''A610 Magny-Cours''' was created for the [[WilliamsF1|Williams]]-[[Renault Sport|Renault]] Formula One victory in the [[French Grand Prix]] at [[Circuit de Nevers Magny-Cours|Magny-Cours]] in [[1991 French Grand Prix|July 1991]]. 31 cars were built, with specific color and interior. They carry a \"Magny-Cours\" legend on the doors and have body-colored rims.\n\nThe A610 did not result in an improvement in sales over the commercially disappointing GTA and the car was discontinued in 1995, despite acclaim from the motoring press, and approval from the British car show [[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]]. The A610 was to be the last car to carry the Alpine name until the 2017 release of the new [[Alpine A110 (2017)|Alpine A110]]. After production of the A610 ended, the Alpine factory in Dieppe produced the [[Renault Spider]]. 818 were built, 67 of which were right-hand-drive. Sales the first two years were acceptable, but from 1993 until production ended in 1995 a mere 80 cars were built.\n\nIn Jeremy Clarkson\u2019s 2007 direct to DVD film \u2018Supercar Showdown\u2019, the production infamously destroyed a particularly rare right-hand-drive example of the A610, by driving it into a concrete K-rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=LWGchdsJaA0|title=A610 on Top Gear 2007|website=www.youtube.com|accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Specifications===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"0\"  cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:91%;\"\n! Model\n|'''A610''' - '''D 503 05'''\n|-\n! [[Engine type]]\n| [[PRV engine|PRV]] 90\u00ba [[V6 engine|V6]] Code: Z7X-744\n|-\n! [[Automobile layout|Position]]\n| [[Longitudinal engine|Longitudinally-mounted]],<br/>[[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout]]\n|-\n! Fuel feed\n| [[Renix#Renault applications|Renix Bendix-Siemens]] [[fuel injection]]\n|-\n! [[Valvetrain]]\n| [[Overhead camshaft#Single overhead camshaft|SOHC]] [[Multi-valve#Four-valve cylinder head|4 valves]] per [[Cylinder (engine)|cylinder]]\n|-\n! [[Bore (engine)|Bore]] X [[Stroke (engine)|Stroke]]\n| {{convert|93x73|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Engine displacement|Displacement]]\n| {{convert|2975|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}}<br/>({{convert|2963|cc|L CID|1|abbr=on}} since March 1993)\n|-\n! [[Compression ratio]]\n| 7.6:1\n|-\n! Max. [[Power (physics)|power]]\n| {{Convert|250|PS|bhp kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5,750 rpm\n|-\n! Max. [[Torque#Machine torque|torque]]\n| {{convert|350|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} @ 2,900 rpm\n|-\n! [[Catalytic converter]]\n| 3 ways [[Oxygen sensor|Lambda-sensor]]\n|-\n! [[Fuel#Chemical|Fuel type]]\n| [[Research Octane Number|RON]] 95 or 98 unleaded [[petrol]]\n|-\n! [[Engine aspiration method|Aspiration]]\n| [[Garrett AiResearch]] T3 [[Turbocharger]] {{Convert|0.76|bar|psi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Gearbox]]\n| 5 speed [[manual transmission]]\n|-\n! Kilometer start-stop\n| 25 to 26 s\n|-\n! 0 to {{convert|100|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}\n| 5.9 s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=26070|website=carfolio.com|title=1992 Renault Alpine A610|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> or 5.7 s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1992/224090/alpne_renault_a610_turbo.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1992 Alpine Renault A610 Turbo|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! Max. speed\n| {{convert|265|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Fuel consumption in automobiles|Consumption]] {{convert|90|km/h|0|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|120|km/h|0|abbr=on}}<br>Town\n|\n{{convert|7.3|l/100 km|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|9.2|l/100 km|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|14.7|l/100 km|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! [[Fuel tank]]\n| {{convert|80|L|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n! Aerodynamic [[Drag coefficient]]\n| Cx : 0.30 - SCx :  0.54\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|Renault Alpine A610/GTA}}\n\n{{Renault}}\n{{Renault vehicles timeline 1945 to 1989}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Renault Alpine GTA A610}}\n[[Category:Renault vehicles|Alpine A610 GTA]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1984]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with backbone chassis]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Removed redundant category as per WP:Subcat. Parent category not needed when one of its subcategories is already present.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renault_Alpine_GTA/A610"}
{"title_page": "James Lindsay, 24th Earl of Crawford", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Refimprove|date=February 2011}}\n[[File:Haigh Hall - geograph.org.uk - 50440.jpg|thumb|Haigh Hall, built by James Lindsay]]\n'''James Lindsay, 24th Earl of Crawford and 7th Earl of Balcarres''' (24 April 1783 &ndash; 15 December 1869) was an Earl in the Scottish peerage.\n\n==Biography==\nJames Lindsay was born on 24 April 1783 at [[Balcarres House]] in [[Fife]], the son of [[Alexander Lindsay, 23rd Earl of Crawford|Alexander Lindsay, 6th Earl of Balcarres]] and inherited the title of 7th Earl of Balcarres on his father's death in 1825. In 1826 he was created Baron of Wigan in the peerage of Great Britain. In 1843 he claimed the abeyant title of Earl of Crawford and in 1848 the House of Lords allowed the claim and conferred on him the title of 24th Earl of Crawford, and by extension, the title of 23rd Earl of Crawford on his dead father.{{clarify|date=October 2015}}\n\nHe entered the army and attained the rank of major in the [[20th Hussars|20th Light Dragoons]] until he left in 1804. He was returned as Tory MP for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]] from 1820 to 1825.\n\nHe inherited a third share of a company that supplied slaves to the British Army from his father (a former [[Governor of Jamaica]]). After the [[Slavery Abolition Act 1833]] he was paid a large amount of compensation for the loss of slaves. James was able to use his family's wealth, derived in significant part from slavery, to invest in the profitable coal industry.<ref>{{cite web|author=James Lindsay, 7th Earl of Balcarres |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/21571 |title=Summary of Individual &#124; Legacies of British Slave-ownership |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2013-02-28}}</ref>\n\nHe designed [[Haigh Hall]] in [[Haigh, Greater Manchester]], to replace the then existing hall which dated back to Norman times and lived in a cottage in the grounds whilst it was constructed between 1830\u20131849. The family owned Haigh Colliery, [[cannel]] and [[coal mines]], and formed the [[Wigan Coal and Iron Company]] in 1865.\n\nAfter his death on 23 December 1869 he was buried at [[Wigan Parish Church|All Saints' Church, Wigan]], Lancashire, and succeeded by his eldest son, [[Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford]].\n\n==Family==\nOn 21 November 1811 at [[Muncaster]] in Cumbria, he married the Hon. Maria Margaret Frances Pennington, daughter of [[John Pennington, 1st Baron Muncaster]]. They had four sons of whom the eldest was Alexander Lindsay. Alexander's genealogical research had enabled his father to claim the title of Earl of Crawford which had fallen into abeyance.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n* {{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n* [http://www.electricscotland.com/history/nation/balcaress.htm Balcarres Family]\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|author=Lindsay, Lord &#91;[[Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford]]&#93;|title=Report of the Speeches of Counsel, and of the Lord Chancellor and Lord St. Leonards in Moving the Resolution, upon the Claim of James Earl of Crawford and Balcarres to the Original Dukedom of Montrose (created in 1488), as Referred to the House of Lords by Her Most Gracious Majesty the Queen, for Their Advice and Opinion thereupon: Preceded by an Address to Her Majesty, in Humble Remonstrance against the Opinion Reported to Her Majesty; and by an Analysis of the Argument as between the Claimant and the Officers Representing the Crown, with the Opinions of the Committee of Privileges, Point by Point, throughout; and Followed by an Appendix, Containing the Leading Arguments Adduced and Referred to, and the Oral Evidence Delivered, by and on behalf of the Claimant and the Crown, in this Case|location=London|publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]], [[Albemarle Street]]|year=1855|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwhDAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover|oclc=67232132}}.\n*{{citation|last=Barker|first=Nicolas|title=Bibliotheca Lindesiana: The Lives and Collections of Alexander William, 25th Earl of Crawford and 8th Earl of Balcarres, and James Ludovic, 26th Earl of Crawford and 9th Earl of Balcarres|edition=2nd corr.|location=London|publisher=For Presentation to the [[Roxburghe Club]], and published by [[Bernard Quaritch]]|year=1978|oclc=931340384}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-james-lindsay-2 | the Earl of Crawford }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Sir Robert Holt Leigh, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Holt Leigh]]<br />[[Johm Hodson]]\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]]\n | with   = [[James Alexander Hodson]]\n | years  = 1820\u20131825\n | after  = [[James Lindsay (1791-1855)]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Alexander Lindsay, 6th Earl of Balcarres|Alexander Lindsay]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Balcarres]]\n       | years  = 1825&ndash; 1869 }}\n{{s-aft| rows   = 2 | after  = [[Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford|Alexander Lindsay]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Alexander Lindsay, 6th Earl of Balcarres|Alexander Lindsay]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Crawford]]\n       | years  = 1848 &ndash; 1869 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawford, James Lindsay, 24th Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1783 births]]\n[[Category:1869 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Crawford]]\n[[Category:Earls of Balcarres]]\n[[Category:Tory MPs (pre-1834)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1820\u20131826]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Wigan]]\n[[Category:Clan Lindsay|James]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Refimprove|date=February 2011}}\n[[File:Haigh Hall - geograph.org.uk - 50440.jpg|thumb|Haigh Hall, built by James Lindsay]]\n'''James Lindsay, 24th Earl of Crawford and 7th Earl of Balcarres''' (24 April 1783 &ndash; 15 December 1869) was an Earl in the Scottish peerage.\n\n==Biography==\nJames Lindsay was born on 24 April 1783 at [[Balcarres House]] in [[Fife]], the son of [[Alexander Lindsay, 23rd Earl of Crawford|Alexander Lindsay, 6th Earl of Balcarres]] and inherited the title of 7th Earl of Balcarres on his father's death in 1825. In 1826 he was created Baron of Wigan in the peerage of Great Britain. In 1843 he claimed the abeyant title of Earl of Crawford and in 1848 the House of Lords allowed the claim and conferred on him the title of 24th Earl of Crawford, and by extension, the title of 23rd Earl of Crawford on his dead father.{{clarify|date=October 2015}}\n\nHe entered the army and attained the rank of major in the [[20th Hussars|20th Light Dragoons]] until he left in 1804. He was returned as Tory MP for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]] from 1820 to 1825.\n\nHe inherited a third share of a company that supplied slaves to the British Army from his father (a former [[Governor of Jamaica]]). After the [[Slavery Abolition Act 1833]] he was paid a large amount of compensation for the loss of slaves. James was able to use his family's wealth, derived in significant part from slavery, to invest in the profitable coal industry.<ref>{{cite web|author=James Lindsay, 7th Earl of Balcarres |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/21571 |title=Summary of Individual &#124; Legacies of British Slave-ownership |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2013-02-28}}</ref>\n\nHe designed [[Haigh Hall]] in [[Haigh, Greater Manchester]], to replace the then existing hall which dated back to Norman times and lived in a cottage in the grounds whilst it was constructed between 1830-1849. The family owned Haigh Colliery, [[cannel]] and [[coal mines]], and formed the [[Wigan Coal and Iron Company]] in 1865.\n\nAfter his death on 23 December 1869 he was buried at [[Wigan Parish Church|All Saints' Church, Wigan]], Lancashire, and succeeded by his eldest son, [[Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford]].\n\n==Family==\nOn 21 November 1811 at [[Muncaster]] in Cumbria, he married the Hon. Maria Margaret Frances Pennington, daughter of [[John Pennington, 1st Baron Muncaster]]. They had four sons of whom the eldest was Alexander Lindsay. Alexander's genealogical research had enabled his father to claim the title of Earl of Crawford which had fallen into abeyance.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n* {{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n* [http://www.electricscotland.com/history/nation/balcaress.htm Balcarres Family]\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|author=Lindsay, Lord &#91;[[Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford]]&#93;|title=Report of the Speeches of Counsel, and of the Lord Chancellor and Lord St. Leonards in Moving the Resolution, upon the Claim of James Earl of Crawford and Balcarres to the Original Dukedom of Montrose (created in 1488), as Referred to the House of Lords by Her Most Gracious Majesty the Queen, for Their Advice and Opinion thereupon: Preceded by an Address to Her Majesty, in Humble Remonstrance against the Opinion Reported to Her Majesty; and by an Analysis of the Argument as between the Claimant and the Officers Representing the Crown, with the Opinions of the Committee of Privileges, Point by Point, throughout; and Followed by an Appendix, Containing the Leading Arguments Adduced and Referred to, and the Oral Evidence Delivered, by and on behalf of the Claimant and the Crown, in this Case|location=London|publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]], [[Albemarle Street]]|year=1855|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwhDAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover|oclc=67232132}}.\n*{{citation|last=Barker|first=Nicolas|title=Bibliotheca Lindesiana: The Lives and Collections of Alexander William, 25th Earl of Crawford and 8th Earl of Balcarres, and James Ludovic, 26th Earl of Crawford and 9th Earl of Balcarres|edition=2nd corr.|location=London|publisher=For Presentation to the [[Roxburghe Club]], and published by [[Bernard Quaritch]]|year=1978|oclc=931340384}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-james-lindsay-2 | the Earl of Crawford }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Sir Robert Holt Leigh, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Holt Leigh]]<br />[[Johm Hodson]]\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan]]\n | with   = [[James Alexander Hodson]]\n | years  = 1820\u20131825\n | after  = [[James Lindsay (1791-1855)]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Alexander Lindsay, 6th Earl of Balcarres|Alexander Lindsay]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Balcarres]]\n       | years  = 1825&ndash; 1869 }}\n{{s-aft| rows   = 2 | after  = [[Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford|Alexander Lindsay]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Alexander Lindsay, 6th Earl of Balcarres|Alexander Lindsay]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Crawford]]\n       | years  = 1848 &ndash; 1869 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawford, James Lindsay, 24th Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1783 births]]\n[[Category:1869 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Crawford]]\n[[Category:Earls of Balcarres]]\n[[Category:Tory MPs (pre-1834)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1820\u20131826]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Wigan]]\n[[Category:Clan Lindsay|James]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1830-1849 \u2192 1830\u20131849", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Lindsay,_24th_Earl_of_Crawford"}
{"title_page": "McClain (band)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist|<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = McClain\n| image            = McCLAIN band 2011 cropped.jpg\n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = McClain in 2011, from left to right:<br />Sierra McClain, [[China Anne McClain]], and Lauryn McClain\n| origin           = [[Decatur, Georgia]], United States\n| Background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = {{Flatlist|* McClain Sisters\n* 3mcclaingirls}}\n| genre            = {{Flatlist|*  [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| years_active     = 2005\u20132016 (on hiatus)\n| label            = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]] {{small|(2011\u201313)}}\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| current_members  = * [[China Anne McClain]]\n* Sierra McClain\n* Lauryn McClain\n}}\n'''McClain''' (formerly '''McClain Sisters''' and '''3mcclaingirls''') is an American [[girl group]] that was formed in 2005. The group consists of sisters [[China Anne McClain]], Sierra McClain, and Lauryn McClain. They signed with [[Hollywood Records]] in 2011 and released their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\" in 2012. In 2013, the group left the record label. Their last single \"Feelin' Like\" was released in 2016. The group is now on hiatus and the sisters are pursuing their acting careers.\n\n== Early life ==\nSierra Aylina McClain was born on March 16, 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2057826/|title=Sierra Aylina McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, Lauryn Alisa McClain was born on January 9, 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2055160/|title=Lauryn Alisa McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, and China Anne McClain was born on August 25, 1998. All three sisters were born and raised in [[Decatur, Georgia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1942207/|title=China Anne McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/georgia/decatur/decatur-native-becomes-disney-channel-star|title=Decatur Native Becomes Disney Channel Star|date=2011-05-25|website=Decatur-Avondale Estates, GA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The sisters grew up watching [[Disney]] films and musical classics, and come from an artistic and musical family.<ref name=\"filmb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmbug.com/db/346128|title=Sierra, Lauryn & China Anne McClain|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=Filmbug.com}}</ref> Their father, Michael McClain, is a music producer who produced [[Solange Knowles]]' debut album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/michael-mcclain-mn0001186081|title=Michael McClain {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Their mother, Shontell McClain, is a songwriter and former screenwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2718277/|title=Shontell McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The sisters also have a little brother, Gabriel McClain, who was born on April 17, 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2532716/|title=Gabriel McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the sisters became interested in music when they watched their father write and produce songs. Soon after, the girls began to write songs, choreograph and dance. In addition to acting, singing, and dancing, all three sisters can play the guitar, bass, and piano.<ref name=\"lions\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|title=McClain notes on Lionsgate|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=lionsgatepublicity.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206114300/http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|archivedate=February 6, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 2005\u20132011: 3mcclaingirls and ''Daddy's Little Girls'' ===\nIn 2005, the sisters\u2019 father had a friend over who was music executive. The music executive heard the sisters sing and encouraged director [[Rob Hardy]] to audition China for his 2005 feature film ''[[The Gospel (film)|The Gospel]].'' China was cast as the character Alexis and her sisters were in the supporting cast.<ref name=\"dc\">{{cite web |url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |title=Disney Channel Bio \u2013 China Anne McClain |publisher=Disney Channel Medianet |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The sisters then became serious about a musical career and formed the girl group called the 3mcclaingirls.\n\nThey recorded their first song, \"Silly Games\". The song was produced by their father, Michael McClain, and written by their mother, Shontell McClain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1942207/bio|title=China Anne McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2006 China joined the main cast of ''[[Tyler Perry's House of Payne]]'' as Jazmine Payne and Sierra made guest appearances. In 2007 the group starred in the film ''[[Daddy's Little Girls]]'' as the James sisters.<ref name=\"lions\" /> In 2008 the group recorded the song \"Daddy's Girl\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/daddys-girl-mw0001655815|title=Daddy's Girl - 3mcclaingirls! {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> inspired by the movie, and released it exclusively on Myspace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myspace.com/3mcclaingirls|title=Sierra, Lauryn McClain (3mcclaingirls) on Myspace|website=Myspace|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2008 the group began posting videos on Youtube of themselves singing covers of songs and continued making acting appearances in films and on television.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCksYLtnxiIW0UTegpdbseMQ|title=3mcclaingirls|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132013: McClain Sisters, ''A.N.T. Farm'' and Hollywood Records ===\nOn June 14, 2011 the group signed with [[Hollywood Records]].<ref name=\"hollywoodrecords\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|title=MCCLAIN SISTERS SIGN WITH HOLLYWOOD RECORDS|publisher=Black Celeb Kids|date=June 14, 2011|access-date=February 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126042852/http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The sisters originally planned to use the name III as their group name, the number representing the three McClain girls in the group, but that idea was scrapped.<ref name=\":1\" /> They instead changed their group name to the McClain Sisters. That same year China landed her own show on the [[Disney Channel]] called ''[[A.N.T. Farm]]''. On October 11, 2011, the [[A.N.T. Farm (soundtrack)|''A.N.T. Farm'' soundtrack]] was released on which the group had two songs: \"Perfect Mistake\" and \"Electronic Apology\". The group had plans to release their debut album with the record label<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/11/arts/television/tween-stars-wanted-must-be-primed-for-pressure.html|title=Tween Stars Wanted: Must Be Primed for Pressure|date=2011-05-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but never did. In December the group performed their version of the song \"[[Jingle Bell Rock]]\" at the 2011 [[Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Christmas Parade 2011 McClain Sisters - Celebrity Take with Jake|url=https://video.disney.com/watch/christmas-parade-2011-mcclain-sisters-4bb39f0d70be4a8833003b15|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tigerbeat.com/2011/11/exclusive-bop-and-tiger-beats-photo-shoot-with-china/onerepublic-and-china-anne-mcclain-and-the-mcclain-sisters-perform-for-the-2011-disney-parks-christmas-day-parade/|title=OneRepublic and China Anne McClain and The McClain Sisters Perform for The 2011 Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade {{!}} TigerBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2012 they were the opening act in [[Houston]] for [[Big Time Rush (group)|Big Time Rush]] on their [[Better with U Tour]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/article/Big-Time-Rush-show-leaves-little-to-like-3381325.php|title=Big Time Rush show leaves little to like|date=2012-03-05|website=HoustonChronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/houston-livestock-show-and-rodeo-officials-announce-star-studded-entertainer-lineup-ticket-sales-information-136945508.html|title=Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo\u2122 Officials Announce Star-studded Entertainer Lineup, Ticket Sales Information|last=Rodeo|first=Houston Livestock Show &|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2012 they performed a new song called \"[[Rise (McClain Sisters song)|Rise]]\" at the [[Mall of America]]. The song was written by the sisters and produced by their father, Michael McClain, and was the lead promotional single for the [[Disneynature]] film [[Chimpanzee (film)|''Chimpanzee'']]. The song was released on March 23, 2012. The music video premiered on March 25, 2012 during an episode of ''[[Austin & Ally]]''. It was also a featured song for [[Disney's Friends for Change]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mallofamerica.com/upload/event/pdf/ChinaGuidelinesUPDATE.pdf|title=China Anne McClain & the McClain Sisters Performance and Signing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The music video later premiered online on March 26, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uxVeeqqAyf0|title=McClain Sisters - Rise (Official Video from Disneynature's Chimpanzee)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 11, 2012, their single \"[[The Great Divide (McClain Sisters song)|The Great Divide]]\" was released which was featured in the Disney film [[Secret of the Wings|''Secret of the Wings'']] and on the film's soundtrack [[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust|''Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust'']].\n\nOn November 2, 2012, the McClain Sisters premiered their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/go-single/id573043137|title=Music \u2013 Go - iTunes United States|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> Lauryn and Sierra guest starred and performed the song, alongside China, on November 23, 2012 during the episode \"[[List of A.N.T. Farm episodes#ep41|chANTs of a lifetime]]\" for ''[[A.N.T. Farm]].''\n\n=== 2013\u2013present: Leaving Hollywood Records, McClain, and hiatus ===\nIn December of 2013, China announced on Twitter that ''[[A.N.T. Farm]]'' would be ending after its third season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/chinamcclain/status/416460834571694080|title=It was GREAT filming ANT Farm but after 3 seasons it's come to an end. I'm excited about my secret projects and keeping you guys happy!|last=China\u2077|date=2013-12-26|website=@chinamcclain|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Shortly after this announcement, the McClain Sisters parted ways with [[Hollywood Records]]. After leaving the record label the group changed their name from the McClain Sisters to simply McClain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y9ANeuNPocI|title=McClain Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6aCoCtGT5is|title=McClain Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/McClain/|title=mcclain|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The group released an official lyric video for their single \"He Loves Me\" on YouTube on December 14, 2013.<ref>{{Citation|last=mcclainsisters|title=He Loves Me- Lyric Video|date=2013-12-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z21wV7XRaqs|accessdate=2016-06-13}}</ref> The song then became available on iTunes on February 20, 2014. Later that year, McClain released a Christmas song called \"The Holiday Song\".\n\nIn 2015 the group released the song \"Clip My Wings\" which was featured in the film ''The Sparrows: The Nesting'' and on the film's soundtrack ''The Sparrows: Now & Then.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nandarentertainment.com/may-day-film-festival-selects-the-sparrows-nesting-as-an-official-selection/|title=May Day Film Festival selects \u201cTHE SPARROWS: NESTING\u201d as an Official Selection. {{!}} Nandar Group, LLC|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sparrows-Now-Then-Various-artists/dp/B0181WKZ4Y|title=The Sparrows: Now & Then|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm5016989/|title=McClain Sisters|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The last single the sisters released was \"Feelin' Like\" in 2016 and the group now seems to be on hiatus. All three sisters are pursuing their acting careers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n==Personal life==\nThey are [[Christians]] and reside in Los Angeles, California with their family.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of China |url=http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |work=chinaanne.net |accessdate=September 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121125013234/http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |archivedate=November 25, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hollowverse.com/china-anne-mcclain/|title=China Anne McClain\u2019s Religion and Political Views|website=hollowverse.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Disney's Friends for Change#Rise|Rise]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rise-feat.-mcclain-sisters/id509693456|title=Rise \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"He Loves Me\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/he-loves-me-single/id827805733|title=He Loves Me \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Feelin' Like\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/officialmcclain/feelin-like-ode-to-aaliyah|title=Feelin' Like \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=Soundcloud|accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n===Promotional singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Silly Games\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngblackstarz.org/2012/04/03/memory-lane-these-girls-had-no-time-for-silly-games/|title=MEMORY LANE: THESE GIRLS HAD NO TIME FOR \"SILLY GAMES\"|work=Young Black Stars|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref><br />(featuring Tiff Mic)\n| 2005\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Daddy's Girl\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/daddys-girl/id275361079|title=3mcclaingirls! \u2013 Daddy's Girl|work=iTunes|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref>\n| 2008\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust And Pixie Dust#The Great Divide|The Great Divide]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/great-divide-from-secret-wings/id556729644|title=The Great Divide \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2012\n| ''[[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust and Pixie Dust]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Holiday Song\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-holiday-song-single/id952382814|title=The Holiday Song - Single|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Perfect Mistake\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2011\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[A.N.T. Farm (soundtrack)|A.N.T. Farm]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Electronic Apology\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Jingle Bell Rock]]\"\n| 2012\n| ''[[Disney Channel Holiday Playlist]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Sharp As a Razor\"\n| 2013\n| ''[[Shake It Up: I Love Dance|Shake It Up: I <3 Dance]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Clip My Wings\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n| 2015\n| ''The Sparrows: Now & Then''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! cindy=\"sharp\"| Director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Rise (McClain Sisters song)|Rise]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| Mark Albert\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[The Great Divide (McClain Sisters song)|The Great Divide]] \"\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Concert tours==\n;Opening act:\n* 2012: [[Better with U Tour#Opening act|Better with U Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/06/the-mcclain-sisters-take-to-the-stage/|title=THE MCCLAIN SISTERS TAKE TO THE STAGE|work=blackcelebkids.com|date=May 13, 2010|accessdate=May 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308123351/http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/06/the-mcclain-sisters-take-to-the-stage/|archive-date=March 8, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> {{small|([[Big Time Rush (band)|Big Time Rush]])}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mcclainsistersmusic.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical trios]]\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:African-American girl groups]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B musical groups]]\n[[Category:American girl groups]]\n[[Category:Hollywood Records artists]]\n[[Category:American pop girl groups]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American child actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist|<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = McClain\n| image            = McCLAIN band 2011 cropped.jpg\n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = McClain in 2011, from left to right:<br />Sierra McClain, [[China Anne McClain]], and Lauryn McClain\n| origin           = [[Decatur, Georgia]], United States\n| Background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = {{Flatlist|* McClain Sisters\n* 3mcclaingirls}}\n| genre            = {{Flatlist|*  [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| years_active     = 2005\u20132016 (on hiatus)\n| label            = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]] {{small|(2011\u201313)}}\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| current_members  = * [[China Anne McClain]]\n* Sierra McClain\n* Lauryn McClain\n}}\n'''McClain''' (formerly '''McClain Sisters''' and '''3mcclaingirls''') is an American [[girl group]] that was formed in 2005. The group consists of sisters [[China Anne McClain]], Sierra McClain, and Lauryn McClain. They signed with [[Hollywood Records]] in 2011 and released their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\" in 2012. In 2013, the group left the record label. Their last single \"Feelin' Like\" was released in 2016. The group is now on hiatus and the sisters are pursuing their acting careers.\n\n== Early life ==\nSierra Aylina McClain was born on March 16, 1994<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2057826/|title=Sierra Aylina McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, Lauryn Alisa McClain was born on January 9, 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2055160/|title=Lauryn Alisa McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, and China Anne McClain was born on August 25, 1998. All three sisters were born and raised in [[Decatur, Georgia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1942207/|title=China Anne McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/georgia/decatur/decatur-native-becomes-disney-channel-star|title=Decatur Native Becomes Disney Channel Star|date=2011-05-25|website=Decatur-Avondale Estates, GA Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The sisters grew up watching [[Disney]] films and musical classics, and come from an artistic and musical family<ref name=\"filmb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmbug.com/db/346128|title=Sierra, Lauryn & China Anne McClain|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=Filmbug.com}}</ref> Their father, Michael McClain, is a music producer who produced [[Solange Knowles]]' debut album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/michael-mcclain-mn0001186081|title=Michael McClain {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Their mother, Shontell McClain, is a songwriter and former screenwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2718277/|title=Shontell McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The sisters also have a little brother, Gabriel McClain, who was born on April 17, 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2532716/|title=Gabriel McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the sisters became interested in music when they watched their father write and produce songs. Soon after, the girls began to write songs, choreograph and dance. In addition to acting, singing, and dancing, all three sisters can play the guitar, bass, and piano.<ref name=\"lions\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|title=McClain notes on Lionsgate|date=March 22, 2012|publisher=lionsgatepublicity.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206114300/http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/daddyslittlegirls/docs/pro_notes.doc|archivedate=February 6, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 2005\u20132011: 3mcclaingirls and ''Daddy's Little Girls'' ===\nIn 2005, the sisters\u2019 father had a friend over who was music executive. The music executive heard the sisters sing and encouraged director [[Rob Hardy]] to audition China for his 2005 feature film ''[[The Gospel (film)|The Gospel]].'' China was cast as the character Alexis and her sisters were in the supporting cast.<ref name=\"dc\">{{cite web |url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |title=Disney Channel Bio \u2013 China Anne McClain |publisher=Disney Channel Medianet |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/63XM5Q2Ie?url=http://disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900056&type=mcclain |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The sisters then became serious about a musical career and formed the girl group called the 3mcclaingirls.\n\nThey recorded their first song, \"Silly Games\". The song was produced by their father, Michael McClain, and written by their mother, Shontell McClain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1942207/bio|title=China Anne McClain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2006 China joined the main cast of ''[[Tyler Perry's House of Payne]]'' as Jazmine Payne and Sierra made guest appearances. In 2007 the group starred in the film ''[[Daddy's Little Girls]]'' as the James sisters.<ref name=\"lions\" /> In 2008 the group recorded the song \"Daddy's Girl\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/daddys-girl-mw0001655815|title=Daddy's Girl - 3mcclaingirls! {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> inspired by the movie, and released it exclusively on Myspace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myspace.com/3mcclaingirls|title=Sierra, Lauryn McClain (3mcclaingirls) on Myspace|website=Myspace|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> In 2008 the group began posting videos on Youtube of themselves singing covers of songs and continued making acting appearances in films and on television.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCksYLtnxiIW0UTegpdbseMQ|title=3mcclaingirls|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132013: McClain Sisters, ''A.N.T. Farm'' and Hollywood Records ===\nOn June 14, 2011 the group signed with [[Hollywood Records]].<ref name=\"hollywoodrecords\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|title=MCCLAIN SISTERS SIGN WITH HOLLYWOOD RECORDS|publisher=Black Celeb Kids|date=June 14, 2011|access-date=February 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126042852/http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/13/mcclain-sisters-sign-with-hollywood-records/|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The sisters originally planned to use the name III as their group name, the number representing the three McClain girls in the group, but that idea was scrapped.<ref name=\":1\" /> They instead changed their group name to the McClain Sisters. That same year China landed her own show on the [[Disney Channel]] called ''[[A.N.T. Farm]]''. On October 11, 2011, the [[A.N.T. Farm (soundtrack)|''A.N.T. Farm'' soundtrack]] was released on which the group had two songs: \"Perfect Mistake\" and \"Electronic Apology\". The group had plans to release their debut album with the record label<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Brooks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/11/arts/television/tween-stars-wanted-must-be-primed-for-pressure.html|title=Tween Stars Wanted: Must Be Primed for Pressure|date=2011-05-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but never did. In December the group performed their version of the song \"[[Jingle Bell Rock]]\" at the 2011 [[Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Christmas Parade 2011 McClain Sisters - Celebrity Take with Jake|url=https://video.disney.com/watch/christmas-parade-2011-mcclain-sisters-4bb39f0d70be4a8833003b15|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tigerbeat.com/2011/11/exclusive-bop-and-tiger-beats-photo-shoot-with-china/onerepublic-and-china-anne-mcclain-and-the-mcclain-sisters-perform-for-the-2011-disney-parks-christmas-day-parade/|title=OneRepublic and China Anne McClain and The McClain Sisters Perform for The 2011 Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade {{!}} TigerBeat|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2012 they were the opening act in [[Houston]] for [[Big Time Rush (group)|Big Time Rush]] on their [[Better with U Tour]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/article/Big-Time-Rush-show-leaves-little-to-like-3381325.php|title=Big Time Rush show leaves little to like|date=2012-03-05|website=HoustonChronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/houston-livestock-show-and-rodeo-officials-announce-star-studded-entertainer-lineup-ticket-sales-information-136945508.html|title=Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo\u2122 Officials Announce Star-studded Entertainer Lineup, Ticket Sales Information|last=Rodeo|first=Houston Livestock Show &|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2012 they performed a new song called \"[[Rise (McClain Sisters song)|Rise]]\" at the [[Mall of America]]. The song was written by the sisters and produced by their father, Michael McClain, and was the lead promotional single for the [[Disneynature]] film [[Chimpanzee (film)|''Chimpanzee'']]. The song was released on March 23, 2012. The music video premiered on March 25, 2012 during an episode of ''[[Austin & Ally]]''. It was also a featured song for [[Disney's Friends for Change]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mallofamerica.com/upload/event/pdf/ChinaGuidelinesUPDATE.pdf|title=China Anne McClain & the McClain Sisters Performance and Signing|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The music video later premiered online on March 26, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uxVeeqqAyf0|title=McClain Sisters - Rise (Official Video from Disneynature's Chimpanzee)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn September 11, 2012, their single \"[[The Great Divide (McClain Sisters song)|The Great Divide]]\" was released which was featured in the Disney film [[Secret of the Wings|''Secret of the Wings'']] and on the film's soundtrack [[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust|''Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust'']].\n\nOn November 2, 2012, the McClain Sisters premiered their debut single \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/go-single/id573043137|title=Music \u2013 Go - iTunes United States|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> Lauryn and Sierra guest starred and performed the song, alongside China, on November 23, 2012 during the episode \"[[List of A.N.T. Farm episodes#ep41|chANTs of a lifetime]]\" for ''[[A.N.T. Farm]].''\n\n=== 2013\u2013present: Leaving Hollywood Records, McClain, and hiatus ===\nIn December of 2013, China announced on Twitter that ''[[A.N.T. Farm]]'' would be ending after its third season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/chinamcclain/status/416460834571694080|title=It was GREAT filming ANT Farm but after 3 seasons it's come to an end. I'm excited about my secret projects and keeping you guys happy!|last=China\u2077|date=2013-12-26|website=@chinamcclain|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> Shortly after this announcement, the McClain Sisters parted ways with [[Hollywood Records]]. After leaving the record label the group changed their name from the McClain Sisters to simply McClain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y9ANeuNPocI|title=McClain Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6aCoCtGT5is|title=McClain Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/McClain/|title=mcclain|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The group released an official lyric video for their single \"He Loves Me\" on YouTube on December 14, 2013.<ref>{{Citation|last=mcclainsisters|title=He Loves Me- Lyric Video|date=2013-12-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z21wV7XRaqs|accessdate=2016-06-13}}</ref> The song then became available on iTunes on February 20, 2014. Later that year, McClain released a Christmas song called \"The Holiday Song\".\n\nIn 2015 the group released the song \"Clip My Wings\" which was featured in the film ''The Sparrows: The Nesting'' and on the film's soundtrack ''The Sparrows: Now & Then.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nandarentertainment.com/may-day-film-festival-selects-the-sparrows-nesting-as-an-official-selection/|title=May Day Film Festival selects \u201cTHE SPARROWS: NESTING\u201d as an Official Selection. {{!}} Nandar Group, LLC|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sparrows-Now-Then-Various-artists/dp/B0181WKZ4Y|title=The Sparrows: Now & Then|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm5016989/|title=McClain Sisters|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The last single the sisters released was \"Feelin' Like\" in 2016 and the group now seems to be on hiatus. All three sisters are pursuing their acting careers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n==Personal life==\nThey are [[Christians]] and reside in Los Angeles, California with their family.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of China |url=http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |work=chinaanne.net |accessdate=September 26, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121125013234/http://chinaanne.net/chinaanne/biography/ |archivedate=November 25, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hollowverse.com/china-anne-mcclain/|title=China Anne McClain\u2019s Religion and Political Views|website=hollowverse.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Disney's Friends for Change#Rise|Rise]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rise-feat.-mcclain-sisters/id509693456|title=Rise \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Go (McClain Sisters song)|Go]]\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"He Loves Me\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/he-loves-me-single/id827805733|title=He Loves Me \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Feelin' Like\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/officialmcclain/feelin-like-ode-to-aaliyah|title=Feelin' Like \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=Soundcloud|accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 2016\n|-\n|}\n\n===Promotional singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Silly Games\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngblackstarz.org/2012/04/03/memory-lane-these-girls-had-no-time-for-silly-games/|title=MEMORY LANE: THESE GIRLS HAD NO TIME FOR \"SILLY GAMES\"|work=Young Black Stars|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref><br />(featuring Tiff Mic)\n| 2005\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Daddy's Girl\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/daddys-girl/id275361079|title=3mcclaingirls! \u2013 Daddy's Girl|work=iTunes|date= |accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref>\n| 2008\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust And Pixie Dust#The Great Divide|The Great Divide]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/great-divide-from-secret-wings/id556729644|title=The Great Divide \u2013 Single by McClain|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2012\n| ''[[Disney Fairies: Faith, Trust and Pixie Dust]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Holiday Song\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-holiday-song-single/id952382814|title=The Holiday Song - Single|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Other appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Perfect Mistake\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2011\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[A.N.T. Farm (soundtrack)|A.N.T. Farm]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Electronic Apology\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Jingle Bell Rock]]\"\n| 2012\n| ''[[Disney Channel Holiday Playlist]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Sharp As a Razor\"\n| 2013\n| ''[[Shake It Up: I Love Dance|Shake It Up: I <3 Dance]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Clip My Wings\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n| 2015\n| ''The Sparrows: Now & Then''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! cindy=\"sharp\"| Director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Rise (McClain Sisters song)|Rise]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| Mark Albert\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[The Great Divide (McClain Sisters song)|The Great Divide]] \"\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Concert tours==\n;Opening act:\n* 2012: [[Better with U Tour#Opening act|Better with U Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/06/the-mcclain-sisters-take-to-the-stage/|title=THE MCCLAIN SISTERS TAKE TO THE STAGE|work=blackcelebkids.com|date=May 13, 2010|accessdate=May 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308123351/http://www.blackcelebkids.com/2012/03/06/the-mcclain-sisters-take-to-the-stage/|archive-date=March 8, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> {{small|([[Big Time Rush (band)|Big Time Rush]])}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mcclainsistersmusic.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical trios]